= Outline
<sec:outline>

#set heading(numbering: "1.1")

*@sec:intro* gives a brief introduction to the new field of materials informatics and the promise it holds by combining advances in machine learning with the growing wealth of materials data in open experimental and first-principles databases.
We highlight some challenges holding back progress that motivate the projects presented in later chapters.

*@sec:global-methods* provides a brief overview of core concepts in density functional theory and machine learning, which underpin all work presented in this thesis.

The actual research starts in *@sec:mbd* which explores the utility of machine learning (ML) models for materials discovery.
At the start of my Ph.D., the ability of ML to accelerate the search for new stable crystals remained questionable @bartel_critical_2020.
We sought to address open questions around measuring discovery acceleration factors enabled by ML guidance in the context of a realistic high-throughput materials discovery effort.
This work resulted in *#mbd*, a benchmark task designed to resemble a real-world materials discovery campaign, published in
#pad(x: 2em, y: 3pt)[
  #cite(<riebesell_matbench_2023>, form: "full")
  [Currently under review at Nature Machine Intelligence]
]
Using Materials Project @jain_commentary_2013 as training data and the Wang-Botti-Marques (WBM) dataset @wang_predicting_2021 as an out-of-distribution test set, we compared a variety of ML models to predict the thermodynamic stability of inorganic crystals from unrelaxed structures.

*@sec:diel* presents work aimed at demonstrating the real-world benefits of ML-guided materials discovery in the context of a challenging multi-objective search for novel dielectrics.
This project was published in
#pad(x: 2em, y: 3pt)[
  #cite(<riebesell_pushing_2024>, form: "full")
  [Invited submission to Digital Discovery]
]
and culminated in the successful de-novo synthesis of #CTTO and #BZO, showcasing the real-world viability of ML-guided discovery efforts, especially in a multi-objective optimization setting with a concave Pareto front.

The training of #mace-mp in @sec:mbd directly led to *@sec:mace-mp* which presents an extensive analysis of #mace-mp as a foundation model for inorganic materials published in
#pad(x: 2em, y: 3pt)[
  #cite(<riebesell_foundation_2023>, form: "full")
  [Currently under review at Nature]
]
Although trained purely on bulk crystals, #mace-mp is surprisingly capable of accurately simulating the physics of highly diverse chemistries as demonstrated in over 35 test cases.

Finally, *@sec:summary* summarizes results, and *@sec:outlook* explores directions for future work.

