= Introduction
<sec:intro>

== Importance of Materials Science for Technology
<sec:intro-materials-science>

Eras of human development are named for the materials we knew how to leverage at the time into tools and increasingly complex technology, reflecting the close link between our ability to manipulate new classes of materials and the progress of civilization.
The rough chronology goes _stone_ → _bronze_ → _iron_ → _steam_ → _nuclear_ → _silicon_.

Despite our growing ability to control matter on the atomic scale, synthesizing and characterizing new materials remains laborious, expensive and failure-prone.
Designing atomic configurations with desired properties that enable new technologies and then devising working recipes for synthesizing them requires decades of work in the best case.
More often, such efforts encounter unforeseen roadblocks and remain outside our reach entirely.
Thus, prioritizing our efforts towards candidate materials of greatest promise for critical applications is paramount.
However, conserving time and resources requires the ability to computationally predict how specific atomic arrangements attain stability and give rise to target properties.
Over recent decades, computational materials science has made great strides in this direction.
Functional materials design is an inherently interdisciplinary subject at the intersection of physics, chemistry, engineering, and computer science which has become a driving force behind innovations in every sector of modern civilization, from electronics and energy to medicine and transportation.
Prominent examples include:

- Decades of research into *semiconductors* led to incredible transistor miniaturization and exponential gains in computing power.
- A dramatic drop in price per watt even outpacing optimistic projections has allowed *solar cells* to undercut many historical price projections to become one of the cheapest means of electricity generation @creutzig_underestimated_2017 @kavlak_evaluating_2018 @haegel_terawattscale_2019 @irena_renewable_2023.
  Energy used in cell production has similarly fallen with concomitant reductions in time to energy and cost amortization, making solar the most scalable and perhaps cleanest energy source going forward.
- *Li-ion batteries* store energy in a safe, rechargeable, portable, energy-dense medium, enabling ubiquitous modern technologies like mobile computing and electric vehicles.

To accelerate such developments, the vastness of materials space requires faster and more efficient discovery methods.
The complexity of the underlying physics makes it difficult, if not impossible, for a single tool to accurately model all relevant processes while remaining computationally tractable.
Many problems cannot be solved with _any_ existing tool, inviting further method development to enable systematic chemical design across a wider range of materials applications.

=== Need for New Tools to Navigate Materials Space
<sec:intro-materials-space>

Multi-decade delays between discovery and deployment into functional applications are common in materials science.
A large part of the intervening time is spent by human experts iterating on synthesis recipes and optimizing process conditions to produce the desired material in sufficient quantity and purity at acceptable energy, time and precursor cost.

Traditional materials discovery and design have proceeded iteratively, often guided by heuristic design rules and accumulated human expert knowledge confined to narrow material subspaces.
This reduces time and resource expenditure, helps de-risk the research and allows navigating local materials space with some degree of intent as opposed to pure random walk.
At the same time, it biases efforts towards minor variations of known materials, thereby limiting discovery to close relatives and curtailing far-flung exploration.

=== Autonomous Labs and High-Throughput Synthesis
<sec:intro-autonomous-labs>

While iterative research improves over a purely Edisonian trial-and-error approach, urgency around global warming and the need for cheaper mass-producible sustainable technology demands we accelerate all aspects of the multi-stage new-chemistry-to-device pipeline.
The immense scale of materials space and the time-consuming nature of human-driven experimentation mean comprehensive experimental exploration will remain permanently infeasible.
Thus, a strong focus should be placed on aggressively pursuing lab automation @burger_mobile_2020 @shuang_highthroughput_2019 @szymanski_autonomous_2023, combinatorial synthesis @briceno_class_1995 @ding_solidification_2012 @green_fulfilling_2017 @ludwig_discovery_2019, and rational synthesis route efforts @aykol_rational_2021 @coley_machine_2018 @mcdermott_assessing_2023 @aykol_predicting_2023.

While no fully autonomous inorganic chemistry lab exists today and the path to such a future is long and fraught with challenges, the combined expertise and ingenuity of experimental chemists, roboticists, software engineers and computational materials scientists can be brought to bear on this problem to achieve a step-change reduction in the time and cost of future experiments.
Fully self-driving labs running human-out-of-the-loop exploration with integrated actively learning simulations and synthesis planning will likely prove the most scalable solution in the long run, thus promising to alleviate the growing bottleneck of validating even a fraction of computational property predictions from ever faster and more accurate simulation methods.
However, the reality of the challenge is that even automated labs cannot possibly scale to the full space of possible materials spanned by arbitrary combinations of the 98 naturally occurring elements and the sheer infinite ways of arranging atoms in 3D space.
To elucidate the scale of the challenge, as of April 2024 the Inorganic Crystal Structure Database (#link("https://icsd.products.fiz-karlsruhe.de/en/nachricht/icsd-now-contains-299045-crystal-structures")[ICSD]) @belsky_new_2002 @hellenbrandt_inorganic_2004 holds #si1(299045) @icsd_size_2024 experimentally determined structures.
Davies et al. @davies_computational_2016 estimated that taking into account stoichiometric and polymorphic degrees of freedom
in the #si1(3612280) possible element combinations of the 98 naturally occurring elements up to quaternary order @walsh_quest_2015 expands the search space to $10^10$ distinct and plausible materials that comply with valency and charge balancing rules.
Thus, the extensive coverage of known materials in ICSD represents just 0.003% of the available design space up to quaternary order.
Such a vast space is impossible to fully explore with first-principles simulation, let alone high-throughput experiments.
Hence there is a persistent need for highly scalable computational tools to guide and prioritize experimental efforts.

While the slow pace of synthesis and characterization is perhaps the most pressing present bottleneck impeding progress in materials science today, it cannot be tackled by individual research groups but instead requires major governmental research initiatives and large industry investments.
This thesis will not delve deeper into the experimental side of the problem and instead focus on the problem of optimally directing what experimental throughput we have towards the highest-reward candidate materials.

== Accelerating Discovery through Virtual Screening
<sec:intro-virtual-screening>

Virtual screening efforts for inorganic materials have relied primarily on ab-initio calculations, especially density functional theory (DFT).
DFT has been the workhorse of computational materials science for several decades and has led to the discovery of numerous novel functional materials @ceder_identification_1998 @zhou_high_2015 @jain_computational_2016 @yan_solar_2017 @newhouse_discovery_2017.

A crucial concept for making computational stability prediction is the convex hull of stability illustrated in @fig:convex-hull.
The convex hull, or just hull, is spanned by the lowest energy surface in composition space for a given chemical system (all possible ratios for a given set of elements).
Materials whose energy lies on this hull are stable against decomposition into other phases.
Materials above the hull are metastable or unstable depending on the height of stabilizing kinetic energy barriers.
Larger hull distances correlate strongly with greater instability.
Whenever a new polymorph with lower energy than all previously known phases made from the same set of elements is discovered, it lowers the convex hull in that chemical system.
In a well-studied chemical system, new low-energy discoveries are rare.
However, in unexplored chemical spaces, even high-energy structures may initially be on the known hull until true ground-state structures are found.
Only thorough exploration can increase confidence that the known hull approximates the true hull and that phases predicted to be on the hull are truly stable.

#figure(
  image("figs/intro/convex-hull-of-stability.svg", width: 90%),
