  ],
)<fig:convex-hull>

However, the current silicon age (a.k.a. information age) has brought the momentous development that existing knowledge in the form of structured, computationally-generated data significantly boosts our ability to further advance our understanding of materials on the atomic scale, creating the possibility for a positive feedback loop of accelerating progress.
A new field of materials informatics has emerged to put this flywheel into motion by developing automated workflows that perform intricate multi-step simulations to quickly predict relevant material properties in large quantities and algorithms that can leverage our growing databases generated by such workflows into statistical models with unprecedented cost-accuracy tradeoffs.
Such models can in turn power said workflows at an even lower cost albeit with a significant but shrinking reduction in reliability and extrapolability.
Physically-agnostic data-driven models can thus serve a vital function in aiding the systematic exploration of much larger regions of unknown chemical space.
They may become a similar workhorse for materials simulation as DFT over the next decade.

