As the number of known materials and their properties grows it has become impossible for any one human to assimilate and formulate hypotheses connecting all relevant information.
The severe limits of human memory mean efforts to standardize and digitize our collective knowledge are essential, both for managing this complexity and to enable the development of algorithmic tools that can fully leverage our compounding data.
Preeminent experimental databases include the ICSD @belsky_new_2002 @hellenbrandt_inorganic_2004 and the Crystallography Open Database (COD) @grazulis_crystallography_2009 from which some of the ab-initio databases in @tab:mat-db-sizes were seeded.
As the amount of existing data informing new research grows, it also becomes increasingly crucial to ensure that data is trustworthy, has clear provenance and is disseminated in a standardized, machine-readable format.
Databases like
#for (idx, (db_name, url, ref)) in (
  ("Materials Project (MP)", "https://materialsproject.org", <jain_commentary_2013>),
  ("Open Quantum Materials Database (OQMD)", "http://oqmd.org", <saal_materials_2013>),
  ("Cambridge Structural Database (CSD)", "https://ccdc.cam.ac.uk", <groom_cambridge_2016>),
  ("Materials Cloud", "https://materialscloud.org", <talirz_materials_2020>),
  ("NOvel MAterials Discovery (NOMAD)", "https://nomad-lab.eu", <draxl_nomad_2018>),
).enumerate() {
  [#if idx > 0 {
      ", "
    } #link(url, db_name) #cite(ref)]
}
have been instrumental in pushing in this direction for over a decade as can be seen in @fig:mp-growth by example of MP's roughly linear data (@fig:mp-data-growth) and exponential user growth (@fig:mp-user-growth) since its inception in 2011.

However, the proliferation of databases also brings challenges.
There is now an urgent need for standardization and interoperability between databases to ensure data can be easily shared, compared and combined across different platforms.
If the many new rows in @tab:mat-db-sizes since 2020 are any indication, this need is only going to increase in importance as the number of datasets appears to grow super linearly.
The FAIR principles @wilkinson_fair_2016 provide a framework for Findable, Accessible, Interoperable and Reusable data.
While each database aids findability and accessibility (FA), the siloed nature of databases and the lack of common data formats and application programming interfaces (APIs) hinder interoperability and reusability (IR).

The OPTIMADE consortium @evans_developments_2024 champions consolidation by providing a standardized API specification for any materials database to implement.
OPTIMADE enables uniform client access and data integration across providers, amplifying the utility of the existing conglomerate of databases beyond the sum of its parts and fostering federated interoperability that frees the end user from needing to know the wildly incompatible API details from each data provider.
As the volume and diversity of materials data grow rapidly (@tab:mat-db-sizes), OPTIMADE's vendor-neutral integration is uniquely positioned to uphold the IR in FAIR materials data, allowing stakeholders to harness more of our collective materials knowledge at constant user effort.

=== Limitations of DFT
<sec:intro-dft-limitations>

The cubic scaling of DFT's computational cost with system size severely limits the length and time scales that can be simulated, even on modern supercomputers.
It remains challenging to study complex dynamical processes such as catalytic reactions, phase transitions, and ion transport, which often involve thousands of atoms over nanoseconds to microseconds.
Furthermore, the accuracy of semi-local DFT is limited by its simple form of the approximate exchange-correlation functional.
More accurate hybrid functionals exist but come at such high computational cost as to prohibit their use in high-throughput searches.

While DFT remains indispensable for high-fidelity calculations and is sufficiently cheap to generate reference data for small systems, there is a growing need for faster and more scalable methods to navigate the vast chemical space in search of promising materials.
ML has emerged as a powerful complementary approach that can leverage the wealth of DFT data to build faster methods that scale to larger systems and longer times yet approach DFT's accuracy for in-domain predictions.

=== Emergence of ML as a Complementary Tool
<sec:intro-ml-emergence>

The rapid progress of ML for materials in recent years has led to property predictors that are sufficiently accurate and reliable to act as useful early-stage filters in many virtual screening tasks such as:

#pad(x: 1em)[#grid(
    columns: 2,
    rows: 2,
    gutter: 1em,
    [- molecular electronic properties @faber_prediction_2017],
    [- direct property prediction @dunn_benchmarking_2020 @choudhary_large_2023],

    [- IS2RE#footnote[IS2RE = Initial Structure to Relaxed Energy.
    Terminology introduced by @chanussot_open_2021] stability @riebesell_matbench_2023 @chanussot_open_2021 @merchant_scaling_2023 @jang_structurebased_2020 @mok_directionbased_2022],
    [- driving diverse simulations @riebesell_foundation_2023 @takamoto_teanet_2022 @takamoto_towards_2022 @deng_chgnet_2023 @chen_universal_2022],
  )]
Materials simulations historically driven by physics-based models (either semi-empirical or fully ab-initio) are increasingly making use of purely data-driven (physics-agnostic) models.
Hybrid workflows that combine the two (where ML often serves as a low-cost, lower-fidelity filter) are also quickly gaining traction @ganose_atomate2_2024 @kavanagh_doped_2024.
Geometry optimization and molecular dynamics (MD) in particular benefit immensely from ML force fields that predict energies and forces at a fraction of the cost of DFT by circumventing the need to update atom positions via Hellmann-Feynman forces.
The Hellmann-Feynman theorem @feynman_forces_1939 @guettinger_verhalten_1932 requires solving the electronic Schrödinger equation anew at each step in the trajectory which constitutes a large computational overhead if the sole goal is to update ion positions.
Pre-relaxing with ML force fields has been shown to significantly reduce the number of ionic steps needed to reach the DFT ground state.
// TODO at citations for Joe Montoyas TRI paper or others showing this
DFT calculations can then be appended at the end to reach the true DFT ground state or compute electronic structure where necessary e.g. to obtain band gaps, conductivity, optical properties, Born charges to estimate long-range interactions @zhu_highthroughput_2024 and resulting non-analytical corrections (NAC) to the dynamical matrix @pick_microscopic_1970, etc.

Significant progress was made recently in applying inverse design methods to inorganic crystals @fu_mofdiff_2023 @jiao_crystal_2024 @zeni_mattergen_2023, enabled by fruitful cross-pollination between the pure ML and cheminformatics communities.
The idea is to avoid the arduous task of checking every one of the $ord(10)$ possible materials with individual forward calculations and instead 'jump' straight to the proverbial needle in the haystack by generating crystal structures conditioned on desired properties.
Conditional sampling takes place in a generative model's latent space.
A separate surrogate model for the functional property of interest is constructed that operates in the latent space and identifies embeddings corresponding to structures with a high likelihood of exhibiting the desired functionality @gomez-bombarelli_automatic_2018.
Samples corresponding to promising embedding vectors are then decoded into crystal structures by the generative model.
Such methods were largely pioneered by the organic materials community, where chemical diversity is lower (usually focussed on C, H, N, O, S, P and a varying handful of heavy elements), symmetry constraints are simpler, thermodynamic stability concerns play a smaller role and industry interest and funding is higher.
However, equivalent methods for inorganic materials have emerged that efficiently handle the increased complexity of more variable chemistries and more stringent symmetry constraints imposed by the periodicity of bulk crystals @xie_crystal_2022 @zeni_mattergen_2023.
Generative models for inverse design may be on the cusp of becoming trusted tools in the wider materials community.
However, synthesizing and measuring a generated material experimentally that satisfies the initial target properties has yet to be demonstrated to prove viability.

== Machine Learning for Materials Simulation
<sec:intro-ml>

=== Molecular Dynamics
<sec:intro-md>

MD simulations are an essential tool for gaining atomic-scale insights into many-body interactions over time.
While DFT provides a computationally tractable method for approximately solving the electronic Schrödinger equation, its time-independent formulation only yields the potential energy surface (PES) for a given set of fixed atomic positions at zero temperature.
To gain insights into dynamical processes such as catalytic reactions on surfaces or ion migration through an electrolyte requires atomic simulations over time at non-zero temperature.
MD provides that by time-integrating Newton's equations of motion:

$
  vector(F)
  = -vector(nabla) V(vector(r))
  = m #h(1pt) vector(a)
  = m #h(1pt) dot.double(vector(r)),
$<eqn:newton>

for a potential energy surface $V(vector(r))$ with resulting forces $vector(F)$ from its negative gradient $-vector(nabla) V(vector(r))$.

However, the short femtosecond timesteps needed to accurately simulate chemical reactions that occur over nano-- or even microseconds require millions to billions of integration steps, each one having to compute the forces acting on all particles.

=== Classical Force Fields and Ab-Initio MD
<sec:intro-ff-aimd>

Classical force fields can efficiently simulate up to millions of atoms and nanosecond timescales.
However, their simplified functional forms limit accuracy and transferability, especially for complex reactions with changing chemical environments as encountered e.g. in catalysis, phase transitions, ion transport, and solid-electrolyte interphase formation.
Conversely, quantum-mechanical methods like DFT-driven ab-initio MD (AIMD) provide high accuracy but are limited to hundreds or a few thousand atoms and sub-nanosecond timescales due to the cubic scaling of compute cost with system size.

=== Machine Learning Interatomic Potentials
<sec:intro-mlip>

MLIPs, also known as ML force fields, have emerged as a promising third paradigm on a new previously unreachable point of the cost-accuracy Pareto front.
They are statistical, physically agnostic models that learn energies and forces from reference data, often generated in large quantities with DFT.
Many have the appealing property of scaling _linearly_ with system size, enabling simulations of millions of atoms over nanosecond to microsecond timescales on current supercomputers.
However, until recently, MLIPs have been severely limited in transferability, often fitted to only single- or few-element chemical systems due to insufficient training data and/or scaling constraints in the model architecture @wang_exact_2019.

The latest generation of high-body-order message-passing MLIPs @batzner_equivariant_2022 @batatia_mace_2023 @deng_chgnet_2023 @chen_universal_2022, have demonstrated a step-change in the ability to benefit from training on the largest and most diverse ab-initio databases available @jain_commentary_2013 @saal_materials_2013 @kirklin_open_2015 @schmidt_machinelearningassisted_2023 @merchant_scaling_2023 @chanussot_open_2021 @sriram_open_2023 @clausen_adapting_2024, yielding unprecedented applicability across diverse chemical spaces#footnote[How much of this transferability is true extrapolation as opposed to interpolation in a high dimensional space is debatable but also somewhat moot as utility is unlocked either way.].
By learning rich, generalizable representations of atomic environments, these so-called _foundation models_ pre-trained on millions of crystal structures and their energies, forces, stresses, and more recently magnetic moments @deng_chgnet_2023 and response to external fields @falletta_unified_2024, have the potential to run a wide variety of materials simulation at near-DFT accuracy but orders of magnitude cheaper, or, conversely, at orders of magnitude larger length and time scales.
They also serve as excellent starting points for both small and large-data fine-tuning in cases where out-of-the-box performance proves insufficient.
This 'pre-train then fine-tune' paradigm marks the defining feature of a foundation model and is an advantage of deep learning not applicable to prior ML methods that lack transferable end-to-end-learned internal representations.
#cite(<bommasani_opportunities_2022>, form: "author") @bommasani_opportunities_2022 who coined the term 'foundation model' in the context of natural language processing (NLP) define them as models broadly applicable across a wide range of tasks and datasets, transferable to new tasks with minimal fine-tuning, and a strong baseline for further model development.
In direct analogy to chemistry, we define *foundational ML force fields* in this thesis as models that are
- trained on millions of chemical spaces covering much of the periodic table, thereby becoming
- applicable to various tasks in computational materials science, from crystal structure prediction to molecular dynamics,
- effective starting points for data-efficient fine-tuning on account of having learned rich, generalizable representations of millions of atomic environments.

Developing foundational force fields that can accurately simulate the full diversity of inorganic materials presents an exciting avenue for achieving the trifecta of large-system, long-timescale high-accuracy simulations.
Such simulations greatly facilitate understanding and designing materials for applications like catalysis, energy storage and #ce("CO2") capture.
While encouraging progress has been made in training single large models on multiple modalities beyond bulk crystals such as amorphous materials, surfaces, interfaces, alloys and defects @shoghi_molecules_2023 @takamoto_towards_2022 @takamoto_teanet_2022, challenges remain regarding:

#pad(left: 1em)[
  + Developing *good metrics* to compare foundation models going forward.
    We partially address this in @sec:mbd[Chapters] and @sec:mace-mp[].
    In particular, @sec:mbd presents results on thermodynamic stability prediction from unrelaxed hypothetical crystals under realistic conditions to filter out likely unstable ones, demonstrating that stability can be predicted to useful accuracy before conducting costly DFT relaxation.
  + Ensuring model development remains *open and reproducible*.
    We contribute to this by open-sourcing #chgnet @deng_chgnet_2023 and #mace-mp @riebesell_foundation_2023, two models co-developed in @sec:mbd and thoroughly tested in @sec:mace-mp.
    Both models established a new state of the art (SOTA) at time of publication among 10 tested open-source, open-data models#footnote[The proprietary #gnome of #nequip architecture and trained on a much bigger proprietary dataset was the only model known to perform better on #mbd.].
  + *Commoditizing* foundation models so they become usable by non-experts.
    By academic standards, #link("https://github.com/CederGroupHub/chgnet")[#chgnet] and #link("https://github.com/ACEsuit/mace-mp")[#mace-mp] have well-maintained code bases and versatile easy-to-use and install APIs, public weights, public training data and public training scripts to reproduce our results and finetune the models on new data.
]

While scaling efforts from industry are likely to drive rapid progress that academia will likely struggle to keep up with (as recently demonstrated by large language models @vaswani_attention_2017 @openai_gpt4_2024 @anil_gemini_2023 @anthropic_introducing_2024), the academic and open source communities must step up to champion reproducibility and FAIRness in model development and training data generation.
Overcoming these challenges will enable the rapid deployment of GNN foundation models to the wider materials community and help unlock their full scientific utility.

