The central quantity in DFT is the electron density $n(vector(r))$, a function of just three spatial coordinates $vector(r) = (x,y,z)$.
It replaces the much more complex full electronic many-body quantum wave function $Psi(vector(R), vector(r))$ of $3N + 3M$ spatial coordinates for a system of $N$ electrons and $M$ nuclei.
Despite being a much simpler object, $n(vector(r))$ nonetheless uniquely determines the system's ground state.
This crucial insight is due to Hohenberg and Kohn, who showed that the ground-state energy $E[n(vector(r))]$ of a system is a unique functional of the electron density.
Moreover, the ground-state electron density is the minimizer of this functional, thus offering variational access to the ground state of any quantum system.
An iteratively-derived self-consistent solution @kresse_efficient_1996 of the Kohn-Sham equations @kohn_selfconsistent_1965 as shown in @fig:dft-kohn-sham-cycle, therefore, yields both the ground-state electron density and the total energy of the system from which many downstream properties can be derived.

The time-independent many-body Schrödinger equation describes the quantum behavior of a system of $N$ electrons and $M$ nuclei @martin_electronic_2020:
$
  hat(H) thin Psi(vector(R), vector(r))
  = E thin Psi(vector(R), vector(r)).
$<eqn:schroedinger>

with $Psi(vector(R), vector(r))$ the many-body wave function of $M$ nuclear coordinates $vector(R) = {vector(R)_1, ..., vector(R)_M}$ and $N$ electronic coordinates $vector(r) = {vector(r)_1, ..., vector(r)_N}$, $E$ the energy, and $hat(H)$ the many-body Hamiltonian operator that splits into
$
  hat(H)
  &=
  - overbrace(frac(planck.reduce^2, 2 m_e) sum_i vector(nabla)_i^2, hat(T)_"e")
  quad - quad overbrace(planck.reduce^2 / 2 sum_k vector(nabla)_k^2 / M_k, hat(T)_"n") \
  &quad + quad underbrace(1 / 2 sum_(i eq.not j) e^2 / (|vector(r)_i - vector(r)_j|), hat(V)_(e e))
  quad + quad underbrace(1 / 2 sum_(k eq.not l) (Z_k Z_l) / (|vector(r)_k^n - vector(r)_l^n|), hat(V)_(n n))
  quad - quad underbrace(sum_(i, k) (e Z_k) / (|vector(r)_i - vector(r)_k^n|), hat(V)_(n e))
$

where $hat(T)_(e"/"n)$ are the electronic/nuclear kinetic energy operators, $hat(V)_(e e)$ is the electron-electron interaction energy, $hat(V)_(e n)$ is the electron-nucleus interaction (also referred to as external potential $hat(V)_"ext"$), $E_(n n)$ denotes the classical nucleus-nucleus interactions.
$planck.reduce$ is the reduced Planck constant, $m_e$ the electron mass, $M_k$/$Z_k$ the mass/nuclear charge of nucleus $k$ and $e$ the elementary charge.

The Born-Oppenheimer approximation @born_zur_1927 makes use of the fact that nuclei are 3 orders of magnitude heavier than electrons, allowing us to treat the nuclear wave function as approximately stationary and solving for the electronic wave function independently at a given nuclear configuration defined by the external potential $hat(V)_(e n)$.
The resulting Hamiltonian with purely-nuclear terms removed reads:

$
  hat(H)_"BO"
  = -hat(T)_e + hat(V)_(e n) + hat(V)_(e e).
$

Although straightforward to formulate, solving this equation scales exponentially with system size, rendering it intractable for more than $cal(O)$(10) particles @kohn_nobel_1999.
To circumvent this, DFT relies on a reformulation of the many-body problem onto a system of non-interacting electrons in an external potential.
This transformation is predicated on two theorems, known as the Hohenberg-Kohn theorems @hohenberg_inhomogeneous_1964.
The first theorem states that for a given system $hat(V)_(e n)$, its total energy $E$ is a functional of the ground state charge density $n(r)$ given by:

$
  E[n(vector(r))]
  = integral "d "^3r med V_(e n)(vector(r)) med n(vector(r)) + F[n(vector(r))] + E_(n n),
$<eqn:hohenberg-kohn-1>

where the functional $F[n(vector(r))]$ maps electron density to kinetic energy and electron-electron interactions.
The second theorem asserts that the density minimizing the total energy corresponds to the ground state charge density.
Together, the two theorems establish the profound insight that the ground state total energy of a system of interacting electrons and nuclei is determined by the ground state electron density.
Thus, variational minimization of the energy functional $E[n(vector(r))]$ yields the ground state charge density and the total energy of the system.
In contrast to the $3N$ variables of an $N$-particle wavefunction, the charge density $n(vector(r))$ with $vector(r) = (x, y, z)$ has just three variables.

In practice, the self-consistency cycle for a given configuration of nuclei is often initialized to a charge density resulting from the superposition of atomic orbitals centered at each nucleus.
From this charge density, we calculate the effective potential $hat(V)_(e n)$ and the resulting electronic wavefunction $Psi_i(vector(r))$.
We then repeatedly solve the Kohn-Sham equations to get the total energy, each time modifying the charge density in the direction of decreasing energy until the input charge density guess and resulting wavefunction converge to a desired degree of self-consistency.

While the Hohenberg-Kohn theorem proves the existence of the functional @eqn:hohenberg-kohn-1, it says nothing about how to derive it nor how to make it computable.
Thankfully, as mentioned earlier, Kohn and Sham devised a method to map the many-body problem onto a non-interacting electron system in an effective potential produced by the surrounding nuclei and electrons.
Solving for the ground state charge density of the non-interacting approximation yields the same ground state as the true interacting many-body system.
Specifically, the Kohn-Sham approach reformulates the Hohenberg-Kohn expression for the ground state functional as:

$
  E_(K S)[n]
  = T_S[n] + integral "d "^3 vector(r) med V_(e n)(vector(r)) med n(vector(r)) + E_"Hartree" [n] + E_(n n) + E_"xc" [n],
$<eqn:kohn-sham>

with $T_S[n]$ the kinetic energy of non-interacting electrons, $E_"Hartree" [n]$ the mean-field Coulomb interaction energy of the electron density, and $E_"xc" [n]$ the exchange-correlation functional.
This is a useful restating of the problem as it packages all of the difficult-to-compute quantum exchange and correlation contributions into the last term $E_"xc" [n]$.
This so-called exchange-correlation energy is where most of the DFT development effort since its 1965 inception has been focused.
By rewriting @eqn:kohn-sham, we see that $E_"xc" [n]$ captures the difference in kinetic and potential energy between the interacting and non-interacting electron systems @martin_electronic_2020:

$
  E_"xc" [n]
  = angle.l hat(T)angle.r - T_S[n] + angle.l hat(V)_(e n)angle.r - E_"Hartree" [n].
$<eqn:e-xc-def>

=== Density Functionals
<sec:methods-dft-functionals>

DFT would not have reached its modern utility and resulting ubiquity without the development of highly effective approximations of $E_"xc" [n]$.
Some of the most successful are ranked by increasing accuracy and cost in @fig:dft-jacobs-ladder, Jacob's ladder of $E_"xc"$ approximations @perdew_jacob_2001.
The local density approximation (LDA) and the generalized gradient approximation (GGA) are the first two rungs of this ladder and the most popular choices for inorganic crystals.

LDA is a strictly local functional, using only the value of the electron density $n(vector(r))$ at each point to estimate $E_"xc"^"LDA" [n]$.
It is based on the exact exchange of a homogeneous electron gas $epsilon_"xc"^"homogen"$ as calculated by quantum Monte Carlo @kohn_selfconsistent_1965 @ceperley_ground_1980 @perdew_selfinteraction_1981:

$
  E_"xc"^"LDA" [n]
  = integral "d "^3 vector(r) med n(vector(r)) med epsilon_"xc"^"homogen" (n(vector(r))),
$<eqn:e-xc-lda>

Despite its strictly local dependence on the charge density and its assumption of a uniform electron gas, seemingly unjustified for highly non-uniform systems like molecules and crystals, LDA has been remarkably successful in describing the properties of condensed matter systems.
It contributed in no small part to the tremendous early success of DFT, motivating many of the resources subsequently directed toward the development of more sophisticated functionals.

GGA comprises a class of functionals one step up on the complexity ladder that approximate $E_"xc" [n]$ as a functional of both the charge density $n(vector(r))$ and its spatial gradient $nabla n(vector(r))$:

$
  E_"xc"^"GGA" [n]
  = integral "d "^3 vector(r) med n(vector(r)) med
  epsilon_"xc"^"homogen" (n(vector(r)), nabla n(vector(r))).
$<eqn:e-xc-gga>

By far the most widely used GGA variant is the Perdew-Burke-Ernzerhof (PBE) functional @perdew_rationale_1996.
It generated all ML reference data used in this thesis and was the functional of choice for high-throughput screening in @sec:diel.
GGAs improve on LDA results for many types of systems.
However, both LDA and GGA fail to reproduce long-range van der Waals dispersion interactions
These are non-local correlations that require distant information about the charge density not captured by its local value and gradient.
While LDA exhibits a systematic overbinding error, PBE is biased towards underbinding atoms.
That is, LDA (GGA) lattice parameters are typically smaller (larger) than experiment.
Both are well known to band gaps (the energy difference between highest occupied and lowest unoccupied electronic states in a material) by on average 10--40% @qu_high_2020 @assadi_theoretical_2013 @sham_densityfunctional_1983.
For more accurate band gaps, a hybrid functional like Heyd-Scuseria-Ernzerhof (HSE) @heyd_efficient_2004 @heyd_energy_2005 or an excited-state formalism beyond DFT such as many-body perturbation theory must be used.

=== Plane waves and pseudopotentials
<sec:methods-dft-basis>

To represent wavefunctions, a (preferably orthonormal) basis set is required.
According to Bloch's theorem @bloch_ueber_1929, solutions to the Schrödinger equation in a periodic potential can be expressed as plane waves modulated by periodic functions.
This makes plane waves a natural choice for basis expansion of the electron wave functions in simple metals where ionic cores only apply small perturbations to the nearly free periodic electron potential.
In fact, plane waves apply well to general extended systems such as infinitely periodic crystals.
For computational efficiency, the infinite series of plane waves must be truncated at a finite number of terms by imposing a cutoff $E_"cut"$ on the maximum electronic kinetic energy.
Depending on the unit cell's lattice parameters and a given choice of $E_"cut"$, all plane waves $exp(i vector(G) dot vector(r))$ satisfying the following equation are used in the wavefunction expansion:

$
  ℏ^2 / (2 m_e) |vector(G) + vector(k)|^2 < E_"cut",
$<eqn:plane-wave-cutoff>

where $vector(G)$ is a reciprocal lattice vector and $vector(k)$ is an electron wave vector.
For example, for $E_"cut"$ = 520 eV, the basis set resolution $d$ is:

$
  d
  = |G_"cut"|^(-1)
  = ℏ / sqrt(2 m_e E_"cut")
  = ℏ / sqrt(2 m_e dot 520 "eV")
  approx #si4(8.6e-12)"m "
  = #si4(num-mode: "format")[0.086Å].
$<eqn:plane-wave-resolution>

Core electrons are densely packed and highly localized near the nucleus.
The need for fermionic wavefunctions to be orthogonal to one another results in highly oscillatory wavefunctions for core electrons.
Meanwhile, valence electrons with more slowly varying wavefunctions in the outermost shells are much more important for chemical bonding and the resulting material properties.
Thus, all-electron DFT calculations incur a large, often unjustified (in terms of their chemical accuracy) computational cost due to the need to include high-energy plane waves to accurately describe the oscillating core electrons.
To accurately describe core wavefunctions would require a basis resolution comparable to these sub-$10^(-2) thin$Å oscillations, which would require $E_"cut"$ to grow $\~$100-fold due to appearing in the square root.
A very common and often accurate approximation is to freeze core electrons into an effective nucleus whose positive charge is reduced by the number of neglected core electrons.
This so-called pseudopotential formalism creates a smoother external potential and reduces the number of plane waves needed to accurately electronic wavefunctions.
This approach is extremely common and was used for all DFT simulations pertaining to this thesis.

=== Self-Interaction Errors
<sec:methods-dft-selfinteraction>

When representing a many-body quantum system as an effective potential in the Kohn-Sham formalism, electrons neglecting exact exchange experience spurious self-interaction with their own contribution to the charge density @perdew_selfinteraction_1981.
//  via Pauli exclusion (exchange) and Coulomb repulsion (correlation).
This error leads to issues such as over-delocalization of electrons, underestimation of bandgaps, and incorrect description of charge transfer and dissociation @kummel_orbitaldependent_2008.
It is particularly problematic in the context of redox reactions where an electron migrates between atoms with strongly differing localization environments @zhou_firstprinciples_2004 @wang_oxidation_2006.
In such cases, the self-interaction errors between initial and final electron environment do not cancel, leading to inaccurate results.
To mitigate self-interaction errors, various techniques have been developed including hybrid functionals, @heyd_hybrid_2003, the Perdew-Zunger one-electron self-interaction correction scheme @perdew_selfinteraction_1981, and the DFT+$U$ method @anisimov_firstprinciples_1997.

Hybrid functionals such as HSE include a fraction $a in (0, 1)$ (e.g. $a = 0.25$ in HSE06 and PBE0 @perdew_rationale_1996) of exact Hartree Fock exchange @heyd_hybrid_2003,

$
  E_x^"HF"
  = -1 / 2 sum_(i eq.not j) sum_(sigma=arrow.t arrow.b) integral.double "d "^3r_1 "d "^3r_2
  (Psi_i^*(vector(r)_1) Psi_j^*(vector(r)_2) Psi_i (vector(r)_1) Psi_j (vector(r)_2)) / (|vector(r)_1 - vector(r)_2|),\
$<eqn:hf-exchange>

where $i$ and $j$ sum over electron pairs and $Psi_i$ are the Kohn-Sham orbitals.
This term is added to the hybrid exchange-correlation functional:

$
  E_"xc"^"hybrid"
  = a thin E_x^"HF" + (1 - a) E_"x"^"PBE" + E_"c"^"PBE",
$<eqn:e-xc-hybrid>

with $E_"x"^"PBE"$ and $E_"c"^"PBE"$ the PBE exchange and correlation functionals.
#footnote[Incidentally, fortuitous error cancellation between $E_"x"^"PBE"$ and $E_"c"^"PBE"$ contributed in no small part to the success of semi-local functionals.]

However, while hybrid functionals avoid the need for Hubbard $U$ corrections and do so with much less empirical fitting, they also incur a significantly higher computational cost, making them as yet unsuitable for high-throughput calculations.
Existing high-throughput DFT databases instead largely opted for PBE(+$U$) for its computational efficiency.

=== Hubbard $U$ Corrections
<sec:methods-dft-hubbardu>

The Hubbard $U$ correction is primarily designed to address the problem of strongly correlated electron systems, where standard (semi-)local density functionals like LDA/GGA fail to accurately describe the electronic structure @anisimov_firstprinciples_1997.
The Hubbard $U$ correction introduces an additional term to the DFT Hamiltonian that accounts for the on-site Coulomb interaction (the $U$ term) between electrons in localized orbitals, such as $d$ or $f$ orbitals in transition metal oxides or rare-earth compounds @dudarev_electronenergyloss_1998.
This correction helps to improve the description of localized electronic states, opens up bandgaps, and better describes magnetic properties in strongly correlated systems @cococcioni_linear_2005, as well as mitigate the lack of self-interaction error cancellation among environments with contrasting localization in redox reactions @zhou_firstprinciples_2004 @wang_oxidation_2006.
The Materials Project uses $U$ corrections for all compounds containing Co, Cr, Fe, Mn, Mo, Ni, V, W in combination with O or F @jain_formation_2011.
$U$ values are calibrated specifically for the VASP `PBE_52` pseudo-potentials and phase stability analyses of oxides, and the same oxide $U$ values are also used for sulfides (presumably due to a lack of experimental sulfide fitting data).
However, MP $U$ corrections are not structure-site specific (a potential source of inaccuracy), instead applying to all sites with one of the above elements, and in those, only to the $d$-orbitals.
MP values were fitted solely with phase stability in mind.
As a result, they may harm just as easily as help in the calculation of properties such as band structures.
Crucially when training ML models on a wide range of chemical systems, the use of $U$ corrections causes inconsistent energies and forces between corrected and non-corrected DFT calculations, presenting a potential source of model (as well as user) confusion.
This establishes a lower bound on the error with which even a perfect ML model can be fit to MP reference data if $U$-corrected energies are not carefully filtered out or otherwise accounted for during training @jain_formation_2011 @wang_framework_2021.
We consider this a dangerous pitfall to newcomers and even experts, especially those entering materials informatics from the computer science domain (see e.g. spuriously elevated errors for #mace-mp and #m3gnet in @yu_systematic_2024[fig.~5] from not applying #link("https://github.com/materialsproject/pymatgen/blob/a2ab944bf8e1b90e51ca2b65f853972392177286/pymatgen/entries/compatibility.py#L824")[`MaterialsProject2020Compatibility`] @wang_framework_2021 GGA/GGA+U mixing corrections).
For an extensive discussion of $U$ corrections in MP, we refer to @zhou_firstprinciples_2004 @wang_oxidation_2006 @jain_formation_2011.

== Machine Learning
<sec:methods-ml>

Machine learning (ML) is a powerful technique for encoding carefully designed inductive biases (task-specific constraints and symmetries) into optimization algorithms that can make machines "write" or rather converge on useful programs given the right loss function to optimize.
These "programs" consist largely of conceptually simple linear algebra operations, but at a scale and level of fine-tuning that would be impossible to achieve manually.
The viability of current ML methods relies on the massive increase in compute power over recent decades and the compounding growth of digital data, be it in the form of natural language, images and video, or, in the case of materials science, high-throughput ab-initio databases.
This potent combination of large data and large compute has allowed artificial neural networks in particular to significantly outperform many other ML methods.
A challenge with applying ML to materials is designing models capable of manipulating internal representations for 3D atomic configurations in a way that adheres to physical symmetries, most importantly rotation, translation and inversion symmetry, invariance to permutation of identical atom species and, specific to crystals, respecting periodic boundary conditions.

Similar to the development of machine learning in other domains, computational chemists have approached this issue using two different paradigms: shallow and later deep learning.

+ *Shallow Learning* involves the design of hand-crafted input features for representing atomic systems as fixed-length numerical vectors to use with existing ML architectures @artrith_efficient_2017 @artrith_implementation_2016 @behler_generalized_2007 @smith_ani1_2017.
+ *Deep Learning* for materials, by contrast, developed ML architectures tailor-made for end-to-end learning of internal representations of chemical systems @kearnes_molecular_2016 @faber_prediction_2017 @xie_crystal_2018 @schutt_schnet_2018 @chen_graph_2019 @chen_universal_2022 @deng_chgnet_2023, taking lower-level data like atomic coordinates and element types as input.

The next two sections (@sec:intro-shallow-ml[] and @sec:intro-deep-ml[]) provide a high-level overview of these two approaches following @goodall_accelerating_2022.
Unsupervised and self-supervised learning -- while important subfields of ML in other domains -- have had comparatively little impact in materials science, and will be skipped in this introduction for brevity.
We touch on the future prospects of generative modeling for materials in the outlook (@sec:outlook-generative-modeling[sec.]), another major subfield of ML omitted in this introduction.

=== Shallow Learning
<sec:intro-shallow-ml>

The first appearances of ML in materials science were off-the-shelf architectures such as linear regression, support vector machines, random forests and gradient boosting.
These were trained in a supervised manner on labeled data and input features crafted by domain experts to encode local atomic environments based on existing knowledge of physical properties relevant to the target problem.

Ensemble methods like random forests @breiman_random_2001 and gradient boosting @friedman_greedy_2001 have been particularly successful in materials informatics due to their ability to capture complex, non-linear relationships between descriptors and properties from relatively small amounts of data @goodall_accelerating_2022.

The performance of shallow models in materials science is limited by the task relevance and information content of their descriptors.
Various hand-crafted atomic structure-based descriptors have been developed to represent local atomic environments @behler_generalized_2007 @rupp_fast_2012 @bartok_machinelearning_2013 @faber_crystal_2015 @huo_unified_2017 @faber_alchemical_2018 @willatt_atomdensity_2019.
To improve data efficiency and guarantee physically consistent models, these descriptors must reflect the symmetries of the underlying systems.
That means a model's internal representation must be equivariant under $E(3)$, the group of rotations, translations, reflections in 3d space, as well as permutations of same-species atoms @rupp_fast_2012.

Two featurization schemes to highlight since they are the only shallow learning techniques used in this thesis (see Voronoi Random Forest in @sec:mbd-tested-models) are the Magpie set @ward_general-purpose_2016 of general-purpose compositional descriptors and structural attributes derived from Voronoi tessellations @ward_including_2017.
Magpie introduced a 145-dimensional feature vector derived from element-amount-weighted statistics (mean, min, max, ...) of atomic, stoichiometric and electronic properties.
Unlike some earlier compositional descriptors, Magpie can be applied to arbitrary chemical systems.
It found use in discovering metallic glasses @ren_accelerated_2018 and predicting band gaps of diverse inorganic compounds @ward_general-purpose_2016.
The second technique, Voronoi tessellation, has the advantage of not relying on knowledge of the DFT-relaxed lattice parameters and being invariant to dilations or contractions of the lattice, making it a particularly applicable shallow learning method for incorporating structural information into ML-guided materials discovery where only the unrelaxed crystal structure is known.
The concatenated Magpie + Voronoi tessellation feature set is fed into a Random Forest in @sec:mbd-tested-models to establish a strong shallow learning baseline and measure the scaling advantages of end-to-end-learned representations.

=== Deep Learning
<sec:intro-deep-ml>

Unlike shallow learning, deep learning models are trained to construct information-dense internal features directly from raw low-level data.
This sidesteps the time-consuming process of handcrafting bespoke features for every new problem of interest.
Since deep learning representations are not limited by domain knowledge and human intuition, they simultaneously lift the ceiling on feature fidelity and expressiveness.
Empirically, end-to-end learned representations generally outperform hand-crafted features once training data exceeds a domain-dependent threshold, often on the order of $gt.tilde #ord(4)$ samples @chauhan_comparison_2019 @goodall_predicting_2020 @benkendorf_effects_2020 @cho_how_2016.

