The first and still widely used deep learning model is the multi-layer perceptron (MLP) @rosenblatt_perceptron_1958 dating back to 1958.
It stacks layers of simple linear transformations combined with non-linear activation functions to gradually extract hierarchical representations of the input features $vector(x)$ to predict some target property $vector(y)$ @goodall_accelerating_2022:

$
  hat(vector(y))
  = f(vector(x))
  = matrix(W)_l sigma(matrix(W)_(l-1) thin...thin sigma(matrix(W)_1 vector(x) + vector(b)_1)thin...thin + vector(b)_(l-1)) + vector(b)_l,
$<eqn:mlp>

where $matrix(W)_i in RR^(M_i times M_(i-1))$ is the matrix storing the parameters of layer $i$ which are tuned from data, $M_i$ is the number of units (a.k.a. neurons) in the layer, and $sigma(vector(x))$ is a non-linear activation function, often one of the popular choices shown in @fig:ml-activation-functions.
These have largely replaced sigmoidal activations @han_influence_1995 due to their susceptibility to vanishing gradients @hochreiter_vanishing_1998.

#par-heading[Gradient Descent and Automatic Differentiation]

A central ingredient to the success of deep learning is the ability to train deeply layered models with simple first-order gradient optimization algorithms like stochastic gradient descent @bengio_practical_2012.
This feature relies on the ability to automatically and efficiently differentiate through the model via backpropagation (i.e. repeatedly applying the chain rule of calculus to obtain gradients of the loss function with respect to the model parameters).
Given sufficient data and compute power, this allows deep learning models to learn extremely complex functions impossible to write by hand.
Modern deep learning frameworks @bradbury_jax_2018 @abadi_tensorflow_2015 @paszke_pytorch_2019 provide a plethora of modular building blocks including custom layers tailored for certain application domains with out-of-the-box automatic differentiation, abstracting away the technical complexities of implementing backpropagation @baydin_automatic_2018.
This allows researchers to focus on innovating the model forward pass and combining existing layers in novel ways, contributing to the rapid pace of progress in the field.
These frameworks also enable hardware acceleration such as graphical and tensor processing units (GPU and TPU) support to significantly reduce training times.

Among the many choices of optimizers, gradient descent is the simplest, simply updating the model parameters $vector(theta)$ at each step according to the gradient of the loss function $L(vector(theta)_t)$:

$
  vector(theta)_(t+1)
  = vector(theta)_t - eta thin nabla_vector(theta) L(vector(theta)_t).
$<eqn:gradient-descent>

The learning rate $eta$ is a hyperparameter (i.e. not optimized during training) and determines the size of each parameter update.
In practice, the full gradient on the complete data set is replaced by a stochastic approximation calculated from (usually randomly sampled) mini-batches of data samples drawn without replacement until the training set is exhausted, marking the completion of one training epoch.
Stochastic gradient descent tends to speed up convergence and provide regularization effects.
Training can often be further sped up by choosing more sophisticated optimizers that include momentum, learning rate schedules or adaptive learning rates @kingma_adam_2014, as well as weight decay, early-stopping and dropout regularization methods @srivastava_dropout_2014.

=== Graph Neural Networks
<sec:intro-gnn>

A common and widely used strategy for infusing domain knowledge into deep learning revolves around designing custom layers with inductive biases whose moving parts often naturally map onto core concepts in the data being modeled.
Notable examples include recurrent neural networks (RNNs) for series data @cho_learning_2014 @hochreiter_long_1997, transformers for language @bahdanau_neural_2016 @vaswani_attention_2017 and convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for vision @lecun_backpropagation_1989 @krizhevsky_imagenet_2012 @he_deep_2016.
In computational chemistry, this paradigm has led to the adoption of graph neural networks (GNNs), also known as message-passing neural networks (MPNNs), that operate on graph representations of molecules and crystals where nodes map onto atoms and edges model interactions between atoms as illustrated in @fig:gnn-node-aggregation.
GNNs are not chemistry-specific but have emerged as a powerful approach in various domains to learn from arbitrary graph-structured data including reconstruction, tagging, and end-to-end analysis of collider events in high-energy physics @shlomi_graph_2020 @thais_graph_2022, modeling dynamics of online social networks @rossi_temporal_2020, recommendation systems @skarding_foundations_2021 and predicting time-of-travel in navigation tools like Google Maps @derrow-pinion_eta_2021.
The one commonality in all cases is that nodes naturally map onto entities of the modeled data and edges represent relationships and interactions between them, providing a highly versatile framework for inductive biases.

#figure(
  image("figs/intro/gnn-node-aggregation.svg", width: 90%),
  caption: [
    Diagram of the node aggregation process common to all message-passing GNNs.
    The top shows the information flow from other nodes to the target node $A$ from up to two hops away corresponding to a two-layer GNN.
    The first layer aggregates information up to one hop away, i.e. from neighboring nodes $B$, $C$ and $D$ by combining the node states into a message function $U$ whose output is used to update node $A$'s state before it enters the next layer.
    The second layer then aggregates (strongly attenuated) information up to two hops away including nodes $E$ and $F$.
    The bottom shows aggregation trees for nodes $B$ to $F$, again for up to two hops away to illustrate the quickly growing receptive field of each node with layer count, especially in highly connected graphs.
    Adapted from @hamilton_graph_2020[p.~55] and @ying_graph_2018[fig.~1].
  ],
)<fig:gnn-node-aggregation>
// Local atomic environment features can then be learned by imposing a radius cutoff and letting the embedding vectors of nodes and edges within each cutoff sphere participate in a message-passing operation that determines the central node's feature vector in the next graph convolution layer @frenkel_understanding_2023.
// Early GNNs ensured $E(3)$ invariance by incorporating atomic positions only as relative distances between sites @schutt_schnet_2018 @xie_crystal_2018 @chen_graph_2019, while more recent architectures incorporate angular @gasteiger_directional_2022 @choudhary_atomistic_2021 @deng_chgnet_2023 or even higher-order vectorial information @geiger_e3nn_2022 @batzner_equivariant_2022.

The key idea behind GNNs is to iteratively update each node representation by aggregating information from its neighboring nodes and edges.
This allows GNNs to learn node embeddings that infuse node and edge features with the local graph structure directly from raw data.

Mathematically, a GNN layer can be formulated as a two-step process of message passing and node update.
Let $vector(h)_i^((t))$ denote the hidden state (a.k.a. learned representation or embedding) of node $i$ at layer $t$, and $vector(e)_(i j)^((t))$ denote the state of the edge connecting nodes $i$ and $j$.
In the message passing step $t$, each node $i$ aggregates the messages $vector(m)_(i j)^((t))$ from its neighbors $j in cal(N)(i)$:

$
  vector(m)_i^((t))
  = plus.circle.big_(j in cal(N)(i)) M_(t)(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(h)_j^((t)), vector(e)_(i j)^((t)))
$<eqn:message-passing>

where $M_t$ is a differentiable and thus trainable message function (usually a small feed-forward neural network) and $plus.circle.big$ is a permutation-invariant aggregation operator (e.g. sum, mean, min, max).
The node state $vector(h)_i^t$ is then updated by combining the aggregated message $vector(m)_i^((t))$ with the node's previous state:

$
  vector(h)_i^((t+1))
  = U_(t)(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(m)_i^((t)))
$<eqn:node-update>

where $U_t$ is again a learnable update function.
Likewise, the edge state $vector(e)_(i j)^((t))$ is updated by a learnable $E_t$ based on the hidden states of the connected nodes $i$ and $j$:

$
  vector(e)_(i j)^((t+1))
  = E_(t)(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(h)_j^((t)), vector(e)_(i j)^((t)))
$<eqn:edge-update>

By stacking $T$ message-passing layers (often $2 lt.eq T lt.eq 5$), the node representations can (in principle#footnote[In practice, GNNs often overly attenuate long-range interactions, e.g. capturing only $~1%$ of expected van der Waals forces in unpublished testing.]) capture increasingly higher-order interactions and longer-range dependencies in the graph from up to $T$ hops away.
In chemistry, this makes a powerful inductive bias as it allows atoms to exchange information about their local bonding environment, thus setting up the model to recognize recurring structural motifs and what changes to properties of interest such as the energy they correlate with.
For example, a model might learn that certain pairs of elements, when nearby, enter into tight bonds and thus lower the system's energy more than other less attracted pairs of atoms, thus allowing the model to rank different atomic configurations by stability.
The aggregation behavior of GNNs is exactly analogous to the kernel in convolutional neural networks (CNNs), except rather than operating on spatially-defined pixels, GNNs operate on the relational structure of a graph, making CNNs a special case of GNNs.
For this reason, GNN layers are also referred to as graph convolutional networks (GCN) @kipf_semisupervised_2017.

Several key architectural design choices in GNNs determine how exactly information is aggregated and propagated through the graph:

The *initial node and edge features* $vector(h)_i^((0))$ and $vector(e)_(i j)^((0))$ are the starting point for learning graph-dependent representations.
Initial node features can depend on site properties like element type, charge, and coordination number.
Edge features usually encode interatomic distances $r_(i j)$ @xie_crystal_2018.
Later models also include bond angles $theta_(i j k)$ @choudhary_atomistic_2021 @deng_chgnet_2023.
Such atom and bond attributes are often not directly used as features but are first mapped to continuous vectors via learnable embeddings:

$
  vector(h)_i^((0))
  = "Embed"(Z_i, q_i, C_i, ...),
  wide
  vector(e)_(i j)^((0))
  = "Expand"(r_(i j), theta_(i j k))
$<eqn:initial-features>

where $"Embed"$ is a lookup table for atomic embeddings that returns initial node features for the first message-passing iteration (with atomic number $Z_i$, charge $q_i$, coordination number $C_i$) and $"Expand"$ projects the scalar distances $r_(i j)$ and angles $theta_(i j k)$ from node $i$ to its neighbors into a higher-dimensional space using e.g. a radial basis function and spherical harmonics expansion @schutt_schnet_2018 @gasteiger_directional_2022.

The *message function* $M_t$ is a crucial component that determines how information is exchanged between nodes.
SchNet @schutt_schnet_2018 uses a simple element-wise multiplication (denoted as $dot.circle$) between the edge embeddings and the neighboring node features:

$
  M_(t)(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(h)_j^((t)), vector(e)_(i j)^((t)))
  = vector(h)_j^((t)) dot.circle vector(e)_(i j)^((t))
$<eqn:schnet-message>

DimeNet @gasteiger_directional_2022 incorporates angular information by using a spherical Bessel function $j_n$ and spherical harmonics $Y_ell^m$ expansion of the distances and angles:

$
  M_(t)(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(h)_j^((t)), vector(e)_(i j)^((t)))
  = vector(h)_j^((t)) dot.circle (
    sum_(n,ell) a_(n ell)^((t)) dot j_n(r_(i j))
    dot sum_(m=-ell)^ell Y_ell^(m)(vector(r)_(i j)) dot Y_ell^(m*)(vector(r)_(i k))
  )
$<eqn:dimenet-message>

where $a_(n ell)^((t))$ are learnable parameters and $k$ ranges over the neighbors of $i$.

NequIP @batzner_equivariant_2022 uses Clebsch-Gordan tensor products to construct rotationally equivariant message functions:

$
  [M_t(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(h)_j^((t)), vector(e)_(i j)^((t)))]_(k'q')
  = sum_(k thin q thin k'' q'') C_(k q k''q'')^(k'q')
  dot [vector(h)_j^((t))]_(k q) dot [vector(e)_(i j)^((t))]_(k''q'')
$<eqn:nequip-message>

where $[dot]_(k q)$ denotes the component of a feature vector transforming as the irreducible representation of $S O(3)$ with angular frequency $k$ and phase $q$, and $C_(k q k''q'')^(k'q')$ are the Clebsch-Gordan coefficients.

The *node and edge update functions* $U_t$ and $E_t$ are typically implemented as MLPs, sometimes with additional non-linearities like the Swish activation @ramachandran_searching_2017 and layer normalization @ba_layer_2016:

$
  vector(h)_i^((t+1))
  = "MLP"(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(m)_i^((t))),
  quad
  vector(e)_(i j)^((t+1))
  = "MLP"(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(h)_j^((t)), vector(e)_(i j)^((t)))
$<eqn:update-functions>

To improve the flow of information across layers, models such as Schnet @schutt_equivariant_2021, TorchMD-Net @tholke_torchmdnet_2022, CGCNN @xie_crystal_2018 and #chgnet @deng_chgnet_2023 among others use gated update functions, inspired by the gating mechanisms in LSTMs @hochreiter_long_1997 and gated recurrent units (GRUs) @cho_learning_2014.
Residual connections @he_deep_2016 between layers can also be used, especially to facilitate the training of deep GNNs:

$
  vector(h)_i^((t+1))
  = vector(h)_i^((t)) + U_(t)(vector(h)_i^((t)), vector(m)_i^((t)))
$<eqn:residual-update>

In chemistry, we are usually interested in making graph-level predictions such as the system's total energy.
Thus, the final readout of convolved node features consists of a *global pooling* operation in which final node embeddings after the last message-passing layer are pooled into a single vector:

$
  vector(h)_G
  = "Pool"({vector(h)_i^((T)) lr(|, size: #160%) i in G}).
$<eqn:global-pooling>

$"Pool"$ is a permutation-invariant pooling function (e.g. sum, mean, min, max) and $T$ is the total number of layers.
More sophisticated schemes such as differentiable @ying_hierarchical_2018 @ranjan_asap_2020 and attention-based pooling @lee_selfattention_2019 are being explored in pure ML research but have not made their way into GNNs for chemistry yet.

The pooled graph representation $vector(h)_G$ can then be passed through a final MLP to make atomic-environment-aware property predictions for the entire molecule or material:

$
  hat(vector(y))
  = "MLP"(vector(h)_G),
$<eqn:gnn-final-mlp>

with $hat(vector(y))$ commonly being the system's total energy $E$ such that forces $vector(F)_i$ and stress $matrix(sigma)$ follow from it via automatic differentiation w.r.t. the atomic positions $vector(r)_i$ and lattice strain tensor $vector(epsilon)$, respectively:

$
  vector(F)_i
  = -nabla_(vector(r)_i) E wide vector(sigma)
  = 1 / V nabla_vector(epsilon) E.
$<eqn:auto-diff-forces-stress>

*Symmetry* plays another crucial role.
Since all physical properties are either _invariant_ (scalars like energy) or _equivariant_ (vectors and higher-order tensors like forces, magnetic moments, stress) to $E(3)$ symmetry transformations, all GNNs must be designed to preserve these symmetries by using invariant or equivariant message-passing operations.
Notably, invariant models can only predict invariant quantities like total energy (from which equivariant properties like forces can nonetheless be derived), while equivariant models can directly predict equivariant quantities such as forces or magnetic moments.
Examples of equivariant models include Tensor Field Networks @thomas_tensor_2018, Cormorant @anderson_cormorant_2019, PaiNN @schutt_equivariant_2021, E3NN @geiger_e3nn_2022, NequIP @batzner_equivariant_2022, TorchMD-Net @tholke_torchmdnet_2022 and MACE @batatia_mace_2023.
Architectural variations have proliferated to the point that a comprehensive list would be lengthy and quickly outdated.
Many other models such as Schnet @schutt_schnet_2018, DimeNet @gasteiger_directional_2022, CGCNN @xie_crystal_2018, #megnet @chen_graph_2019, #m3gnet @chen_universal_2022 and #chgnet @deng_chgnet_2023 use only invariant messages, or $L=0$ equivariance, meaning the message transforms like spherical harmonic $Y_(L=0)^M$ under rotation.

Which GNN architecture to use depends on various factors including how much training data is available, the chemical diversity and types of systems being studied, the desired balance between accuracy and efficiency and which properties need to be predicted.
As the field evolves, further innovations in GNN architecture often originating in pure ML research will likely make some of the above obsolete.
However, given the generality and extensibility of the GNN framework, it is likely to remain a key asset in the future computational chemist toolbox.
For further details on the full design space of $E(3)$ equivariant interatomic potentials, we refer to @batatia_design_2022.

Early efforts to incorporate additional degrees of freedom beyond ionic positions include the Charge Equilibration Neural Network Technique (CENT) @ghasemi_interatomic_2015 @khajehpasha_cent2_2022 and 4G-BPNN @ko_fourthgeneration_2021 which feature a partial charge equilibration scheme that minimizes electrostatic energy to better handle ionic systems.
SpookyNet @unke_spookynet_2021 goes further and directly takes the number of electrons and their spin state as inputs, allowing it to differentiate the PES of systems with different electronic structures.
It also integrates a distance-independent interaction term allowing it to learn electron delocalization effects and non-local atomic interactions.
However, it still relies on semiempirical corrections for long-ranged electrostatic and dispersion interactions, making it an MLIP-classical force field hybrid.
More recently, #chgnet @deng_chgnet_2023 has incorporated magnetic moments as a proxy for oxidation states to more accurately describe heterovalent ions whose interactions can depend strongly on their valence state.
Closer adherence to the full physics provides additional latent-space regularization to the model and often allows #chgnet to infer the absolute value of magnetic moments from ionic structure, enabling the study of charge distribution and its effects on ionic dynamics in large-scale simulations.
Similarly named but more explicit in its treatment of electronic structure is ChargE3Net @koker_higherorder_2023, an E(3)-equivariant GNN that directly predicts electron density at arbitrary points in atomic systems.
The authors show starting the DFT self-consistent field (SCF) cycle from ChargE3Net-predicted electron densities requires fewer iterations to converge than VASP's default initialization which uses a superposition of atomic densities (SAD) @lehtola_assessment_2019.
Incorporating electronic degrees of freedom into MLIPs at higher fidelity is an active area of research with many innovations likely to come.
If done efficiently and with appropriate inductive biases, it has the potential to enable fully data-driven electronic structure simulations.

GNNs have become established tools for driving MD simulations and various property prediction tasks, often outperforming other ML methods by wide margins, especially on data-rich tasks.
The ability to (pre-)train GNNs on multiple datasets, possibly in an active learning cycle that generates new training data on the fly as needed based on simulation accuracy metrics, is pushing the boundaries of the cost-accuracy Pareto front set by previous, fixed approximations.
This approach maintains linear scaling of simulation cost with system size while quickly increasing in accuracy, with more advances from better data, better models and better training techniques likely to come.

=== From Classical to ML Force Fields: Evolving Fixed into Flexible Functional Forms
<sec:cff-mlff-evolution>

Force field development aims to expand the capabilities of (semi-)empirical materials modeling which revolves around increasing accuracy and transferability while minimizing cost.
This progression started with classical force fields (CFF), also known as empirical potentials, which typically model interactions as the sum of bonded and non-bonded energy terms.

$
  E_"total" = E_"bonded" + E_"non-bonded"
$

where $E_"bonded"$ includes terms for bond stretching, angle bending, and bond torsions.
In their most simplistic approximation using Hooke's law, these terms can be written as

$
  E_"bonded"
  &= E_"bonds" + E_"angles" + E_"torsions"\
  &= sum_"bonds" k_r (r - r_0)^2 + sum_"angles" k_theta (theta - theta_0)^2 + sum_"torsions" k_phi [
    1 + cos(n phi - delta)
  ],
$

where $r$, $theta$, and $phi$ are bond lengths, angles, and dihedral angles with $r_0$, $theta_0$, and $phi_0$ their equilibrium values, while $k_r$, $k_theta$, $k_phi$, are force constants and $n$ and $delta$ are phase angles.

$E_"non-bonded"$ accounts for electrostatics and van der Waals interactions, the most simplistic approximation here being Lennard-Jones potentials.

$
  E_"non-bonded"
  &= E_"electrostatics" + E_"van der Waals"\
  &= sum_(i<j) (
    frac(q_i q_j, 4pi epsilon_0 r_"ij") + 4epsilon_"ij" [(frac(sigma_"ij", r_"ij"))^12 - (frac(sigma_"ij", r_"ij"))^6]
  ),
$

where $q_i$ and $q_j$ are the partial charges on atoms $i$ and $j$, $r_"ij"$ is the distance between them, $epsilon_0$ is the vacuum permittivity, $epsilon_"ij"$ and $sigma_"ij"$ are the Lennard-Jones parameters, and $k_r$, $k_theta$, $k_phi$, $n$, and $delta$ are force constants and phase angles for the bonded terms.

CFFs enabled simulations of specific classes of (bio-)molecules and materials which for which they had to be specifically designed for.
As a result, every new material class or even chemical system required fitting a new bespoke force field, potentially requiring architectural changes, and thus placing a high barrier to entry for studying new systems, making classical force fields a suboptimal choice exploring new chemical spaces.
While computationally efficient, thus allowing simulation of up to millions of atoms over nanosecond timescales, their simple functional forms place inherent limits on accuracy and transferability, especially for chemical reactions or many-component chemical environments @cornell_second_1995 @mackerell_allatom_1998 @jorgensen_development_1996.
Key limitations of classical force fields include:

+ Unable to describe bond breaking/formation
+ Limited accuracy for polarization and many-body interactions
+ Struggle to capture complex electronic effects
+ Challenges in determining when to use more complex functional forms (e.g., polarizable force fields)
+ Reliance on predefined bonding patterns

The progression from classical force fields to modern MLFFs can be broadly characterized by several key steps:

+ Reactive Force Fields (1990s -- 2000s): Introduced bond order terms and allowed for dynamic formation and breaking of chemical bonds @vanduin_reaxff_2001.

+ Ab Initio Molecular Dynamics (1980s -- present): Directly use quantum mechanical calculations to determine forces, providing high accuracy but at huge computational cost @car_unified_1985.

+ Neural Network Potentials (2000s -- 2010s): Used artificial neural networks to represent potential energy surfaces, trained on quantum mechanical data @behler_generalized_2007.

+ Deep Learning Potentials (2010s -- present): Employ graph neural networks and end-to-end training to learn representations directly from atomic coordinates and charges @schutt_schnet_2017 @unke_physnet_2019.

MLFFs have emerged as a promising avenue to address these limitations by learning the potential energy surface directly from high-quality quantum mechanical reference data.
Human engineering occurs only at the high-level of inductive biases (e.g. designing a suitable graph representation and adherence to $E(3)$ equivariance) but otherwise trained end-to-end from raw data with little or no tailoring of the model to specific systems.
They typically employ flexible functional forms such as neural networks or kernel methods.
The universal approximation theorem states that feedforward networks with non-polynomial activations are dense in continuous function space between two Euclidean spaces @hornik_multilayer_1989.
As a result, MLIPs offer essentially infinite functional flexibility able to model atomic interactions of all kinds.
A simple feed-forward neural network potential might take the form:

$
  E = sum_i "NN"(G_i)
$

where $"NN"$ is a neural network and $G_i$ is a descriptor of the local atomic environment of atom $i$ used to predict each atom's contribution to the system's total energy $E$.
Knowing $E$, many other system properties can be derived.
More sophisticated graph neural network architectures, as described in the previous section, offer increased expressivity and data efficiency due to equivariance to physical symmetries.

Key advantages of MLIPs include:

+ Automatic capture of complex many-body interactions without predefined functional forms
+ Highly flexible end-to-end learned descriptors for arbitrary numbers of diverse chemical environments and reactions
+ Potential for ab initio accuracy with classical force field efficiency
+ Ability to systematically improve towards ab initio accuracy with more training data while maintaining linear scaling with system size
+ Controllable increase in model inference cost with growing data set size (increased parameter count to keep up with growing datasets often leads to sublinear increase in inference cost due to efficient hardware acceleration)

The flexibility of MLIPs comes at the cost of requiring large, high-quality datasets and careful training procedures.
Generating such datasets and training large models on them both require highly specialized skill sets that are in high demand but draw from largely disjoint talent pools.
However, once trained, they enable simulations at near-DFT accuracy but orders of magnitude faster @behler_perspective_2016.
While hard to predict where the rapid pace of current improvements might stall, MLFFs currently appear as the most promising method for bridging the gap between classical force fields and DFT for accurate yet large-scale materials simulations.
They approach both the speed and favorable scaling of classical force fields and the accuracy of ab initio quantum simulations, thus pushing the cost-accuracy Pareto boundaries in materials modeling as illustrated in @fig:dft-mlff-cff-speed-accuracy-transfer.

#figure(
  image("figs/intro/dft-mlff-cff-speed-accuracy-transfer.svg", width: 70%),
  caption: [
    Speed-accuracy-transferability trade-off of DFT, foundational MLFFs, and CFFs.
    DFT provides the highest accuracy and versatility but is slow and scales poorly with system size.
    CFFs are very computationally efficient at decent accuracy but are tailored to specific chemical systems and interaction types and so offer poor transferability.
    MLFFs offer near-DFT accuracy at a fraction of the cost and scale linearly with system size, thus bridging the gap between the speed of classical force fields and the accuracy and versatility of DFT.
  ],
)<fig:dft-mlff-cff-speed-accuracy-transfer>

=== ML in DFT
<sec:ml-in-dft>

While this thesis is exclusively focused on training full-PES ML models from DFT reference data, it is worth noting that ML can also be integrated into the DFT formalism itself by only learning the most challenging contribution to the energy of a quantum system: an ML functional for the Kohn-Sham exchange-correlation $E_"xc"^("ML")[n(vector(r))]$ @li_kohnsham_2021 @trepte_data_2022 @kovacs_what_2022 @nagai_machinelearningbased_2022 @bystrom_nonlocal_2024.
This approach is particularly compelling as it keeps all the easily calculable physics, such as electronic and ionic kinetic energy, ion-ion and electron-ion interactions while learning only $E_"xc"^("ML")[n(vector(r))]$ from high-quality reference data.
This reduces the problem space needed to solve with statistical methods and provides new avenues for regularization as exchange-correlation $E_"xc" [n(vector(r))]$ is well-known to adhere to 17 exact physical constraints @sun_strongly_2015 which if satisfied greatly enhance the functional's transferability and accuracy.
By using ML only to learn a correction, the combination of DFT and ML acts in a similar fashion to a gradient-boosting ensemble.
DFT becomes the first tree that models most of the physical variation while ML as the second tree learns to account for the residuals.
Similar to linear-scaling GNNs, this line of research also provides a path to pushing the cost-accuracy Pareto front, albeit at a higher point on the cost spectrum.
In the best case, it has the potential to yield an orbital-dependent and non-local functional with the accuracy of hybrid DFT at the cost of semi-local functionals @bystrom_nonlocal_2024.

