== Introduction
<sec:mbd-intro>

Materials science can be viewed as a combinatorial problem of mixing and arranging different atoms to leverage the complex range of properties that emerge.
To date, $~10^5$ combinations have been tested experimentally @bergerhoff_inorganic_1983 @belsky_new_2002 and $~10^7$ have been simulated @jain_commentary_2013 @saal_materials_2013 @curtarolo_aflow_2012 @draxl_nomad_2018.
However, an estimated $~10^10$ quaternary materials are allowed by electronegativity and charge-balancing rules @davies_computational_2016.
The space of quinternaries and higher is even larger but much less explored, leaving vast numbers of potentially useful materials to be discovered.
The discovery of new materials is a key driver of technological progress and lies on the path to more efficient solar cells, lighter and longer-lived batteries, and smaller and more efficient transistor gates just to name a few.
In light of our sustainability goals, these advances cannot come fast enough.
Any speed-up novel discovery methods might yield should be leveraged to their fullest extent.

Despite significant advances in all areas of materials science, discovering new compounds still requires complex calculations, and labor-intensive trial-and-error experimentation, and often happens fortuitously rather than through rational design.
Machine learning (ML) methods efficiently extract and distill trends from huge datasets, and can handle high dimensionality, multiple objectives @riebesell_pushing_2024, uncertainty @borg_quantifying_2022 @goodall_rapid_2022 @zhu_fast_2023 @schwalbe-koda_information_2024, and noisy or sparse data @depeweg_decomposition_2017 @bartel_critical_2020, making them powerful additions to the computational materials science tool set.

ML models are less accurate and reliable but orders of magnitude faster than ab-initio simulation.
This makes them most suitable for use in high-throughput (HT) searches to triage more expensive, higher-fidelity simulation methods.
The use of neural networks for learning the Kohn-Sham density-functional theory (DFT) potential energy surface (PES) can be traced as far back as #cite(<behler_generalized_2007>, form: "year") @behler_generalized_2007.
This work kicked off rapid advances and significant efforts to fit ever more sophisticated ML models to known samples of the PES.
Initially, most of these models were trained and deployed as interatomic potentials (also known as force fields) to study known materials of interest, a workflow that requires curating custom training data for each new system of interest @bartok_machine_2018 @deringer_general-purpose_2020.
As larger and more diverse datasets have emerged from initiatives like the Materials Project (MP) @jain_commentary_2013 @saal_materials_2013 @kirklin_open_2015 @schmidt_machinelearningassisted_2023 @merchant_scaling_2023 @chanussot_open_2021 @sriram_open_2023 @clausen_adapting_2024, researchers have begun to train so-called universal models that cover 90 or more of the most-application relevant elements in the periodic table.
This enables new ways of ML-guided materials discovery across the periodic table in hopes of increasing the hit rate of stable crystals and speeding up DFT- and expert-driven searches.

Progress in ML for materials is often measured according to performance on standard benchmark data sets.
As ML models have grown in complexity and applicability, benchmark datasets need to grow with them to accurately measure their usefulness.
However, due to the rapid pace of the field and the variety of possible approaches for framing the discovery problem, no large-scale benchmark yet exists for measuring the ability of ML to accelerate materials discovery.
As a result, it is unclear which methodologies or models are best suited for this task.
Recent works focusing on prospective computational materials discovery have proposed strategies based on one-shot coordinate free predictors @goodall_rapid_2022, iterative Bayesian optimizers @zuo_accelerating_2021, and universal interatomic potentials (UIP) @chen_universal_2022@deng_chgnet_2023 @batatia_mace_2023.
These papers deploy their respective models on specific systems and custom datasets to highlight certain strengths but have yet to be compared in a systematic standardized manner that allows them to be ranked by their ability to accelerate materials discovery.
Our work aims to identify the state-of-the-art (SOTA) model by proposing a novel evaluation framework that closely simulates a real-world discovery campaign guided by ML models.

Specifically, we designed a task that addresses three central challenges.
We believe meeting these challenges is a requirement when seeking to justify experimental validation of ML predictions:

+ *Mimic Real-world Deployment*: Idealized and overly simplified benchmarks can fail to reflect the real-world challenges a model faces when used for actual prospective discovery.
  This can result in a disconnect between benchmark metrics and real-world performance.
  Possible reasons for this include choosing the wrong target @bartel_critical_2020 or picking an unrepresentative train/test split @wu_moleculenet_2018 @kpanou_robustness_2021.
  In the case of materials discovery, formation energies - although widely used as regression targets - do not indicate thermodynamic stability.
  (Free) energy distance to the convex hull spanned by competing phases in the same chemical system is a much more informative indicator.
  Moreover, ML models relying on relaxed crystal structures as input render any discovery pipeline circular since obtaining relaxed structures requires computationally expensive DFT simulations, thus depending on the very process we intend to accelerate.

+ *Opportunity cost*: Accurate regressors are susceptible to unexpectedly high false-positive rates if those accurate predictions lie close to the decision boundary.
  Looking purely at global metrics like MAE, RMSE and $R^2$ can give practitioners a false sense of security about their model's reliability.
  Failed experiments incur a high opportunity cost by wasting lab time and resources.
  Thus false positive rate (FPR) is a pivotal metric.

+ *Scalability*: Future discovery efforts are likely to encounter large data regimes.
  Small benchmarks can lack chemical diversity, obfuscate poor scaling relations or poor out-of-distribution (OOD) performance (see @fig:wbm-final-struct-matminer-features-2d-umap for a UMAP projection of our train and test sets).
  For instance, random forests achieve excellent performance on small datasets but are prone to overfit and are typically outperformed by neural networks on datasets exceeding #ord(4) samples due to the benefits of deep representation learning @goodall_predicting_2020.

Two prior efforts worth highlighting that have partially addressed the above challenges are Matbench @dunn_benchmarking_2020 and the Open Catalyst Project (OCP) @chanussot_open_2021.

By providing a standardized collection of 13 datasets ranging in size from $~300$ to $~#si1(132e3)$ samples from both DFT and experimental sources, Matbench addresses the scalability challenge, highlighting how model performance changes as a function of data size.
It also helped direct the field, increase comparability across papers and provide a quantitative measure of progress over time.
However, all tasks were exclusively concerned with the properties of known materials.
We believe a task that simulates a materials discovery campaign by requiring materials stability prediction from unrelaxed structures to be a missing piece for ranking ML model utility.

OCP is a large-scale initiative to discover substrate-adsorbate combinations that catalyze key industrial reactions to convert said adsorbates into more useful products.
OCP has released two data sets for training and benchmarking ML models thus far, OCP20 @chanussot_open_2021 and OCP22 @tran_open_2022.
OCP certainly addressed challenge 1 of closely mimicking a real-world problem.
However, the metrics are not task-specific, only reflect regression performance and fail to account for opportunity cost.
They have recently shown that despite not reaching the target accuracy they deem necessary to entirely replace DFT, using ML in conjunction with confirmatory DFT calculations dramatically speeds up their combinatorial screening workflow @lan_adsorbml_2023.

We believe that addressing all three challenges in a single benchmark will enable future ML-guided discovery efforts to expand materials databases to confidently select appropriate models and methodology.
Our findings show that UIPs outperform all other methodologies we tested both in accuracy and robustness.

== Evaluation Framework for Materials Discovery
<sec:evaluation-framework-for-materials-discovery>

Our proposed evaluation framework places no constraints on the type of data a model trains on as long as it would be available to a practitioner conducting a real materials discovery campaign.
We only enforce that at test time, all models must make predictions on the convex hull distance of the relaxed structure with only the unrelaxed structure as input.
This setup avoids circularity in the discovery process, as unrelaxed structures can be cheaply enumerated through element substitution methodologies and do not contain information inaccessible in a prospective discovery campaign.
Eschewing the frequently used regression target of formation energy, we instead choose to focus on the relaxed structure's zero Kelvin convex hull distance as the highest fidelity proxy of true crystal stability available in large quantities >#ord(5).
We recognize that our ground truth is ignorant of entropic stabilization and metastable states.
While these factors influence experimental synthesizability, both data availability and current model restrictions force us to neglect them.
Future benchmarks should aim to use the free energy hull distance instead as an even more realistic stability proxy once a sufficiently comprehensive free energy hull becomes available, preferably at multiple temperatures.
The decision to use hull distance over formation energy was also motivated by the analysis in @bartel_critical_2020 who found even composition-only models capable of predicting DFT formation energies with useful accuracy.
However, when tasking those same models with predicting decomposition enthalpy, performance deteriorated sharply due to the smaller value spread of formation energies and less systematic cancellation of errors among similar compounds.
This insight meant that ML models are much less useful than DFT for discovering new inorganic solids.
Moreover, the qualitative leap in performance from Roost @goodall_predicting_2020, the best compositional model benchmarked, to CGCNN @xie_crystal_2018, the single structural model they tested, reaffirms the well-known fact that structure plays a crucial role in determining material stability.
Hence our decision to restrict test-time model input to unrelaxed structures to avoid the above-mentioned circularity and measure true prospective utility while still allowing for more precise structure-based energy predictions.

Standard practice in ML benchmarks is to hold as many variables as possible fixed -- most importantly the training data -- and vary only the model architecture to isolate architectural effects on the performance.
We deliberately deviate from this practice due to diverging objectives from common ML benchmarks.
Our goal is to identify the best methodology for accelerating materials discovery.
An ML potential that can learn a higher fidelity model of the physical interactions between ions from the forces and stresses recorded in DFT relaxations has a genuine advantage in training data size over another model that trains on energies only which we want our benchmark to reflect.
For that reason, valid model submissions are permitted to train on the entirety of the Materials Project (MP) @jain_commentary_2013 database release #link("https://docs.materialsproject.org/changes/database-versions#v2022.10.28")[v2022.10.28].
Any subset of the energies, forces, stresses, magnetic moments or any other recorded DFT data are valid training targets.
All of these would be available to a practitioner performing a real materials discovery campaign and hence are fair game in our benchmark.
Models may train on every single relaxation frame, or diversity maximizing subsets thereof such as initial and final relaxed structures only.
Our test set consists of the unrelaxed structures generated via element substitution in the WBM dataset @wang_predicting_2021.
Their target values are the PBE formation energies of the corresponding DFT-relaxed structures.

=== Materials Project Training Set
<sec:materials-project-training-set>

The Materials Project is a well-known effort to calculate the properties of all inorganic materials using high-throughput ab-initio methods.
Seeded from a subset of the Inorganic Crystal Structure Database (ICSD) @allen_crystallographic_1999, the initial release of the database consisted of $~#si1[9k]$ crystals.
At the time of writing, the Materials Project database @jain_commentary_2013 has grown to $~#si1(n-mp-entries)$ crystals, covering diverse chemistries and providing the relaxation trajectory and VASP charge densities among other things for every entry.

Our benchmark defines the training set as all data available from the #link("https://docs.materialsproject.org/changes/database-versions#v2022.10.28")[v2022.10.28 MP release].
We recorded a snapshot of energies, forces, stresses and magnetic moments for all MP ionic steps on 2023--03--15 as the canonical training set for #mbd, and provide convenience functions through our #link("https://pypi.org/project/matbench-discovery")[Python package] for easily feeding that data into future model submissions.

The flexibility in specifying the maximum allowed dataset is intended to allow authors to experiment with and exploit the large variety of available data.
This choice is motivated by two factors.
First, whilst it may appear that models that train on multiple snapshots containing energies, forces and stresses are getting more training data than models that are only trained or able to be trained on the energies of the relaxed structures the critical factor is that all this additional data was generated as a byproduct of the workflow to produce the relaxed structures i.e. all models have been trained from the same total cost of training data acquisition.
If some architectures or approaches can leverage more of this byproduct data to make improved predictions this is a fair comparison between the two models.
This approach diverges philosophically from other benchmarks such as the OCP and Matbench where it has been more common to subcategorize different models and look at multiple alternative tasks (e.g. composition-only vs structure-available in Matbench or IS2RS, IS2RE, S2EF in OCP) and do not make direct comparisons of this manner.
Second, recent work in the space from @li_critical_2023 @li_exploiting_2023 has claimed that much of the data in large databases like MP are redundant and that models can be trained more effectively by taking a subset of these large data pools.
We believe that from a systems-level perspective identification of novel cleaning and or active-learning strategies that do not leak signal from the test set are equally as important as architectural improvements as they can lead to similar improvements in performance, particularly given the prevalence of errors in high-throughput DFT that can disrupt learning of the PES.
Consequently, such strategies where they lead to improved performance should be able to be recognized within the benchmark.
We encourage submissions to submit ablation studies showing how different system-level choices affect performance.

We highlight for example data sets that are valid within the rules of the benchmark that take advantage of these freedoms.
The first is the #link("https://figshare.com/articles/dataset/MPF_2021_2_8/19470599")[MPF.2021.2.8] dataset ref.~@chen_universal_2022 curated to train the #m3gnet model which takes a subset of materials from the #link("https://docs.materialsproject.org/changes/database-versions#v2021.02.08")[v2021.02.08] MP release.
Rather than taking every ionic step from the relaxation trajectory this dataset opts to select only the initial, final and one intermediate structure for each material to avoid biasing the dataset towards examples where more ionic steps were needed to relax the structure.
Additionally, the MPF.2021.2.8 dataset filters the #link("https://docs.materialsproject.org/changes/database-versions#v2021.02.08")[v2021.02.08] release significantly to select a subset of calculations for increased self-consistency.
That is, keeping only DFT calculations that ran prior to minor changes in the `MPRelaxSet` VASP settings prior to 2019 to increase dataset homogeneity.
MPF.2021.2.8 is a proper subset of the training data as no materials were deprecated between database releases #link("https://docs.materialsproject.org/changes/database-versions#v2021.02.08")[v2021.02.08] and #link("https://docs.materialsproject.org/changes/database-versions#v2022.10.28")[v2022.10.28].
The second dataset we highlight is #mptrj @deng_chgnet_2023.
It was introduced alongside #chgnet @deng_chgnet_2023 but has since been used to train other universal force fields including #mace-mp and #sevennet.
#mptrj was curated from the v2021.11.10 MP release and contains #si1(n-mptrj-entries) frames from #si0(n-mp-entries) DFT relaxations, i.e. nearly all of MP.
It removed only a small number of suspect and potentially confusing energy, force, stress and magnetic moment labels which required designing carefully tuned consistency filters before the frames were subsampled using the `pymatgen` @ong_python_2013 `StructureMatcher` to remove nearly identical structures with no additive training value.
It therefore covers nearly all of MP's structural and chemical variety, thus making it an excellent training set for ML potentials for its time.

Importantly, #mptrj is also a proper subset of the canonical #mbd training set, making any model trained on it a valid submission.
The v2022.10.28 release contains a small number of additional Perovskite structures not found in #mptrj that could be added to the training set while staying within the scope of the benchmark.

We also note that #link("https://docs.materialsproject.org/changes/database-versions#v2023.11.1")[v2023.11.1] deprecated $~#si1[5k]$ calculations so data queried from subsequent database releases is not considered valid for #mbd.

=== WBM Test Set
<sec:wbm-test-set>

The WBM dataset @wang_predicting_2021 consists of $~#si1(n-wbm-entries)$ structures generated via chemical similarity-based element substitution of MP source structures followed by DFT relaxation and calculating each crystal's convex hull distance.
Which element replaces an existing one in a given source structure was determined by random sampling according to the weights in a chemical similarity matrix data-mined from the ICSD @glawe_optimal_2016.

The WBM authors performed five iterations of this substitution process (we refer to these iterations as batches).
After each step, the newly generated structures found to be thermodynamically stable via PBE relaxation flow back into the source pool to partake in the next round of substitution.
This split of the data into batches of increasing substitution count is a unique and compelling feature of the test set as it allows out-of-distribution (OOD) testing by seeing if model performance degrades with substitution count.
A higher number of element substitutions on average carries the structure further away from the region of material space covered by the MP training set (see @fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-models[Figs.] and @fig:wbm-final-struct-matminer-features-2d-umap[] for details).
While this batch information makes the WBM dataset a very useful data source for examining the extrapolation performance of ML models, except for @fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-models our evaluation primarily looks at metrics that consider all batches as a single test set.

Throughout this work, we define stability as being on or below the convex hull of the MP training set ($E_"MP hull dist" lt.eq 0$).
$~#si1(n-wbm-stable)$ out of $~#si1(n-wbm-entries)$ materials (#wbm-pct-stable) in WBM satisfy this criterion.
Of these, $~#si1[33k]$ are unique prototypes, meaning they have no matching structure prototype in MP nor another higher-energy duplicate prototype in WBM.
Our code treats the stability threshold as a dynamic parameter, allowing for future model comparisons at different thresholds.
This may reveal systematic differences in stability calibration, as hinted by the different TPR/TNR tradeoffs observed for #chgnet and #m3gnet in @tab:metrics-table-first-10k.
A looser stability threshold (e.g. $E_"MP hull dist" lt.eq 0.05$ eV/atom) may benefit a model like #m3gnet which is more conservative in its stability predictions, whereas a stricter threshold should favor a model like #chgnet that is more optimistic in its stability predictions.
In @fig:roc-models (or the #link(mbd-site-url + "/preprint#roc-curves")[interactive web version] which shows the stability threshold corresponding to each point on hover), the ROC curves of #chgnet and #m3gnet indeed exhibit the largest gap for a stricter stability threshold of $E_"MP hull dist" lt.eq #si1[-10meV/atom]$.

As WBM explores regions of materials space not well sampled by MP, many of the discovered materials that lie below MP's convex hull are not stable relative to each other.
Of the $~#si1(n-wbm-stable)$ that lie below the MP convex hull less than half, or around $~#si1[20k]$, remain on the joint MP+WBM convex hull.
This observation suggests that many WBM structures are repeated samples in the same new chemical spaces.
It also highlights a critical aspect of this benchmark in that we purposely operate with an incomplete convex hull.
Only current knowledge of competing points on the PES is accessible when doing real discovery and our metrics are designed to reflect this.

== Models
<sec:mbd-tested-models>

To test a wide variety of methodologies proposed for learning the potential energy surface, our initial benchmark release includes 10 models.

+ *MACE* @batatia_mace_2023 (UIP-GNN) - MACE builds upon recent advances @batzner_equivariant_2022 @thomas_tensor_2018 in equivariant neural network architectures by proposing an approach to computing high-body-order features efficiently via Atomic Cluster Expansion @drautz_atomic_2019.
  Unlike the other UIP models considered, MACE was primarily developed for molecular dynamics of single-material systems, not the universal use case studied here.
  Submitting it to this benchmark required significant upfront engineering effort including migrating the edge embeddings of interatomic distances to Gaussian radial basis functions, tuning the loss function by moving to Huber loss which deweights outliers and stabilizes the training process, and implementing multi-GPU training required to scale to the this larger training set than what MACE has traditionally been trained on.
  MACE is the only open $E(3)$-equivariant model we tested.#footnote[
    #gnome shown in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos-with-closed using a #nequip architecture is also $E(3)$-equivariant but trained on a much larger incompatible dataset, allowing no direct architectural comparisons to the other invariant UIPs #chgnet and #m3gnet.
  ]

+ *#chgnet* @deng_chgnet_2023 (UIP-GNN) - #chgnet is an invariant ML potential for charge-informed atomistic modeling.
  Its distinguishing feature is that it was trained to predict magnetic moments on top of energies, forces and stresses in the #mptrj dataset consisting of relaxation trajectories for $~#si1(1.5e6)$ MP structures (see @sec:mp-wbm-eda for a detailed analysis of this dataset).
  By modeling magnetic moments, #chgnet learns to accurately represent the orbital occupancy of electrons which allows it to predict both atomic and electronic degrees of freedom.

+ *#m3gnet* @chen_universal_2022 (UIP-GNN) - #m3gnet is another $E(3)$-invariant GNN-based universal interatomic potential for materials trained on up to 3-body interactions that significantly inspired #chgnet's development.
  The version submitted to this benchmark was trained on the initial, middle and final frame of pre-2019 MP DFT relaxations.
  Like #chgnet and #mace-mp, model was tested in relaxation mode, meaning force predictions were used to move atoms to the input structures ML-PES ground state before predicting its energy.

+ *ALIGNN* @choudhary_atomistic_2021 (GNN) - The Atomistic Line Graph Neural Network (ALIGNN) is a message-passing GNN architecture that takes as input both the interatomic bond graph and a line graph corresponding to 3-body bond angles.
  The ALIGNN architecture involves a global pooling operation which means that it is ill-suited to force-field applications.
  To address this the ALIGNN-FF model was later introduced without global pooling @choudhary_unified_2023.
  We also attempted to test that model variant in relaxation mode but encountered severe #link("https://github.com/janosh/matbench-discovery/blob/d8386081/models/alignn_ff/readme.md?plain=1")[technical hurdles] which forced us to abort.

+ *#megnet* @chen_graph_2019 (GNN) - MatErials Graph Network is a GNN inspired by and similar to CGCNN originally intended mainly for property prediction of relaxed structures.
It can incorporate global features (like pressure, temperature and entropy) in its message-passing operation.
This work showed that learned element embeddings encode periodic chemical trends and can be transfer-learned from large data sets (formation energies) to predictions on small data properties (band gaps, elastic moduli).

+ *CGCNN* @xie_crystal_2018 (GNN) - The Crystal Graph Convolutional Neural Network (CGCNN) was the first neural network model to directly learn eight different DFT-computed material properties from a graph representing the atoms and bonds in a periodic crystal.
  CGCNN was among the first to show that just like in other areas of ML, given large enough training sets, neural networks can learn embeddings that outperform human-engineered structure features directly from the data.

+ *CGCNN+P* @gibson_data-augmentation_2022 (GNN) - This work proposes simple structure perturbations of relaxed structures as a means of training data augmentation to supplement the data set with further from equilibrium configurations but mapped to the same DFT final energy.
  The authors introduced this data augmentation method applied to CGCNN but in principle, it could be used with any structure-based GNN.
  We chose $P = 5$ for our CGCNN-P submission, meaning the training set is augmented with 5 random perturbations of each relaxed MP structure mapped to the same target energy.
  In contrast to all other structure-based GNNs considered in this benchmark, CGCNN+P is not attempting to learn the Born-Oppenheimer potential energy surface.
  The model is instead taught the PES as a step-function that maps each valley to its local minimum.
  The idea is that during testing on unrelaxed structures, the model will predict the energy of the nearest basin in the PES.
  The authors confirm this by demonstrating a lowering of the relaxed energy error when given unrelaxed structures as input.

+ *#wrenformer* (Transformer) - For this benchmark, we introduce #wrenformer which is a variation on the coordinate-free Wren model @goodall_rapid_2022 constructed using standard QKV-self-attention blocks @bahdanau_neural_2016 @vaswani_attention_2017 in place of message-passing layers.
  This architectural adaptation reduces the memory usage allowing the architecture to scale to structures with greater than 16 Wyckoff positions on common hardware.
  Like its predecessor, #wrenformer is a fast coordinate-free model aimed at accelerating screening campaigns where even the unrelaxed structure is a priori unknown.
  The key idea is that by training on the coordinate anonymized Wyckoff positions (symmetry-related positions in the crystal structure), the model learns to distinguish polymorphs while maintaining discrete and computationally enumerable inputs.
  The benefit of an enumerable input is that it allows users to predict the energy of all possible combinations of spacegroup and Wyckoff positions for a given composition and maximum unit cell size.
  The lowest-ranked prototypes can then be fed into downstream analysis for further validation, thus potentially making the task of materials discovery a countable exercise.

+ *#bowsr* @zuo_accelerating_2021 (BO-GNN) - #bowsr combines a symmetry-constrained Bayesian optimizer (BO) with a surrogate energy model to perform an iterative exploration-exploitation-guided search of the potential energy surface.
  Here we use #megnet @chen_graph_2019 for the energy model as proposed in the original work.
  The high sample count needed to explore the PES with BO makes this by far the most expensive model tested.

+ *#voronoi-rf* @ward_including_2017 (Structure Fingerprint) - A random forest trained to map a combination of composition-based Magpie features @ward_general-purpose_2016 and structure-based relaxation-robust Voronoi tessellation features @ward_including_2017 (effective coordination numbers, structural heterogeneity, local environment properties, etc.) to DFT formation energies.
  This fingerprint-based model predates most deep learning for materials but significantly improved over earlier fingerprint-based methods such as the Coulomb matrix @rupp_fast_2012 and partial radial distribution function features @schutt_how_2014.
  It serves as a baseline model to see how much value the learned featurization of deep learning models can extract from the increasingly large corpus of available training data.

Except for #m3gnet and #mace-mp which are trained to predict the total PBE electronic free energy, all models predict the formation energy $E_"form"$ including #link("https://github.com/materialsproject/pymatgen/blob/02a4ca8/pymatgen/entries/compatibility.py#L823")[MP2020 GGA/GGA+U and anion energy corrections] @wang_framework_2021.

== Results
<sec:results>

#figure(
  kind: table,
  image("figs/mbd/metrics-table-uniq-protos.svg", width: 115%),
  caption: [
    Classification and regression metrics for all models tested on our benchmark ranked by F1 score.
    All metrics are calculated from ML-predicted $E_"above MP hull"$ in units of eV/atom.
    For classification metrics, only $"sign"(E_"above MP hull" - t_"stab")$ matters where the stability threshold $t_"stab" = 0$ is a benchmark parameter we set to zero.
    Thus, classification metrics measure whether a model's predictions for compounds to be above or below the convex hull agree with PBE DFT.
    The heat map ranges from yellow \(best) to blue \(worst) performance.
    DAF = discovery acceleration factor is the ratio of model precision to percentage of stable structures in the test set, TPR = true positive rate = $"TP" / ("TP" + "FN")$, TNR = true negative rate = $"TN" / ("TN" + "FP")$, MAE = mean absolute error, RMSE = root mean squared error.
    The dummy classifier uses the `scikit-learn` `stratified` strategy of randomly assigning stable/unstable labels according to the training set prevalence.
    The dummy regression metrics MAE, RMSE and $R^2$ are attained by always predicting the test set mean.
    The three universal interatomic potentials MACE, #chgnet and #m3gnet take the top 3 spots by F1 score and achieve an impressive performance gap especially in regression metrics to the other seven force-free models, highlighting the high information content of forces and stresses for learning a more accurate PES.
    #voronoi-rf, CGCNN and #megnet perform worse than dummy in regression metrics but better than dummy on some classification metrics which are more indicative of model utility for guiding discovery, demonstrating that regression metrics alone can be misleading.
    To increase 'OOD-ness' of WBM, this table is restricted to the subset of materials with no matching structure prototype in MP nor another higher-energy duplicate prototype in WBM, reducing the test set size to #si1(n-wbm-entries) → #si1(n-wbm-uniq-protos).
    See @tab:metrics-table for metrics on the whole WBM test set and details on prototype matching.
  ],
)<tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos>

@tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos shows performance metrics for all models included in the initial release of #mbd.
Regression metrics for ML vs PBE convex hull distance have units of eV/atom.
MACE takes the top spot and emerges as the current SOTA for ML-guided materials discovery.
It outperforms the nine other models on all six classification metrics but is slightly overtaken by #chgnet in 2 of 3 regression metrics, $R^2$ and RMSE, which are sensitive to outliers.
The discovery acceleration factor (DAF) is the ratio of the precision to the prevalence.
It measures how many more stable structures a model found compared to the dummy discovery rate achieved by randomly selecting test set crystals.
The maximum possible DAF is the inverse of the prevalence or dummy discovery rate which on our dataset is $(#si1(n-wbm-stable-uniq-protos) \/ #si1(n-wbm-uniq-protos))^(-1) approx #si1(n-wbm-uniq-protos / n-wbm-stable-uniq-protos)$.
Thus, the current SOTA of 3.85 achieved by #mace-mp leaves room for improvement.
However, evaluating each model on the much smaller subset of its #si1[10k] most stable predictions as shown in @tab:metrics-table-first-10k, #chgnet takes the lead in all nine metrics, in particular achieving an impressive DAF of 5.29 which approaches optimal performance, indicating that the most confident stable crystal predictions from SOTA models are becoming reliable.

We find a large performance gap between models that make one-shot predictions directly from unrelaxed inputs (#megnet, #wrenformer, CGCNN, CGCNN+P, ALIGNN, #voronoi-rf) compared to UIPs that learn from force and stress labels to emulate DFT relaxation (#chgnet, #m3gnet, MACE).
While the F1 scores and DAFs of force-free models are surprisingly less affected, their regression metrics such as $R^2$ and RMSE are significantly worse.
Of the force-free models, only ALIGNN, #bowsr and CGCNN+P achieve positive predictive power $R^2$.
Negative $R^2$ means model predictions explain the observed variation in the data less than simply predicting the test set mean.
In other words, these models are not predictive in a global sense (across the full dataset range).
However, even models with negative $R^2$ can be locally good in the positive and negative tails of the test set distribution.
They suffer most in the mode of the distribution near the stability threshold of #si1[0eV/atom] above the hull.
This reveals an important shortcoming of $R^2$ as a metric for stability prediction which ultimately comes down to a yes or no decision on whether to validate a prediction and hence reduces to a binary classification task.

The results for #m3gnet depart from the trend that F1 is broadly rank-correlated with the other classification metrics.
#m3gnet achieves a high true positive rate (TPR = 0.8) but a notably lower true negative rate (TNR = 0.81) than #chgnet and ALIGNN which have similar F1 scores.
@fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-models provides a visual explanation for this observation.
#m3gnet has a lower rolling mean of the absolute errors (rolling MAE) as a function of hull distance for materials above the convex hull (right half of plot) but incurs comparably large errors for materials below the hull (left half of plot).
Since $"TPR" = "TP" / ("TP" + "FN")$, lower error for energies above the hull increases TN and decreases FP, resulting in #m3gnet's high TPR.

The reason CGCNN+P achieves better regression metrics than CGCNN but performs worse as a classifier is apparent from @fig:hist-clf-pred-hull-dist-models.
The CGCNN+P histogram is more sharply peaked at the 0 hull distance decision boundary, causing even small errors in the predicted convex hull distance to be large enough to invert a stability classification.
Again, this is evidence to choose carefully which metrics to optimize for materials discovery.
Regression metrics are far more prevalent when evaluating energy predictions.
However, our benchmark treats energy predictions as merely a means to the end of stability classification.
Improvements in regression accuracy are of limited use to materials discovery in their own right unless they also improve classification accuracy.
Our results demonstrate that this is not a given.

#figure(
  image("figs/mbd/cumulative-precision-recall.svg", width: 110%),
  caption: [
    This figure measures model utility for discovery efforts of varying sizes by plotting the precision and recall as a function of the number of model predictions validated.
    #chgnet initially achieves the highest cumulative precision and recall.
    However, for a campaign that validates $~#si1[25k+]$ model predictions, #mace-mp overtakes #chgnet in both precision and recall and maintains that lead till the end.
    A typical discovery campaign will rank hypothetical materials by model-predicted hull distance from most to least stable and validate the most stable predictions first.
    A higher fraction of correct stable predictions corresponds to higher precision.
    The reverse, fewer stable materials overlooked corresponds to higher recall.
    This figure highlights how different models perform better or worse depending on the length of the discovery campaign.
    The UIPs (#chgnet, #m3gnet, MACE) are seen to offer significantly improved precision on shorter campaigns of $~#si1[20k]$ or less materials validated as they are much less prone to false positive predictions among highly stable materials.
  ],
)<fig:cumulative-precision-recall>

@fig:cumulative-precision-recall has models rank materials by model-predicted hull distance from most to least stable; materials furthest below the known hull first, materials on the hull last.
For each model, we iterate through that list and calculate at each step the cumulative precision and recall of correctly identified stable materials.
This simulates exactly how these models would be used in a prospective materials discovery campaign and reveals how a model's performance changes as a function of the number of materials screened for stability.
Practitioners have a certain amount of resources available to validate model predictions.
These curves allow them to identify the best model given their search pool and validation budget as well as the optimal trade-off between fewer false positives (precision) or fewer negatives (recall) for the discovery task at hand.
In this case, it so happens that #chgnet achieves the highest precision _and_ recall initially, but is overtaken by #mace-mp after $~#si1[25k+]$ materials are screened.

A line terminates when a model believes there are no more materials in the WBM test set below the MP convex hull.
The dashed vertical line shows the actual number of stable structures in our test set.
All models are biased towards stability to some degree as they all overestimate this number, most of all #bowsr by 133%, least of all #megnet by 30%.
This is only a problem in practice for exhaustive discovery campaigns that validate _all_ stable predictions from a model.
More frequently, model predictions will be ranked most-to-least stable and validation stops after some pre-determined compute budget is spent, say, #si1[10k] DFT relaxations.
In that case, the concentration of false positive predictions that naturally accumulates near the less stable end of the candidate list can be avoided with no harm to the campaign's overall discovery rate (see @tab:metrics-table-first-10k for a similar metrics table considering only the #si1[10k] materials predicted by each model to be furthest below the known convex hull).

The diagonal Optimal Recall line would be achieved if a model never made a false negative prediction (classifying a stable structure as unstable) and stopped predicting crystals as stable exactly when the true number of stable materials is reached.
Zooming in on the top-left corner of the precision plot, we observe that #chgnet is the only model without a sudden drop in precision right at the start of the discovery campaign, meaning its first few hundred most stable materials are largely actually stable.
MACE in particular suffers from several initial failure cases.
MACE underpredicts the energy of these unstable materials by several eV/atom (see @fig:each-parity-models), resulting in MACE's initial precision starting at 0 before abruptly climbing to $~0.8$.
We experienced this behavior with multiple independently trained MACE variants; even more so with a checkpoint we received directly from the MACE authors which was trained on the #m3gnet training set.
The results shown here are from a superior MACE trained on the $~10$x larger (though much more redundant) #mptrj training set which we trained specifically for #mbd.
#m3gnet likewise exhibits the early-on precision drop.
As a result, #chgnet has a strong lead over #m3gnet until reaching $~#si1[3k]$ screened materials.
From there, #chgnet and #m3gnet slowly converge until they almost tie at a precision of 0.52 after $~#si1[56k]$ screened materials.
At that point, #chgnet's list of stable predictions is exhausted while #m3gnet continues, dropping in precision to 0.45 at #si1[76k], attributable to many false positives near the convex hull.

All force-free models exhibit much stronger early-on precision drop, falling to 0.6 or less in the first #si1[5k] screened materials.
Many of these models (all except #bowsr, #wrenformer and #voronoi-rf) display an interesting hook shape in their cumulative precision, recovering again slightly between $~#si1[5k]$ and up to $~#si1[30k]$ screened materials before dropping again towards the end.

#figure(
  image("figs/mbd/rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-models.svg"),
  caption: [
    Universal potentials are more reliable classifiers because they exit the red triangle earliest.
    These lines show the rolling MAE on the WBM test set as the energy to the convex hull of the MP training set is varied.
    Lower is better.
    Inside the large red 'triangle of peril', models are most likely to misclassify structures.
    As long as a model's rolling MAE remains inside the triangle, its mean error is larger than the distance to the convex hull.
    If the model's error for a given prediction happens to point towards the stability threshold at $E_"above MP hull" = 0$, its average error will change the stability classification from true positive/negative to false negative/positive.
    The width of the 'rolling window' box indicates the width over which prediction errors were averaged.
  ],
)<fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-models>

@fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-models provides a visual representation of the reliability of different models as a function of a material's DFT distance to the MP convex hull.
The lines show the rolling MAE of model-predicted hull distances vs DFT.
The red-shaded area, which we coin the 'triangle of peril', emphasizes the zone where the average model error surpasses the distance to the stability threshold at 0 eV.
As long as the rolling MAE remains within this triangle, the model is most susceptible to misclassifying structures.
Because the average error is larger than the distance to the classification threshold at 0, it is large enough on average to flip a correct classification into an incorrect one (if the error happens to point toward the decision boundary).

The sooner a model exits the triangle on the left side (negative DFT hull distance), the less likely it is to incorrectly predict stable structures as unstable, thereby reducing false negatives.
Exciting the triangle early on the right side (positive DFT hull distance) results in a lower likelihood of predicting unstable structures as stable, leading to fewer false positives.

On both sides, MACE exits the triangle first at a remarkably low $±30$ meV/atom hull distance followed closely by #chgnet, consistent with the high accuracy of these models in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos.
#m3gnet performs similarly to #chgnet for stable structures but has a widening performance gap for increasingly unstable structures on the right side of the plot.
This leads to #m3gnet's relatively low TNR of 0.81 compared to #chgnet's 0.87 in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos.

All models tend to have lower rolling error towards the plot's left edge compared to the right edge.
This imbalance shows that models are more prone to false positive than false negative predictions.
In other words, all models are less likely to predict a material at −#si4[0.2eV/atom] DFT hull distance as unstable than a material at #si4[0.2eV/atom] DFT hull distance as stable.
From a practitioner's standpoint, this is undesirable as attempting to validate an unstable material usually has a much higher opportunity cost than missing a stable one.
We hypothesize this error imbalance is due to the MP training set having an uncharacteristically high share of stable materials, causing models trained on it to be biased towards low-energy predictions even for high-energy structures.

As the convex hull becomes more thoroughly sampled by future discovery, the fraction of unknown stable structures decreases, naturally leading to less enriched future test sets.
This has several implications, including allowing for higher maximum DAFs but also skewing the hull distance distribution towards positive values (i.e. the right half of @fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-models) as there are fewer undersampled chemical spaces.
Consequently, just to retain equally accurate stability classifications, model accuracy will need to improve concomitantly.
This is particularly the case for the left half of @fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-models, where models will most need to become more accurate to still be able to exit the shaded triangle.

=== Metrics on full test set and for #si1[10k] materials predicted most stable
<sec:metrics-for-10k-materials-predicted-most-stable>

While @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos evaluates model performance on the subset of #si1(n-wbm-uniq-protos) WBM structures with no matching structure prototype in MP and no higher-energy duplicate prototype in WBM, @tab:metrics-table includes the full WBM test set of #si1(n-wbm-entries) unrelaxed structures.
The #si1(32784 + 11175) removed materials with non-unique prototypes comprise #num-fmt(11175) discarded due to having a matching structure prototype in MP and #num-fmt(32784) materials which are prototype duplicates of another WBM material with lower energy.
The motivation to remove identical structure prototypes is that when correctly relaxed, both will result in the same ground state structure.
This has two downsides: it increases the chance of leakage between train and test set and screening materials already in the database does not constitute discovery.
For the most part, however, we find metrics to be insensitive to testing on the full WBM test set or the subset of unique prototypes.
The most noteworthy difference between the two tables is a drop in DAF for all models in @tab:metrics-table compared to @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos.
MACE for example achieves a DAF of 3.5 on the full test set (@tab:metrics-table) compared to 3.85 on the subset of #si1(n-wbm-uniq-protos) materials with unique prototypes (@tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos).
This #percent(3.85 / 3.5 - 1) increase is largely due to an #percent(1 - (n-wbm-stable-uniq-protos / n-wbm-uniq-protos) / (n-wbm-stable / n-wbm-entries)) decrease in the fraction of materials below the MP convex hull: #percent(n-wbm-stable-uniq-protos / n-wbm-uniq-protos) (#num-fmt(n-wbm-stable-uniq-protos) out of #num-fmt(n-wbm-uniq-protos)) in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos vs #wbm-pct-stable (#num-fmt(n-wbm-stable) out of #num-fmt(n-wbm-entries)) in the full dataset (@tab:metrics-table).
Since DAF is the ratio of the model's precision for stability prediction to the prevalence of stable structures, a lower prevalence results in a higher DAF if model performance remains constant.

Although matching prototypes is non-trivial and could potentially introduce bias into the test set during deduplication, we still opted to feature @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos as the main metrics table.
Even if it made little difference here, we expect the removal of prototypes overlapping with MP to better reflect a model's true ability to extrapolate to out-of-domain materials.
Prototypes were matched based on an Aflow-style @hicks_aflow_2021 Wyckoff representation as implemented in #link("https://github.com/CompRhys/aviary/blob/3289c4de/aviary/wren/utils.py#L264")[`aviary.wren.utils.get_protostructure_label_from_spglib`] @goodall_rapid_2022.
This string encodes the crystal's prototype and is invariant to relaxation (unless the system changes spacegroup during relaxation, usually by gaining symmetry).
It will therefore count structures with different lattice parameters as duplicates if both are expected to relax to the same ground state.

#figure(
  kind: table,
  image("figs/mbd/metrics-table.svg", height: 170pt),
  caption: [
    Same as @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos but computed for all #si1(n-wbm-entries) structures in the WBM test set, no duplicate prototypes excluded.
    The prevalence of stable structures is #wbm-pct-stable (#num-fmt(n-wbm-stable) out of #num-fmt(n-wbm-entries)), placing a ceiling of 6 on the maximum possible DAF.
  ],
)<tab:metrics-table>

A real-world discovery campaign is unlikely to validate all stable predictions from a given model as we did in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos.
Presumably, it will rank model predictions from most to least stable and screen that list as far as time and compute budget permits.
Assuming that increases in compute resources will allow average future discovery campaigns to grow in scope, we believe #si1[10k] model validations to be a reasonable scope for a representative discovery effort.
@tab:metrics-table-first-10k measures performance for this scenario by calculating classification and regression metrics for the #si1[10k] test set materials predicted to be most stable by each model.
We again show dummy performance in the bottom row.
Note that each model is now evaluated on a different slice of the data.
However, the bottom row still shows dummy performance across the whole dataset.
#chgnet and #m3gnet achieve an impressive precision of 0.83 and 0.8, respectively.
In concrete terms, a discovery campaign that validates #si1[10k] model predictions from a search pool of #si1(n-wbm-entries) crystals that are chemically dissimilar from the training set and of which #wbm-pct-stable are stable, would get four stable structures for every five predictions from #chgnet and #m3gnet.
We emphasize that in light of the significant resulting increase in stability hit rate, these models are well worth integrating into future materials searches.

