@fig:box-hull-dist-errors shows the interquartile ranges (IQR) of hull distance errors for each model.
#bowsr has the highest median error of 0.054, while #voronoi-rf has the highest IQR of 0.19.
#mace-mp by contrast achieves the lowest median error of 0.014 and the lowest IQR of 0.062.
#megnet and CGCNN are the only models with a positive median, meaning they are more likely to overestimate rather than underestimate the DFT hull distance.
This explains their ability in the cumulative precision/recall curves (@fig:cumulative-precision-recall) to get the overall number of stable structures in the test set nearly right.

=== Classification Histograms using Model-Predicted Energies
<sec:classification-histograms-using-model-predicted-energies>

#figure(
  image("figs/mbd/hist-clf-pred-hull-dist-models-5x2.svg", width: 90%),
  caption: [
    *Model-predicted hull distance distributions colored by stability classification.*
    Models are sorted from top to bottom by F1 score.
  ],
)<fig:hist-clf-pred-hull-dist-models>

The thickness of the red and yellow bands in @fig:hist-clf-pred-hull-dist-models shows how often models misclassify as a function of how far away from the convex hull they predict a material.
While #chgnet and #m3gnet perform almost equally well overall, they do so via different trade-offs.
#m3gnet has a thinner yellow band than #chgnet, meaning it commits fewer false negatives, but a thicker red band corresponding to more false positives.
In a real discovery campaign, false positives (red) have a higher opportunity cost than false negatives (yellow), since they result in wasted DFT relaxations or even wasted synthesis time in the lab.
A false negative by contrast is merely one missed opportunity out of many.
Thus, a practitioner might prefer a model like #chgnet over #m3gnet in order to trade more false negatives (missed stable materials) in exchange for fewer false positives.
This observation is also reflected in the higher TPR and lower TNR of #m3gnet vs #chgnet in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos, as well as the lower rolling MAE for #chgnet vs #m3gnet on the stable side (left half) of @fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-models and vice-versa on the unstable side (right half).

Note the CGCNN+P histogram in @fig:hist-clf-pred-hull-dist-models is more strongly peaked than CGCNN's which agrees better with the actual DFT ground truth distribution of hull distances in our test set (see @fig:hist-wbm-hull-dist).
This explains why CGCNN+P performs better as a regressor, but also reveals how it can simultaneously be a worse classifier.
By moving predictions closer to the stability threshold at #si4[0eV/atom] above the hull, even small errors can tip a stability prediction over the decision boundary.

=== Measuring extrapolation performance from WBM batch robustness
<sec:measuring-extrapolation-performance-from-wbm-batch-robustness>

The WBM test set was generated in 5 successive batches, each step applying another element replacement to an MP source structure or a new stable crystal generated in one of the previous replacement rounds.
The likelihood by which one element replaces another is governed by ISCD-mined chemical similarity scores for each pair of elements.
Naively, one would expect model performance to degrade with increasing batch count, as repeated substitutions should on average 'diffuse' deeper into uncharted regions of material space, requiring the model to extrapolate more.
We observe this effect more for the energy-only models than the ML potentials.

#figure(
  grid(
    columns: (1fr, 1fr),
    column-gutter: 1em,
