    image("figs/mbd/rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-m3gnet.svg"),
    image("figs/mbd/rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-alignn.svg"),

    image("figs/mbd/rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-megnet.svg"),
    image("figs/mbd/rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-wrenformer.svg"),

    image("figs/mbd/rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-cgcnn.svg"),
    image("figs/mbd/rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-voronoi-rf.svg"),
  ),
  caption: [
    *UIP energy errors remain consistently low even for increased out-of-distribution (OOD) structures in later WBM substitution batches.*
    Each model's rolling MAE as a function of DFT convex hull distance split by WBM substitution batch.
    In general, later batches (esp. 4 and 5) show higher errors than earlier ones, providing strong empirical evidence in support of the claim that the WBM test set constitutes OOD testing.
    In particular, #mace-mp, #chgnet and #m3gnet show strong extrapolation performance as they exhibit low error across the whole DFT stability spectrum and only minor deterioration in performance on later batches.
  ],
)<fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-models>

@fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-models shows the rolling MAE of model-predicted convex hull distance as a function of DFT hull distance for each of the 5 WBM rounds of element substitution.
These plots show a stronger performance decrease for #wrenformer and #voronoi-rf than for UIPs like #m3gnet, #chgnet, #mace-mp and even force-less GNNs with larger errors like #megnet and CGCNN.

On WBM batch 1, #wrenformer performs comparably to the SOTA UIPs #m3gnet and #chgnet.
However, #wrenformer exhibits a pronounced increase in MAE with batch count.
We view these plots as a strong indicator that #mbd is indeed testing out-of-distribution extrapolation performance as it appears to be the simplest (Occam's razor) explanation for the observed model performance drop with increasing batch count.
The effect is larger for some models than others but batches 4 and 5 consistently incur the highest convex hull distance errors for all models.

#megnet and CGCNN both incur a higher rolling MAE than #wrenformer across all five batches and across most or all of the hull distance range visible in these plots.
However, similar to the UIPs, #megnet and CGCNN exhibit less degradation for higher batch counts.
A stronger increase in error for later WBM batches appears to be specific to #wrenformer and #voronoi-rf which suggests training only on composition and coarse-grained structural features (spacegroup and Wyckoff positions in the case of #wrenformer; coordination numbers, local environment properties, etc. in the case of #voronoi-rf) alone is insufficient to learn an extrapolatable map of the PES.

Considering its strong performance on batch 1, given sufficiently diverse training data #wrenformer could potentially become similarly accurate as the UIPs (at least for energies) across the entire PES while being substantially faster at inference time.
However, in light of the difficulty of creating high-quality high-volume training sets, data efficiency is a key consideration for any ML model and #mbd shows ML potentials have an edge over other architectures when it comes to data efficiency.
Moreover, the lack of force and stress predictions makes energy-only models unattractive for simulations.

=== Largest Errors vs DFT Hull Distance
<sec:largest-errors-vs-dft-hull-distance>

Given the large variety of models tested, we asked whether any additional insight into the errors can be gained from looking at how the predictions vary between different models.
In @fig:scatter-largest-errors-models-mean-vs-true-hull-dist-all we see two distinct clusters emerge when looking at the 200 structures with the largest errors.
This clustering is particularly apparent when points are colored by model disagreement.
There is a strong color separation between the mostly dark blue low-energy bias predictions and green/yellow/red high-error predictions.
Blue means models are in good agreement, i.e. all models are "wrong" together.
Green/yellow/red means large-error predictions with little model agreement, i.e. all models are wrong in different ways.
Some of the blue points with large errors yet good agreement among models may be accurate ML predictions for ill-converged DFT relaxations as was the case for the #wrenformer errors analyzed in @sec:wrenformer-high-energy-predictions.
The dark blue points also tend to be slightly larger corresponding to larger structures where DFT issues may be less surprising.
ML model committees could potentially be used to cheaply screen large databases for DFT errors in a high-throughput manner.

The lack of points near the parity line ($x = y$) is due to the nature of the plot only including high-error predictions.
The bias towards underestimating hull distance apparent from the larger share of points below the parity line is unsurprising considering MP training data mainly consists of low-energy structures, leading to a bias towards low-energy predictions.

