=== #megnet formation energies from UIP-relaxed structures
<sec:megnet-e-form-from-uip-structures>

#figure(
  kind: table,
  image("figs/mbd/metrics-table-uip-megnet-combos.svg", width: 100%),
  caption: [
    *#megnet, an energy-only model, does not make better final energy predictions than UIPs when given UIP-relaxed structures as input.*
    All rows in this table show metrics for the task of predicting the relaxed energy given the unrelaxed structure (IS2RE).
    Metrics in rows labeled #m3gnet→#megnet and #chgnet→#megnet are the result of passing #m3gnet/#chgnet$$-relaxed structures into #megnet for formation energy prediction.
    Both model combos perform worse than using the respective UIPs on their own with a more pronounced performance drop from #chgnet to #chgnet→#megnet than #m3gnet to #m3gnet→MEGnet.
    This suggests that #megnet has no additional knowledge of the PES that is not already encoded in the UIPs.
    However, both combos perform better than #megnet on its own, demonstrating that ML relaxation imparts some of the latent knowledge of the PES into the relaxed structure from which a more informed final energy prediction is possible.
    This underscores the utility of ML relaxation at a very low cost for any downstream structure-dependent analysis.
  ],
)<tab:metrics-table-megnet-uip-combos>

@tab:metrics-table-megnet-uip-combos shows that #megnet predicts less accurate energies than #chgnet and #m3gnet even when it has access to either the #chgnet or #m3gnet$$-relaxed structure.
While all regression metrics improve for the model combos #m3gnet→#megnet and #chgnet→#megnet over standalone #megnet, the classification metrics even deteriorate except for TPR which markedly increases.
However, @tab:metrics-table-megnet-uip-combos shows that #chgnet→#megnet and #m3gnet→#megnet both perform worse than either #chgnet or #m3gnet by themselves.
There are too many confounding effects at play to draw firm conclusions from this but this tentatively suggests having a separate specifically trained for the purpose of formation energy prediction offers no benefits over a model simultaneously trained on energies, forces and stresses, even when allowing the energy-only model to make its prediction from the same ML-relaxed structure as the UIP's final energy.


While #chgnet was trained to predict formation energies per atom including #link("https://github.com/materialsproject/pymatgen/blob/02a4ca8/pymatgen/entries/compatibility.py#L823")[`MP2020` energy corrections] @wang_framework_2021 and #megnet to predict formation energies with the #link("https://github.com/materialsproject/pymatgen/blob/02a4ca8/pymatgen/entries/compatibility.py#L766")[legacy MP corrections] (which we swapped for the `MP2020` corrections in our analysis), #m3gnet was trained directly on PBE electronic free energies.

Changing the target from raw DFT energies to formation energies in principle merely constitutes a change of gauge since the difference is just a linear transformation of subtracting the elemental reference energies weighted by composition.
But in practice and in the absence of z-scoring the targets, one might expect the problem of stability prediction to be slightly easier for the model when training targets are formation energies, as the data range is much smaller, requiring model parameters to shift less during training from their random initialization.

