== Discussion
<sec:mbd-discussion>

We have demonstrated the effectiveness of ML-based triage in high-throughput materials discovery and posit that the benefits of including ML in discovery workflows now clearly outweigh the costs and risks.
In a realistic benchmark scenario, several models achieve a discovery acceleration greater than 3.5 across the whole dataset (@tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos) and up to 5.6 when considering only the #si1[10k] most stable predictions from each model (@tab:metrics-table-first-10k), approaching the highest possible DAF of #si1(n-wbm-uniq-protos / n-wbm-stable-uniq-protos) on our benchmark.
When starting this project, we were unsure which is the most promising ML methodology for high-throughput discovery.
Our findings demonstrate a clear superiority in the accuracy and extrapolation performance of UIPs like #chgnet, #m3gnet and #mace-mp.
Modeling forces enables these models to chart a path through atomic configuration space closer to the DFT-relaxed structure from where a more informed final energy prediction is possible.
The consistently linear log-log learning curves observed in related literature @vonlilienfeld_retrospective_2020[fig.~2] @merchant_scaling_2023[fig.~1e] suggest that further decreases in the error of UIPs can be readily unlocked with increased training data, even without improvements in model architecture or training techniques.

In summary, we found a substantial increase in the predictive power of UIPs for crystal stability since the sobering 2020 analysis in ref.~@bartel_critical_2020.
Despite its exciting pace of progress, the field of universal ML potentials is still in its early stages.
Many shortcomings remain and invite further research.
All models are biased towards stability, overestimating the correct number of stable materials in our test set by 30% (#megnet) to 133% (#bowsr).
As a result, even the best models in our analysis still exhibit a significant fraction of false positive predictions including for materials as high as #si4[50meV/atom] above the hull (see @fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-models[Figs.] and @fig:hist-clf-pred-hull-dist-models[]), inviting further research into model calibration.
By contrast, both DeepMind's proprietary #gnome and Microsoft's #mattersim trained on $~55$x and $~11x$ larger dataset, respectively, get the true number of #si1(n-wbm-stable) materials stable with respect to the MP convex hull almost right.
#gnome predicts #si1(38993) as stable while #mattersim nails it with #si1(43796), in both cases contributing to fewer false positives from these models and a resulting increase in DAF as shown in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos-with-closed.
We opted to relegate the metrics table @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos-with-closed that includes proprietary models trained on larger incompatible datasets (otherwise identical to @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos) to the appendix as the results are not comparable and strictly speaking not admissible by the rules of the benchmark, yet are likely of interest to a wider audience as demonstrations of how far this technology can be pushed.
As such, proprietary closed-source model submissions, while irreproducible and thus impossible to verify by outsiders given the closed data, trained weights and/or code, may act as guideposts for future community efforts.
In particular, looking beyond the obvious advantage of having seen $~55$x the number of structures during training than the open UIPs trained on #mptrj, we speculate that #gnome's excellent performance is in no small part due to the larger share of far-equilibrium configurations in #gnome's #si1[89M] training set.
By comparison, #mptrj contains only #si1(n-mptrj-entries) structures of which $~#si0(n-mp-entries)$ are relaxation end points.
Specifically, they used a batch size of 32 structures, 16 of which were randomly sampled from across the whole relaxation trajectory while the other 16 were drawn only from initial relaxation frames, increasing the representation of far-equilibrium structures during training to maximize structure diversity.
They report this sampling strategy to "substantially improve performance on downstream tasks" @merchant_scaling_2023[p.~10].
We still caution that no firm conclusions can be drawn from this $N=1$ sample size, especially since many details of the #gnome dataset are unbeknownst to us which could have a confounding effect on this result.
Gaining a detailed understanding of the chemical, structural, energy and force distributions even of the publicly shared subset of the #gnome training data and how that affects ML potential predictions will require a large concerted effort by a diverse committee of expert chemists and ML researchers @cheetham_artificial_2024.
However, our results in @sec:mlff-pes-softening investigating the origins of PES softening in MLFFs likewise indicate datasets less biased towards stable structures will alleviate if not fully remedy the observed tendency for models trained on MP to underpredict energy.

This reinforces the need for future models to train on more diverse datasets less biased towards near-equilibrium structures than #mptrj.
The #link("https://alexandria.icams.rub.de")[Alexandria dataset] @schmidt_crystal_2021 @schmidt_machinelearningassisted_2023 offers a compelling choice for a highly diverse open dataset specifically engineered for training foundational GNN potentials.
It contains PBE, #pbe-sol and SCAN data with a more even distribution of elements and crystal symmetries than MP which is heavily oxide-dominated (see @fig:mp-element-counts-by-occurrence).
Alexandria's impressive size of over #si1(3e6) PBE geometry optimizations ($~20$x the size of MP), #si1(15e4) of which resulted in relaxed structures less than #si4[50meV/atom] above the convex hull, provide good coverage of both ground-state and metastable regions of the PES.
The #link("https://github.com/materialsproject/atomate2/pull/532")[#matpes] collaboration will likewise help fill this data gap, which we launched in the second half of 2023 to generate an even higher-fidelity diverse MLFF training set at the #r2scan level of theory with #ord(5) structures specifically sampled from high-temperature MLMD trajectories to cover far-from-equilibrium regions of the PES.
At time of writing, #matpes has reached #si1(13e4) #r2scan completed static calculations of #si1[300K] #m3gnet$$-MD snapshots with a similar number at #si1[600K] and #si1[900K] hopefully to be finished by the end of 2024.
#matpes uses the latest `PBE_64` VASP pseudo-potentials which offer increased accuracy for several rare-earth elements as well as finer convergence settings than #link(mp-relax-set-url)[`MPRelaxSet`] which generated all data in #mptrj.

// To realize the full potential of these models, we will need to pivot significant resources to generate large quantities of higher-than-PBE fidelity training data.

We believe our work (e.g. @fig:rolling-mae-vs-hull-dist-wbm-batches-models) and others @lan_adsorbml_2023 have caught early glimpses that sufficiently large training sets allow us to narrow the performance gap between in-domain and out-of-distribution performance.
Closing this gap will further increase the discovery acceleration factor, ideally resulting in a virtuous cycle between ML models accelerating new training data generation while becoming more accurate and even stronger accelerators after retraining.
This is a typical active learning cycle but at the scale of the entire ML potential community.
Meanwhile, the setup cost and learning curve of ML potentials are steadily decreasing, likely with a much lower floor on the entry barrier than DFT given the intricacies of high-throughput ab-initio simulation.
Given their already strong performance, this suggests that UIPs combined with data accumulation over the next few years may pave the way to a more comprehensive yet cheap-to-evaluate map of the PES that helps commoditize materials discovery.

Looking beyond finding new stable materials via thermodynamic stability prediction at zero Kelvin, materials research also requires understanding and predicting properties under varying conditions of positive temperature and pressure.
This is where interatomic potentials provide significantly increased utility over energy-only models.
Force and stress predictions enable insights into dynamical properties.
One open question of particular relevance is the extent to which such models may aid research into the computational prediction of synthesis pathways which has received growing attention in recent years @aykol_network_2019 @jang_structurebased_2020 @huo_machinelearning_2022 @lee_machine_2022 @aykol_predicting_2023 @zhu_predicting_2023 @zhang_combining_2024 @duan_reactot_2024.
Many existing approaches for reaction pathway prediction involve the use of heuristic rules for dealing with the significant added complexity of metastability alongside traditional ground state ab-initio data @mcdermott_graph-based_2021@aykol_rational_2021 @wen_chemical_2023.
These algorithms stand to benefit immensely from more efficient estimates of the reaction energy barriers that future UIPs can provide and may enable much more specific guidance to experimentalists including specific synthesis steps to try in order to reach a desired configuration of atoms that was identified as a promising candidate material.
If sufficient reaction barrier accuracy is reached, this will open up a the field of synthesis pathway prediction to a more impactful high-throughput mode.

