We plot the PBE total dielectric constant vs PBE band gap of all #si1[7.2k] MP materials with DFPT results in @fig:diel-total-vs-bandgap-mp.
As indicated by the blue, green and yellow shaded ellipses, ideal high-band-gap-high-permittivity dielectric materials lie in the top right of this plot.
However, different computing applications have different requirements with different priorities for balancing band gap and permittivity.
Materials for flash storage in particular require large band gaps to minimize leakage current and maintain polarization over extended time periods.
CPU gate dielectrics tradeoff lower band gaps in exchange for increased permittivity which lowers the gate voltage required to achieve polarization and hence decreases power consumption.
For random access memory (RAM) applications, increased leakage current resulting from a lower band gap is acceptable since RAM is memory-refreshed hundreds of times a second (stored data is read and immediately rewritten unmodified to preserve integrity; this prevents polarization sapping over time).
Instead, optimal RAM performance relies on exceptionally high permittivity so that each repolarization costs minimal energy.
Our goal is to discover materials in any of these regions beyond the dashed green isoline of constant figure of merit $Φ_M = #si1[240eV]$).
@fig:diel-parts-vs-bandgap-mp reveals the principal permittivity contribution in most materials is ionic rather than electronic and that $ϵ_"ionic"$ is more likely to overcome the $1 / x$ relationship with $E_"gap"$ and allow breaching the current Pareto front.

== Scalable Dielectric Discovery Workflow
<sec:diel-workflow>

The large search space and high cost of experimental validation demand a funnel approach.
To maximize the size of the initial candidate pool and still retain tractable computational cost, less auspicious materials must be discarded by a hierarchy of successively more expensive but higher-fidelity computational filters.
Such an approach maximizes return on invested effort by allotting more resources to candidates which accumulated evidence of expected utility in earlier filters.
@fig:diel-discovery-workflow gives an overview of the components and design decisions that go into our dielectric discovery workflow.
Our proposed implementation precedes high-throughput DFPT with 5 to 6 orders of magnitude cheaper ML pre-screening which in this instance reduced #num-fmt(n-diel-generated) generated candidate materials down to #num-fmt(n-diel-dfpt-us) with computed dielectric properties.

We pre-screen based on 4 ML-predicted quantities: thermodynamic stability (derived from predicted formation energy $E_"form"$), band gap $E_"gap"$, ionic permittivity $ϵ_"ionic"$ and electronic permittivity $ϵ_"elec"$.
Each property is predicted by a separate ensemble of 10 Wren models @goodall_rapid_2022 independently trained from random initializations to enable epistemic uncertainty estimation.
This allows us to both massively expand the search pool of initial candidates and waste fewer resources on unpromising compounds.

The total dielectric response of a material to a given electric field is largely determined by two mechanisms:

+ Electronic contributions $ϵ_"elec"$ due to *electron cloud distortion*, also frequently denoted $ϵ_oo$ since electrons have little mass and thus polarize quickly even in high-frequency electric fields ($~10^(15)thin$Hz)
+ Ionic contributions $ϵ_"ionic"$ due to *atomic displacements*, also frequently denoted $ϵ_0$ since ions have thousands of times greater mass, making atomic displacements more sluggish and only allowing their polarization to manifest in lower-frequency electric fields ($~10^(12)thin$Hz)

We found two separate ML ensembles to estimate the sum $ϵ_"tot" = ϵ_"ionic" + ϵ_"elec"$ in @eqn:fom to perform better than a single model predicting $ϵ_"tot"$ directly.

The formation energy and band gap training sets each contain #num-fmt(n-diel-train-mp-wbm) data points, the combination of #num-fmt(n-diel-train-mp) Materials Project (MP) @jain_commentary_2013 calculations and #num-fmt(n-diel-train-wbm) from the WBM dataset @wang_predicting_2021 which was generated with MP-compatible VASP settings.
The $ϵ_"ionic"$ and $ϵ_"elec"$ ensembles are trained on the much smaller dataset of #link("https://materialsproject.org/materials?has_props=dielectric")[#num-fmt(n-diel-dfpt-mp) DFPT calculations] in MP (#link("https://docs.materialsproject.org/changes/database-versions#v2020.09.08")[2020-09-08]) due to the lack of additional MP-compatible dielectric datasets (as far as we know).

#figure(
  image("figs/diel/drawio/discovery-workflow-build-step-5.svg", width: 100%),
  caption: [
    *Dielectric material discovery workflow integrating ML pre-screening, substitutionally-generated crystals and high-throughput DFPT validation.*
    The discovery pipeline can operate in two modes: screening and generation.
    Screening mode searches for large permittivity among known materials.
    In generation mode, we feed the top #si1[1k] MP structures by figure of merit ($Φ_M$) into a chemical-similarity-guided element substitution process.
  ],
)<fig:diel-discovery-workflow>

While simply screening materials within large ab-initio databases for which properties of interest have yet to be calculated is a viable strategy, it is also important to demonstrate the generative capabilities of ML-based workflows.
To this end, we identify the top #si1[1k] MP structures by figure of merit $Φ_M^"PBE" = ϵ_"tot"^"PBE" dot E_"gap"^"PBE"$ and use them as seed crystals for element substitution.
The expectation is that this generates novel structures with increased likelihood of high $Φ_M$.
The substitution process involves replacing all sites of one element in the structure with a chemically similar element (e.g. #ce("NaCl →[Na→K] KCl")), as determined by a similarity matrix mined from the ICSD @bergerhoff_inorganic_1983.
After filtering out duplicates (compositions that already exist in MP or WBM, i.e. we do not consider structural degrees of freedom) as well as compounds containing noble gases, lanthanides or actinides, we are left with #num-fmt(n-diel-generated) potential new dielectric materials.

Using the trained Wren ensembles, we predict $ϵ_"ionic"$ and $ϵ_"elec"$ for all candidates, both those sourced from high-throughput databases and those produced using our generative methodology, and $E_"form"$ and $E_"gap"$ for the latter where DFT values are not available.
We estimate the convex hull distance for each crystal from these predicted energies and discard those more than #si1[0.1eV/atom] above the hull.
This is motivated by the observation that 90% of crystals in ICSD are predicted to be less than #si4[0.067eV/atom] above the convex hull @sun_thermodynamic_2016.
This tolerance towards instability accounts for errors in DFT energies and the fact that some thermodynamically unstable materials are kinetically or entropically meta-stable and hence synthesizable.

The remaining candidates are ranked by their ML-predicted figure of merit $Φ_M^"Wren"$ and subjected to a high-throughput DFPT workflow as our computational budget permits, resulting in a database of #num-fmt(n-diel-dfpt-us) dielectric properties.

== Finding Dielectrics on the Computational Pareto Front
<sec:diel-computational-results>

The violin plot in @fig:our-diel-elec-vs-ionic-violin shows Gaussian kernel density estimates (KDE) of all #num-fmt(n-diel-dfpt-us) DFPT-computed electronic and ionic dielectric constants split by crystal system.
Unlike the electronic contribution which is lower-bounded by the vacuum permittivity, the ionic dielectric constant can be zero in all crystal systems.
We observe a general trend of higher dielectric constant the higher the crystal symmetry, especially for the ionic contribution.
Only cubic crystals reach significant electronic permittivity with a median of 10.

