== Band Gap Prediction Issues
<sec:band-gap-model-issues>

#figure(
  box(
    width: 110%,
    grid(
      columns: (1fr, 1fr),
      gutter: 1em,
      subfigure(
        image("figs/diel/rolling-bandgap+diel-error-pbe-as-x.svg"),
        caption: [RAE as a function of PBE band gap],
        label: <fig:rolling-bandgap-diel-error-pbe-as-x>,
      ),
      subfigure(
        image("figs/diel/rolling-bandgap+diel-error-wren-as-x.svg"),
        caption: [RAE as a function of Wren band gap],
        label: <fig:rolling-bandgap-diel-error-wren-as-x>,
      ),
    ),
  ),
  gap: 2em,
  caption: [
    *ML predictions are low in the target region of $E_"gap"^"PBE" > #si1[2eV]$ and $ϵ_"total"^"PBE" > 40$.*
    Rolling absolute error (RAE) of Wren band gap and dielectric constant predictions relative to DFPT.
  ],
)<fig:rolling-bandgap-diel-error>

Substantial challenges remain concerning band gap prediction, due in part to a metal-heavy dataset imbalance and in part to band gaps being an inherently challenging-to-model non-local property of the electronic rather than ionic structure.
This makes the prediction problem poorly, if not ill-defined for a coarse-grained structural model with no concept of electronic degrees of freedom.
We describe some attempts to mitigate this issue that achieved limited success but ultimately consider ML band gap prediction a high-impact but unsolved problem (see discussion @sec:diel-discussion).

Our ensemble of 10 Wren band gap models trained with L1 loss achieved a deceivingly low MAE = #si1[0.151eV] and a high coefficient of determination $R^2 = 0.969$.
This is largely due to the aforementioned dataset imbalance.
#num-fmt(n-diel-train-metals) / #num-fmt(n-diel-train-mp-wbm) = #percent(n-diel-train-metals / n-diel-train-mp-wbm) of the combined MP + WBM dataset are PBE metals.
Not wanting to discard 3/4 of our training data, we attempted naive equal loss weighting across all samples as well as increased loss weighting of non-metals.
Finally, we tried prepending a metal-nonmetal classifier to our band gap regressor to only predict the band gap for materials classified as non-metals.
While the latter slightly decreased the false-positive rate, neither managed to significantly improve the overall performance of our band gap model nor fix this main failure mode in our discovery pipeline of metals classified as insulators/semiconductors.
Many of the generated element substitution structures we predicted to have sizable band gaps turned out to be PBE metals.
More recent efforts in training foundation models on giant datasets and then fine-tuning on smaller cognate datasets @shoghi_molecules_2023 have achieved impressive sub-#si4[100meV/atom] band gap MAEs and may be able to overcome this issue.

@fig:rolling-bandgap-diel-error plots the rolling absolute error of our Wren band gap and dielectric constant ensembles with respect to DFPT using a variable window size of 300 samples.
In @fig:rolling-bandgap-diel-error-pbe-as-x, the bottom x-axis spans the range of PBE-computed band gaps for which we also have Wren predictions.
Similarly, the top x-axis spans the range of DFPT-computed dielectric constants for which we also have Wren predictions.
In @fig:rolling-bandgap-diel-error-wren-as-x, we swap the x-axis values to PBE instead.
That is Wren band gap predictions on the bottom x-axis and Wren dielectric constants on the top x-axis.
The y-axis is identical in both subplots: the rolling Wren-vs-DFPT absolute error for band gaps on the left and dielectric constants on the right.

@fig:rolling-bandgap-diel-error-pbe-as-x reveals that the error in the dielectric constant shows a pronounced dip at intermediate ranges from about 40 to 120.
This supports our initial argument for choosing dielectrics as the target material class for this discovery campaign.
We hypothesized that by optimizing the trade-off between two opposing material properties, we can operate both the dielectric and band gap models in regions of good training support where ML models are most reliable and still discover materials with high $Phi_"M"$.
In the case of the band gap model, this argument is less supported by the data.
While the error in band gap prediction indeed drops significantly in our target region of $E_"gap" > #si1[2eV]$, the error does not increase again for extreme values but stays low even for outlier points beyond #si1[5eV].
However, small errors on large band gaps do not negatively affect the chances of dielectric materials discovery and so are not in conflict with our objective.
The issue with the band gap model is that its error for small band gaps is >#si1[2eV] and therefore large enough to predict metals as insulators, thereby introducing false positives into our discovery pipeline.

@fig:rolling-bandgap-diel-error-wren-as-x reveals that our workflow suffered from a negative feedback loop in that we purposely selected materials with large band gaps according to Wren which drew the bulk of our selection towards the lower end of the blue line.
This line ends at a minimum band gap of #si1[2eV], indicating that no smaller Wren band gaps made it into our DFPT validation set.
However, this is precisely the region where model error and its prediction are almost equal, resulting in a large number of false positive insulator predictions that turned out to be PBE metals.

== Dynamic Stability Issues
<sec:dynamic-stability-issues>

#figure(
  grid(
    columns: (2fr, 1fr),
    rows: 1,
    gutter: 1em,
    image("figs/diel/min-phonon-freq-hist.svg"),
    stack(dir: ttb)[
      #image("figs/diel/mp-756175-phonon-freqs.svg")
      #image("figs/diel/mp-1225854-W-to-Te-phonon-freqs.svg")
    ],
  ),
  caption: [
    *Histogram of minimum phonon frequencies.*
    Negative frequencies should be interpreted as imaginary, i.e. dynamically unstable structures.
    The red dashed line indicates the dynamic stability threshold of $omega_"thresh" = -#si1[1meV] eq.est -#si4[0.242THz]$.
    Structures with minimum phonon frequency
  ],
)<fig:min-phonon-freq-hist>

Another significant failure mode in our workflow was the lack of dynamic instability filtering at the cheap ML stage.
Due to using Wren @goodall_accelerating_2022, an energy-only model, we did not have access to harmonic phonon spectra from ML force predictions.
Given Wren uses coarse-grained structural information for making energy predictions, its input features would either change discontinuously or, more often, remain unchanged when displacing atoms to obtain forces via finite differences.
Even without this technical limitation, given the issues we observed with phonons predicted by #chgnet, #m3gnet and #mace-mp in @sec:mlff-phonon-analysis, the quality of ML phonons from a model not trained on forces would likely be much worse, possibly to the point of doing no better than a dummy dynamic stability classifier.

In the present implementation of the workflow, we only have access to the eigenspectrum of the dynamical matrix for a given structure after the DFPT calculation.
At that point, the largest computational cost to screen a candidate material has already been incurred.
As shown in @fig:min-phonon-freq-hist, the lack of dynamic instability filtering resulted in only #n-diel-dfpt-dyn-stable out of #n-diel-dfpt-us DFPT calculations (#percent(n-diel-dfpt-dyn-stable / n-diel-dfpt-us)) being performed on dynamically stable structures.

This is a major flaw of the present workflow implementation and could have been avoided by opting for a force model like #m3gnet for the ML-filtering stage from the start.
While #chgnet and #mace-mp came to be after the computational part of this project was completed, #m3gnet pre-dates the start of this work (both 2022).
In hindsight, #m3gnet would have been a much better choice of model but was insufficiently considered since the performance gap between #m3gnet and Wren demonstrated by #mbd was not yet known nor anticipated by us.
In fact, part of the goal of this dielectric discovery workflow was to demonstrate the utility of coarse-grained structural models like Wren for accelerating materials discovery.
This hypothesis was severely undermined by #mbd which found ML force fields to be both superior for PES exploration and more versatile than energy-only models.

This project outcome serves as a cautionary tale of embarking on long projects with false preconceptions poorly challenged due to insufficient methodological exploration.
Favoring the familiar over the unknown may also have played a role.
Wren was developed "in-house" by Rhys Goodall, myself and Rokas Elijosius whereas we had little experience with #m3gnet at the time.
The decision to use Wren was partially motivated by our false assumption at the time that ML potentials like #m3gnet trained largely on the near-equilibrium structures in MP (where even the relaxation starting points, i.e. the highest-force configurations, are experimental ICSD ground state structures) would not be able to accurately extrapolate to unseen and unrelaxed structures generated by element substitution.
The lesson learned is to perform more comprehensive method testing before committing significant computational resources to a new workflow.
Discovery efforts should not be driven by the motivation to prove the benefits of a particular method but should commit significant effort to explore the best available tools for the task at hand before entering the high-throughput phase.
It also highlights the importance of #mbd which cured us of the misconception that coarse-grained structural energy-only models could be competitive with force models for PES exploration.

Fortunately, not much needs to change in the current workflow to incorporate a force model like #mace-mp which we showed in @sec:mlff-phonon-analysis to achieve better than 80% dynamic stability classification accuracy (with respect to PhononDB PBE reference data @togo_firstprinciples_2023 @togo_implementation_2023).
While outperforming #chgnet (65%) and #m3gnet (70%), all 3 models outperform a random binary classifier and could potentially be combined into a committee classifier with even higher accuracy.

Assuming the #percent(n-diel-dfpt-dyn-stable / n-diel-dfpt-us) dynamic stability ratio we observed is a base rate that holds generally when substitutionally-generating structures, and further assuming such a committee classifier would have a #percent(0.1) false stable rate (1 percentage point better than #mace-mp alone, see @fig:imaginary-freq-conf-mats), we could potentially reduce the number of DFPT calculations on dynamically unstable structures from #percent(1 - n-diel-dfpt-dyn-stable / n-diel-dfpt-us) to #percent((1 - n-diel-dfpt-dyn-stable / n-diel-dfpt-us) * 0.1, precision: 2).
Thus, we expect using universal MLFFs for dynamical instability filtering could almost invert the #n-diel-dfpt-dyn-stable / #num-fmt(n-diel-dfpt-us - n-diel-dfpt-dyn-stable) stable-to-unstable ratio we obtained in the present work at the cost of a few extra minutes of compute time per material on a laptop.
We are eager to test this in future work.

To what extent the imaginary frequencies of #BZO (#mp-link[mp-756175]) and #CTTO (#mp-link[mp-1225854]$thin:$W→Te) in @fig:min-phonon-freq-hist are indicative of ferroelectricity requires further investigation.
The discrepancy between DFPT and synthesized structures may disappear under a displacive symmetry-lowering ferroelectric phase transition.
However, given that imaginary modes associated with dynamic instabilities are anharmonic, a quantitative description would require moving beyond the harmonic approximation @pallikara_physical_2022.
// TODO! use chargemol (e.g. in pymatgen) to confirm that neither mp-756175 nor mp-1225854 have a dipole moment, i.e. are non-polar.
Given neither structure appears to be polar, future work could search for unstable phonon modes that lead to a stable polar structure, a signature for ferroelectricity @markov_ferroelectricity_2021.

== Discussion
<sec:diel-discussion>

We have implemented and run a high-throughput workflow for dielectric materials discovery that combines data-driven and first-principles methods to efficiently navigate the vast space of possible dielectric materials while balancing multiple material properties for optimal device performance.
We show in @tab:diel-hit-rate-comparison that this combination achieves improved enrichment of materials that satisfy $Φ_M = ϵ_"tot" dot E_"gap" > #si1[240eV]$ than ab-initio methods alone.

By deploying this workflow into practice, we identified and synthesized two candidate materials, #CTTO and #BZO.
We performed Rietveld analysis to identify the synthesized structures, finding different polymorphs than the structures produced by the workflow, possibly due to the oversight of neglecting dynamic stability filtering, although entropic and defect effects may also play a role which are much harder to account for in a high-throughput workflow.
We nonetheless went on to measure band gaps and dielectric properties of both synthesized samples.
#BZO shows strong promise for electronic applications given its measured band gap of #si4[2.27eV], dielectric constant of 20.5 and its relatively available constituent elements.
#CTTO is a black semiconductor with a low band gap of #si4[1.05eV] and dielectric constant of 26, making it unsuitable for electronic applications.
#CTTO was substitutionally generated with no prior entries with this formula or even this chemical system in the ICSD or #link("https://materialsproject.org/materials?elements=Cs%2CTa%2CTe%2CO")[MP].
We thus demonstrated successful de novo synthesis on a challenging metastable phase and established a reference point for the dielectric properties of similar materials in this largely unexplored region of chemical space.
Attempting metastable synthesis in an unknown chemical system is a high-risk undertaking, and the successful synthesis of #CTTO demonstrates the benefits computational guidance can offer experiment.
This experimental outcome serves as an early signal that ML-driven stability and property prediction has matured enough in reliability to warrant inclusion in complex multi-step workflows such as ours.

However, two major failure modes negatively impacted the hit rate of high-$Φ_M$ materials in this work.
#pad(x: 1em)[
  + *Inaccurate band gaps* from the Wren ensemble caused a high false-positive insulator rate, predicting many generated structures as insulators which turned out to be PBE metals.
  + Lack of *dynamic instability filtering* at the ML stage due to unavailable phonon predictions from Wren.
]

Dynamic instability is straightforward to remedy.
A future iteration of this workflow could use one of the top-performing force models from #mbd such as #mace-mp which not only provide more accurate energies but also allow filtering for unstable phonon modes at negligible compute cost (2 -- 5 minutes on a laptop for most materials vs many hours with DFPT on a cluster).
This would simultaneously reduce the number of false positives at an early stage of the workflow and provide a significant speedup, allowing for more materials to be screened for a given compute budget.
The reason we did not do so here is largely chronological.
This project started before we produced #mbd results.
At the time, the performance gap between energy-only models and ML potentials was not yet clear to us (as detailed in @sec:dynamic-stability-issues).

The band gap prediction issue on the other hand is less straightforward to solve.
We consider accurate band gap models to be an unsolved problem in materials informatics and encourage more efforts be directed at it.
However, two recent works may offer significant improvements in this area.

- #mattergen @zeni_mattergen_2023[fig.~5b], a generative diffusion model, demonstrated an impressive ability to condition structure generation on band gaps much larger than the mode of its training set.
  #mattergen's training set is sharply peaked at $E_"gap"^"PBE" = 0$ with only long-tail, minuscule coverage of #si1[3eV] and higher band gaps, yet its distribution of generated structures impressively achieved a mode at the band gap target of #si1[3eV].
- Ref.~@shoghi_molecules_2023[table~4] demonstrates that pre-training on a large dataset of diverse materials prediction tasks can significantly improve band gap prediction accuracy on the Matbench $E_"gap"^"MP"$ task, reaching sub-#si4[100meV/atom] MAE after pre-training on many large but non-cognate tasks.
  This suggests current model architectures combined with large data curation and pre-training efforts can already achieve sufficiently accurate band gap predictions to significantly improve the hit rate of high-$Φ_M$ materials in our workflow.

Models that predict a spectrum rather than a single scalar offer another promising avenue to pursue.
Mat2Spec @kong_density_2021 proposed circumventing direct band gap prediction in favor of predicting the electronic density of states (eDOS).
This allows inferring the band gap from the DOS and opens the door to more nuanced loss functions as well as increased regularization during training similar to how including forces in the loss function can regularize energy predictions.
Sufficiently complex models with good inductive bias may learn more subtle features of the electronic structure from this approach than a direct band gap predictor.
It should be noted, however, that Mat2Spec refrained from reporting the accuracy of band gaps inferred from their eDOS predictions, likely indicating more work is required to unlock such benefits.
In summary, while it was not the main focus of this work, we believe there remains urgent need for improving ML band gap predictions.

However, the challenge of predicting band gaps in our workflow is not restricted to ML.
It also applies to DFT.
In the case of #CTTO, PBE exhibits an unusual severe overestimation $E_"gap"^"PBE" > #si4[2.09eV]$ of the experimental band gap of $E_"gap"^"exp" = #si4[1.05eV]$.
While defect chemistry may play a role in this effect, there are obvious computing limitations in a high-throughput workflow, making the simulation of defect effects cost-prohibitive.
Possible improvements to narrow the gap between simulation and reality include incorporating a third computational filter to the funnel directly preceding experiment in the form of a hybrid functional such as HSE or HSE@$$GGA @yim_novel_2015.
The latter only uses HSE to calculate energy levels at the band-edge $k$-points identiﬁed by GGA to lower cost.
HSE@$$GGA assumes the band structure undergoes only a rigid shift from GGA to HSE which is often a good approximation.
In either case, HSE would only be applied sparingly to compounds that have passed ML and PBE filters but before attempting experimental synthesis, thus keeping computational cost manageable while reducing false positives at the lab stage.

Given our workflow -- despite its current limitations -- nonetheless managed to result in the successful synthesis of materials with decent dielectric constants is cause for optimism about the potential for more meaningful discoveries in the future.
In particular, combining #mattergen$$-like high-band-gap structure generation with #mace-mp dynamic stability filtering and HSE@$$GGA band gap prediction should make for a powerful dielectric materials discovery pipeline.

