== Introduction
<sec:mace-mp-intro>

DFT is perhaps the most successful tool for materials modeling to date @kohn_selfconsistent_1965 @giannozzi_quantum_2020 @kuhne_cp2k_2020 @kresse_initio_1993 @hasnip_density_2014 @jain_computational_2016 @neugebauer_density_2013 due to its attractive placement on the cost-accuracy Pareto front.
However, the cubic scaling of compute cost with system size -- while better than other ab-initio methods with comparable or higher accuracy -- still renders simulations of thousands of atoms prohibitively expensive.
These include important use cases such as amorphous solids, condensed phase liquids, nanostructured materials, battery systems, and more.

Fast empirical interatomic potentials (force fields) have existed for years @finnis_interatomic_2003 and provide an alternative option with varying accuracy-generalization trade-offs.
Yet they often fail to match DFT accuracy, especially around reactive events and phase transitions @senftle_reaxff_2016.
Consequently, DFT has remained the main workhorse for materials simulation.

Recent years saw the rise of narrow ML interatomic potentials, custom-trained for a particular material or system, which compared to empirical force fields achieve significant accuracy gains at moderate increase in cost @behler_generalized_2007 @bartok_gaussian_2010 @thompson_spectral_2015 @schutt_schnet_2018 @deringer_machine_2019 @drautz_atomic_2019 @batzner_equivariant_2022 @ko_recent_2023.
Their main drawback is the significant time and human effort needed to generate bespoke training sets (usually from DFT reference data) when then used for model training and validation which are equally time-consuming and need to be repeated for each material class of interest @deringer_gaussian_2021.
This recurring upfront data curation cost that must be paid for every new chemical system is a major inhibitor to their widespread adoption and use by non-experts.

It would mark an important milestone in the lineage of work started nearly two decades ago by #cite(<behler_generalized_2007>, form: "prose") if we succeeded at training a single model whose compute cost scales linearly with system size yet accurately describes the potential energy surface (PES) across all chemical and structural spaces.
This would enable reliable molecular dynamics (MD) simulations over unprecedented time scales and system sizes, opening up the immediate study of important physical processes that can only be studied in all-atom simulations of systems containing many thousands of atoms.
These include vexing problems that have inhibited our understanding and resisted the rapid improvement of more performant sustainability-related materials such as metal-organic frameworks for direct air capture or solid-electrolyte interphases for increasing cycle life of batteries.
Even though the physical laws that govern their behavior were discovered a century ago @dirac_quantum_1929, actually simulating the outcome of these laws for large systems or over long-time scales needed for complex chemical reaction processes remains inaccessible to DFT even with today's largest computers.

Hence there is an urgent need to develop computational tools that retain most of the accuracy and versatility of DFT yet ideally achieve linear scaling of compute cost with system size.
The #megnet model published in 2019 @chen_graph_2019 marked an important first step in the direction of ML foundation models that could satisfy these lofty requirements.
#megnet enabled predicting various properties including band gaps, elastic moduli and most importantly formation energies of diverse inorganic crystals from having trained on the PBE @perdew_rationale_1996 ground states of $~#si1[60k]$ materials covering all 89 elements present in the Materials Project (MP).

== Related Work
<sec:mace-mp-related-work>

#m3gnet @chen_universal_2022 (#cite(<chen_universal_2022>, form: "year")) and #chgnet @deng_chgnet_2023 (#cite(<deng_chgnet_2023>, form: "year")) were important next milestones.
These are $E(3)$-invariant GNN potentials with the ability to predict not only energies but also forces from having trained on snapshots of MP PBE structure relaxations.

The proprietary #gnome @merchant_scaling_2023 (NequIP architecture @batzner_equivariant_2022) which currently ranks SOTA on #mbd (see @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos-with-closed) also starts from MP data (as well as OQMD @saal_materials_2013 @kirklin_open_2015), but uses a complex active learning workflow to generate and iteratively train on a dataset of inorganic crystals nearly two orders of magnitude larger than #mptrj (thus making the results more an indication of what's possible with current architectures and data generation capabilities than something a regular research group can aspire to).

The above models were designed and trained primarily with materials discovery in mind, i.e. predicting thermodynamic stability of hypothetical crystals.
In addition, the force fields are useful drivers for molecular dynamics.
In fact, #chgnet and #gnome were both used to study alkali metal ion diffusion in battery materials.

Another contender for the most general and transferable force field currently in existence is the PFP model @takamoto_towards_2022 from #link("https://matlantis.com")[Matlantis] (TeaNet architecture @takamoto_teanet_2022) which is also proprietary.
Its training set was recently expanded from 45 to 72 elements and at #si0[20M] structures is more than an order of magnitude larger than MP, while also comprising large numbers of molecules and surfaces.
PFP was shown to be able to simulate dynamics in solid-state ionic conductors, molecular adsorption and heterogeneous catalysis.

A largely separate lineage of ML force fields specialized for organic molecules (containing a much more limited set of elements comprising mainly C, H, N, O later extended to anions F, Cl, and S) is the ANI (and later AimNET) series of models @smith_ani1_2017 @smith_approaching_2019 @zubatyuk_accurate_2019.

#figure(
  image("figs/mace-mp/applications.svg"),
  caption: [
    *#mace-mp is an unexpectedly versatile foundation model for materials simulation*.
    Trained only on the DFT relaxations of #si0(n-mp-entries) Materials Project structures @jain_commentary_2013 which comprise almost entirely of inorganic crystals heavily dominated by oxides, #mace-mp can nonetheless drive molecular dynamics and other types of simulation across various chemistries in solid, liquid and gaseous phases.
    Reproduced from @riebesell_foundation_2023 with permission.
  ],
)<fig:mace-mp-sun>

However, the field has yet to deliver a comprehensive demonstration that a single ML potential can describe solid, liquid, and gaseous systems of materials and molecules across the periodic table and well beyond the training set distribution.
This chapter presents #mace-mp, a new foundational interatomic potential that we thoroughly analyzed and benchmarked in a large collaborative effort involving over 70 co-authors and 36 test cases that we believe comes close to such a demonstration @riebesell_foundation_2023.
Built on the MACE force field architecture @batatia_mace_2023 and trained on the same #mptrj dataset curated for and released with #chgnet, we demonstrate its capabilities on an unprecedented range of qualitative and quantitative examples drawn from diverse areas of computational chemistry and materials science, including running stable molecular dynamics simulations in a wide variety of chemistries, predicting phonon spectra, calculating activation energies for point defect and dislocation motion, simulating solvent mixtures, combusting hydrogen gas, modeling a complete rechargeable battery cell, amorphous carbon, and much more; the sheer breadth of applications we found the model able to handle is illustrated in @fig:mace-mp-sun.
We find that this pre-trained _foundation model_ exhibits remarkable zero-shot out-of-distribution performance, making it an all the more promising starting point for fine-tuning for specific applications needed by different modeling communities.

While the complete analysis of this model spanning more than 100 pages in @riebesell_foundation_2023 is too extensive to be reproduced here in its entirety, we instead focus on the parts of the analysis that I led or contributed to.
These include the phonon spectra and elastic moduli benchmarks and the zero-shot OOD formation energy predictions.
The medium-sized #si1(n-mace-medium-params)-parameter MACE model used throughout this paper cost $~#si1(2600)$ Nvidia A100 GPU hours to train.
Compared to the smallest #si1(n-mace-small-params) and largest #si1(n-mace-large-params) parameter models we trained, medium offers the best cost-accuracy tradeoff.

== Training Protocol
<sec:mace-mp-training>

The core piece of the #mace-mp pre-trained interatomic potentials are multi-body message passing (interaction) layers.
In each layer, the message is encoded in an irreducible representation basis with $C$ channels up to an angular frequency of order $L$.
This is specified as `(128x0e+128x1o+128x2e)` for $C = 128$ channels and $L = 2$.

In each batch updating step, the weighted sum of Huber losses~@huber_robust_1992
of energy, forces, and stress incurred by all structures in a batch are
averaged and back-propagated to update the model parameters.
For a given batch size $N_b$ and number of atoms in each structure $N_a$, the full loss function reads

$
  cal(L)
  = lambda_E / N_b sum_(b=1)^(N_b)cal(L)_("Huber")(hat(E)_b / N_a, E_b / N_a, delta_E)
  + lambda_F / (3sum_(b=1)^(N_b)N_a) sum_(b=1)^(N_b) sum_(a=1)^(N_a)sum_(i=1)^(3) cal(L)^star_("Huber")(
    (diff hat(E)_b) / (diff r_(b,a,i)), F_(b,a,i), delta_F
  ) \
  + lambda_sigma / (9N_b) sum_(b=1)^(N_b) sum_(i=1)^(3) sum_(j=1)^(3) cal(L)_("Huber")(
    1 / V_b (diff hat(E)_b) / (diff ϵ_(b,i j)), sigma_(b,i j), delta_sigma
  ),
$<eqn:mace-mp-loss>

where $lambda_E, lambda_F, lambda_sigma$ can be used to control the relative importance placed on energy, forces, and stress losses.
We chose $(lambda_E, lambda_F, lambda_sigma) = (1, 10, 100)$ and trained for 200 epochs.
The energy fine-tuned small model ("small-energy") is subsequently trained for another 50 epochs with an increased emphasis on energy loss $(lambda_E, lambda_F, lambda_sigma) = (10, 1, 100)$.
We used Huber deltas $delta_E = delta_F = delta_sigma = 0.01$.
For forces, we use a conditional Huber loss $cal(L)_"Huber"^star.op$ where the Huber delta $delta_F$ is adaptive to the force magnitude on each atom.
Specifically, $delta_F$ decreases step-wise by a factor from 1.0 to 0.1 as the atomic force increases from 0 to #si4[300eV/Å].
In other words, the force Huber loss is defined as:

$
  cal(L)_"Huber"^star.op ((diff hat(E)_b) / (diff r_(b,a,i)), F_(b,a,i), delta_F)
  = cases(
  cal(L)_"Huber" (..., delta_F) & wide "if" med F_(b,a,i) < 100\
  cal(L)_"Huber" (..., 0.7 delta_F) & wide "if" med 100 lt.eq F_(b,a,i) < 200\
  cal(L)_"Huber" (..., 0.4 delta_F) & wide "if" med 200 lt.eq F_(b,a,i) < 300\
  cal(L)_"Huber" (..., 0.1 delta_F) & wide "if" med F_(b,a,i) gt.eq 300
)
$<eqn:loss-huber-force>

