Standardization of target variables (here energies, forces and stresses) with different scales has been proven to be important for weight initialization and training stability @bishop_neural_1995, in that a large spread of input or output will result in large and uneven weight values and cause model instability and slow convergence.
After each message passing layer $k$, the node energies $ϵ_a$ are scaled and shifted before sum pooling.
The energy prediction of each structure therefore reads:

$
  hat(E)
  = sum_(a = 1)^N [sigma (sum_(k = 1)^K ϵ_a^((k))) + mu_(Z_a)],
$<eqn:energy-pred>

where $K$ denotes the total number of message passing layers and $ϵ_a^((k))$ is the node energy of atom $a$ at layer $k$.
$mu_Z$ and $sigma$ are the mean of atomic energies and the root mean square (RMS) of the atomic forces computed over the training dataset.
The predicted forces and stress are computed through PyTorch's @paszke_pytorch_2019 automatic differentiation `torch.autograd` of total energy with respect to atomic positions and lattice strain tensor.
The models are trained for 200 epochs with 40 -- 80 NVIDIA A100 GPUs across 10 -- 20 nodes with 4 GPUs each on the Perlmutter Cray EX supercomputer operated by the National Energy Research Scientific Computing Center (NERSC) at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL).
The change in validation metrics during training is shown in @fig:mace-mp-train-val-curves.
The total number of GPU hours used for training the medium model analyzed here was about $~#si1(2600)$.

== Phonon Analysis
<sec:mlff-phonon-analysis>

#let phonon-analysis-mp-ids = csv("figs/phonons/phonon-analysis-mp-ids.csv")

#remark[
  I led the work in this section, performed all the calculations, generated the figures (including interactive phonon band structure and DOS figures implemented with `plotly` in `pymatviz` @riebesell_pymatviz_2022), drafted the initial text and extended the analysis to cover 3x more materials (97 → #phonon-analysis-mp-ids.len()) after #mace-mp @riebesell_foundation_2023 appeared as a preprint.
  I would like to thank Janine George and Aakash A. Naik at Federal Institute of Materials Research and Testing (BAM), Berlin, Germany for guidance and help with ingesting PhononDB PBE data as well as convergence testing of their VASP parameters in confirming reference data quality.
]

This section presents an in-depth comparison of phonon predictions from #mace-mp, #chgnet and #m3gnet.
Phonons (from the Greek word for sound) are quasiparticles that describe the collective vibrations of atoms in a periodic crystal.
The phonon spectrum measures the energy of such vibrations as a function of atomic momenta.
It gives a complete description of possible collective vibrations of atoms for a given crystal lattice.
The discrete energy levels such sound waves can acquire turn into a multitude of continuous bands when plotted in reciprocal space as in @fig:mace-pbe-phonon-comparison.
This so-called phonon band structure is an information-dense representation of the crystal's vibrational energy spectrum.
Lattice vibrations of crystals underpin many application-relevant material properties, including volumetric and constant-pressure heat capacities, electrical and thermal conductivity, thermal expansion and speed of sound.
In addition, phonons are key to describing physical phenomena such as phase transitions @cowley_acoustic_1976 @krumhansl_structural_1989, superconductivity @giustino_electronphonon_2017 @ziman_electrons_2001 and ferroelectricity @kristoffel_electronphonon_1973 @yildirim_ferroelectric_2013 which all play critical roles in many materials applications.
But most relevant to this work and crystal stability prediction more generally, the phonon spectrum also encodes the dynamic stability of crystals as well as entropic contributions $S_"vib"$ to the free energy $A = U - T S$ @baroni_phonons_2001 @stoffel_initio_2010 @bartel_review_2022 where $S = S_"vib" + S_"config"$ is the sum of vibrational and configurational entropy.
Hypothetical crystal structures may exhibit lattice vibrations whereby atoms can lower their energy by gaining momentum.
That would mean the crystal flows apart by displacing atoms in real space along the corresponding vibrational eigenvector, thereby transforming into a different crystal structure that inhabits a lower-energy saddle point or the true ground state of the free energy surface.
Such dynamically unstable crystals cannot be realized experimentally and should be filtered out when attempting synthesis of novel structures to avoid wasted effort.
Thus we view phonon analysis as a natural continuation of #mbd for measuring the ability of ML to accelerate materials stability prediction by accounting for previously neglected modes of crystal instability.
In contrast to #link(<sec:mbd>, mbd) which considered only thermodynamic stability, benchmarking MLFFs on phonons allows progressing from a zero Kelvin energy surface to a free energy surface that enables a more holistic assessment of stability.
Finally, finding that MLFFs can accurately model phonons would simultaneously open the door to directly validate ML against many new experimental results in various materials science domains by comparing ML-predicted thermal expansion, speed of sound, etc. to observed values.

=== Brief Primer on Phonons
<sec:phonon-primer>

Phonons are quanta of atomic vibrations in a crystal lattice and measure the curvature of the energy surface.
The connection to curvature becomes apparent through the dynamical matrix $matrix(omega)$ which consists of the second derivative of the PES with respect to displacement of ionic positions in all possible directions:

$
  omega_(i j)
  = 1 / (sqrt(m_i m_j #v(8pt))) (diff^2 E) / (diff vector(u)_i diff vector(u)_j)
$<eqn:dynamical-matrix>

where $m_i$ is the mass of atom $i$, $vector(u)_i = (u_x, u_y, u_z)$ is its displacement and $E$ is the potential energy and its second derivative gives the local PES curvature in different atom displacement directions.
$matrix(omega)$ is a $3N times 3N$ matrix ($N$ is the number of atoms) whose eigenvalues $omega_(vector(q)nu)^2$ are the squares of the phonon frequencies and whose eigenvectors $vector(q)$ are called the phonon modes (or just phonons).
As such, they may constitute a higher fidelity test for the quality of an ML force field than #mbd which restricted PES evaluation to forces (first derivative of $E$) needed for relaxation and reading of the PES value at the relaxed geometry (zeroth derivative of $E$).

The eigenvalues $omega_(vector(q)nu)$ can be positive or negative depending on whether the local energy surface curves upwards or downwards.
Positive eigenvalues correspond to a quadratic increase in energy with atomic displacement, while negative eigenvalues indicate a decrease in energy when displacing atoms along the vibration's corresponding eigenvector $vector(q)$.
At a local minimum of the PES, all eigenvalues are positive, whereas at a saddle point, most eigenvalues are positive, except for those associated with energy-lowering directions.

Since phonon frequencies are the square root of the eigenvalues of $matrix(omega)$, they must be either positive real numbers or purely imaginary #footnote[In band structure plots such as @fig:bs-dos-pbe-vs-mace-mp-2998, imaginary frequencies are plotted as negative numbers for convenience but $y$-axis labels should be read as $-1 arrow i, -2 arrow 2i, ...$].

We suspect phonons may offer a higher fidelity test for the quality of ML potentials compared to methods that restrict PES testing to forces (first derivative) needed for relaxation and the PES value at the relaxed geometry (zeroth derivative) such as #mbd.

=== Methodology
<sec:phonon-methodology>

Harmonic (non-interacting) phonons can be calculated from the restoring force on atomic displacements and require highly accurate force predictions to be physical, making them a sensitive test for the fidelity of ML potentials.
A model trained on PBE forces should be able to reproduce PBE lattice vibrations~@george_combining_2020 @morrow_how_2023.
To assess the accuracy of #mace-mp restoring forces, we compare phonon modes predicted via the finite-displacement method as implemented in `Phonopy`~@togo_first_2015 @togo_firstprinciples_2023 @togo_implementation_2023 and `atomate2`~@ganose_atomate2_2024 with the Togo phonon database @togo_firstprinciples_2023 @togo_implementation_2023.
We restrict our analysis to materials in which magnetism and U-correction do not play a role since the Togo database was calculated at the PBE level of theory but without consideration of magnetism or U-corrections and so will be at odds with the model's MP training data which uses said corrections for such systems.
Additional inaccuracies in the comparison may stem from unconverged kinetic energy cutoffs of the plane-wave expansion or insufficient $k$-point density.
Based on our analysis, Togo DB calculations used the VASP-recommended sufficiently high kinetic energy cutoff ($1.3thin dot thin$`ENMAX` of the highest `ENMAX` indicated in a compound's pseudopotential files for the PAW method).
In most cases, the reciprocal $k$-point density used matches that of `MPRelaxSet` for structure optimization and force calculations.
However, some reciprocal $k$-point densities are slightly lower compared to `MPRelaxSet` by $29 ± 15$ points for structure optimization and $35 ± 21$ points for force calculations.
These are small deviations, leading us to conclude PhononDB results serve as reasonable high-throughput reference data for an MLFF phonon analysis.
To minimize the discrepancy between ML and Togo results, we simulate identical supercells.
In addition, we remove the non-analytic corrections derived from Born charges which are unavailable from ML potentials with no concept of polarization.#footnote[
  The polarization and resulting Born effective charges can in principle be learned by current MLFFs by adding external perturbations such as electric and magnetic fields to the model input and including response properties such as electric/magnetic enthalpy, polarization and Born charges in the loss function.
  An impressive demonstration of this recently appeared in @falletta_unified_2024 but much more DFT training data at non-zero external fields needs to be generated before a model with the chemical scope of #mace-mp and an understanding of external perturbations can be trained.
]
These corrections could be obtained even without changes to the model by a hybrid workflow that performs a DFT static calculation on the MLFF-relaxed structure to obtain Born effective charges and posthoc apply the resulting non-analytic corrections to the MLFF phonon spectrum.
Since we are mainly interested in the part of the phonon spectrum the model *can* predict in order to gain an understanding of the fidelity of #mace-mp restorative forces, we did not pursue this more involved workflow.
However, we hope to soon provide an off-the-shelf implementation of this hybrid workflow compatible with all force fields in `atomate2` @ganose_atomate2_2024 (currently #chgnet, #mace-mp, #m3gnet, GAP, #nequip and #sevennet).
Both MP @jain_commentary_2013 and PhononDB @togo_firstprinciples_2023 provide phonons for several thousand compounds, calculated with density functional perturbation theory (DFPT) and frozen phonons, respectively.
Unfortunately, both databases opted to use the #pbe-sol functional for their phonon calculations, introducing a systematic error when benchmarking models trained on PBE data.
#pbe-sol phonon spectra tend to be slightly stretched compared to PBE, i.e. high frequencies in particular are slightly higher with #pbe-sol due to stiffer bonds.
As such any underpredictions, especially of the highest frequency modes, cannot be purely attributed to model error.
However, the error contribution from systematic differences between PBE forces seen during training and #pbe-sol forces giving rise to the reference phonon spectra is likely small.
While DFPT and the frozen phonon method using the same flavor of DFT should in principle give comparable results, we chose PhononDB as our source of reference data to eliminate another potential source of systematic discrepancy, however minor, between reference data and model predictions.

