@fig:imaginary-freq-conf-mats shows confusion matrices for the presence of imaginary frequencies at any $q$-point as predicted by #mace-mp, #chgnet and #m3gnet compared with PhononDB PBE reference data.
// @fig:imaginary-gamma-freq-conf-mats shows the same for imaginary frequencies at the $Gamma$ point only, which correspond to stationary lattice vibrations with zero net momentum.
We use a tolerance of #si4(num-mode: "format")[0.01THz], meaning any phonon modes above #si4(num-mode: "format")[-0.01THz] are not considered imaginary to account for numerical imprecision.
For example, phonon modes of #si4[−0.09THz] would not be considered dynamically unstable while #si4[-0.11THz] would.
Using those settings yields an imbalanced classification task biased towards dynamic instability with 68% of PBE phonons containing imaginary modes and 62% at the $Gamma$ point.
The confusion matrices are colored white for low values and dark blue for high values.
Optimal performance corresponds to dark blue on the diagonals and white on the off-diagonals.

Surprisingly, there is a much larger performance gap in the accuracy of predicting the presence of imaginary modes between #mace-mp and #chgnet than what we observed in #mbd for stability prediction (see @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos).
#mace-mp achieves an accuracy of 81% for predicting the presence of imaginary frequencies.
This compares to 65% and 57% for #chgnet.
Even #m3gnet which performed noticeably worse in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos outperforms #chgnet on imaginary phonon modes by a meaningful margin, achieving 70% and 67% accuracy for the same tasks.
Looking at the top right quadrant in both #chgnet confusion matrices, we can localize #chgnet's failure mode to a high false unstable rate of $~40%$.
In other words, #chgnet predicts #percent(103/phonon-analysis-mp-ids.len(), precision: 0) of structures as dynamically unstable that are PBE-stable (@fig:chgnet-imag-freq-conf-mat).
This is a much higher false unstable rate than #m3gnet (29% and 24%) and even more so compared to #mace-mp (8% and 8%).
It is currently unclear why #chgnet is strongly biased towards false unstable phonons given that it was trained on a larger dataset and performed better at materials discovery than #m3gnet.
Work is ongoing on a more comprehensive phonon analysis that may shed light on this discrepancy.

