However, while #mace-mp errors are generally smaller and more frequently include overpredictions of phonon frequencies, in general, all models exhibit the same systematic error direction of typically underestimating the bandwidth.
This observation is not limited to phonon predictions but rather one example of many across several projects indicating a more general trend that ML force fields over-soften the PES (i.e. underestimate the forces they were trained on), highlighting a broader unresolved issue in the ML force field design and training methodology.
For many more examples of PES softening, we refer the reader to @riebesell_foundation_2023[esp. secs.~2.1 on water, A.1 on self interstitials, A.2 on amorphous silicon, A.13 on metal defects, A.14 on bulk diffusion, A.25 on carborane barrier heights, A.26 on transition metal dichalcogenides, B.1 on phonons].
We suspect addressing this issue will lead to more reliable ML force fields with enhanced general applicability.
In this case, the MAE can be lowered to between $~1$ and $~#si4[2THz]$ by applying a constant 'PES-stiffening' shift that uniformly moves all predicted frequencies up by $~1 - #si4[3THz]$.

Despite this limitation, the acceptable MAEs and high $R^2$ in this zero-shot test are encouraging.
They indicate significant potential for ML force fields to become accurate universal bandwidth predictors.

