Highly specialized models for one element can achieve much lower errors of 0.1 -- #si4[0.2THz] over the whole band structure @george_combining_2020.
#mace-mp, let alone #chgnet or #m3gnet, in their current form are far from achieving such accuracy.
However, the deviations are close to results from models that specifically train only on the highest phonon peak on MatBench @dunn_benchmarking_2020.
Here, the best models arrive at mean absolute errors of 0.8 -- #si4[1THz] for the last phonon DOS peak, which is a similar but _not_ identical quantity to the bandwidth.
The highest phonon peak is usually slightly but sometimes a lot smaller than the bandwidth.
It's worth reiterating that neither #mace-mp nor its training data was tailored in any way for phonon predictions.
Even so, MLFF phonon band structures, especially those of #mace-mp, achieve at least qualitative agreement with PBE for most materials, which can be sufficient for many practical applications (e.g. models that screen for low or high thermal conductivity @agne_minimum_2018).

While #mace-mp's dynamic stability classification accuracy of 81% (@fig:imaginary-freq-conf-mats) outperforms dummy accuracy of 50%, it also leaves room for improvement.
This is even more true for #chgnet and #m3gnet.
However, given its low compute cost and general applicability, #mace-mp as-is can already serve as a useful pre-screening filter for dynamically unstable materials.
Generating a complete phonon band structure on an Apple M2 Max CPU takes approximately #si1[30s].
Running #mace-mp on a supercomputer could easily generate approximate phonon bands for every material in MP or other large databases.
That said, #mace-mp harmonic phonons should not be used for more than pre-screening as current accuracy is far below what would be needed to reliably replace DFT.

A caveat to the above analysis is that the PBE unstable labels we use as ground truth may themselves contain false positives.
That is, any unconverged values of `ENCUT` and $k$-point density may result in incorrect dynamically unstable PBE labels that would stabilize by reaching numerical convergence.

All data and code for this phonon analysis is available at https://github.com/janosh/ffonons.
The code was written in a model-agnostic way and works with any predictor that conforms to the #link("https://wiki.fysik.dtu.dk/ase/ase/calculators/calculators.html")[ASE `Calculator` API] @larsen_atomic_2017.

== #mace-mp vs #gnome Relaxed Volume of Highly Coordinated Structures
<sec:mace-mp-vs-gnome-relaxed-volume>

#remark[
  Work in this section was led by #link("https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=6AyF1U8AAAAJ")[Aaron D. Kaplan] at Materials Sciences Division, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, USA.
  I offered guidance, reproduced and checked the results and edited the text.
]

The recently published #gnome database @merchant_scaling_2023 contains $~#num-fmt(381000)$ thermodynamically stable crystals which could not be matched to any experimental structure in the Inorganic Crystal Structure Database (ICSD) @zagorac_recent_2019, nor any public repository of theoretical structures such as the Open Quantum Materials Database (OQMD) or Materials Project (MP).

The #gnome dataset was generated via SAPS @merchant_scaling_2023 (i.e. partial Wyckoff-site) element substitution from MP + OQMD parent structures with deduplication and thus does not overlap with MP by construction.
That is not to say that #gnome and MP chemical space are entirely disjoint.
For the #num-fmt(1199) #gnome materials considered here, 131 (#percent(131 / 1199)) contain the same element combination as another MP structure.
The chemical space of maximum overlap, Cu-La-Zn, contains four materials in #gnome (`7ee54b7a37`, `3422b9acb0`, `f36439bb45` and `68a5e7535f`) and two in MP (#mp-link[mp-1223296] and #mp-link[mp-1093834]).

An analysis of the local coordination environment of these structures using the `CrystalNN` algorithm @pan_benchmarking_2021 as implemented in `pymatgen` @ong_python_2013 reveals #num-fmt(21300) structures with unusually high maximum coordination number $N_"cnn"^"max" > 16$.

To evaluate the performance of #mace-mp against #gnome which discovered these structures, we re-relaxed #num-fmt(1199) of them with $N_"cnn"^"max" > 20$.
The `FrechetCellFilter` class in the Atomic Simulation Environment (ASE) @larsen_atomic_2017 was used to relax structures until the maximum (absolute) Cartesian component of any #mace-mp inter-atomic force was below $10^(-5)thin$eV/Å.
No dispersion correction was used to augment #mace-mp, consistent with the lack of dispersion correction in #gnome.
While all relaxations completed successfully, two boron-dominated structures (#gnome identifiers `00edc694b5` and `fc5cb3e024`) required a much larger number of relaxation steps than the average structure to reach force convergence.

@fig:parity-volume-gnome-mace-high-coordination plots the volumes of these #num-fmt(1199) structures after #mace-mp relaxation vs after #gnome relaxation, which are in excellent agreement.
#mace-mp relaxes structures to near identical configurations as #gnome in nearly all cases.
Only 19 structures (#percent(19 / 1199)) undergo energy lowering of more than #si1[10meV/atom] during relaxation.
22 structures (#percent(22 / 1199)) change space group during relaxation, in all cases increasing in symmetry.
The maximum calculated coordination number after #mace-mp relaxation changed for 135 structures (#percent(135 / 1199)) and decreased in all cases.

#figure(
  image("figs/mace-mp/parity-volume-gnome-mace-high-coordination.svg", width: 80%),
  caption: [
    *#mace-mp relaxes highly-coordinated structures to near identical configurations as #gnome.
    If $N_"cnn"^"max"$ changes, it always decreases, while symmetry always increases.*
    Comparison of ML-relaxed volume for #num-fmt(1199) highly-coordinated structures ($N_"cnn"^"max" > 20$) in the #gnome database @merchant_scaling_2023 ($x$ axis) vs the same structures relaxed with #mace-mp ($y$ axis).
    Points are colored by the difference in the total #mace-mp potential energy (in meV/atom) before vs after relaxation.
    Darker points indicate larger energy lowering during relaxation.
    The line of best fit is $V_"MLFF" approx 1.009 times V_(#gnome) - 0.102$, with $R^2 approx 0.998$.
  ],
)<fig:parity-volume-gnome-mace-high-coordination>

In short, #mace-mp performs comparably to #gnome for highly-coordinated structures and equilibrates to structures of equal or higher symmetry.

== Homonuclear Diatomics
<sec:mace-mp-homonuclear-diatomics>

#remark[
  Work in this section was led by #link("https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=spPcIs4AAAAJ")[Tamas K. Stenczel] at Engineering Laboratory, University of Cambridge, UK.
  I reproduced and checked the results, performed additional analysis of #mace-mp PES divergence issues for homonuclear dimers at close approach, edited the text and implemented the periodic table line plotting functions to generate @fig:mace-mp-homonuclear-diatomics in `pymatviz` @riebesell_pymatviz_2022.
]

#figure(
  image("figs/mace-mp/homonuclear-medium-periodic-table.svg", width: 120%),
  caption: [
    *Energy-distance curves of homonuclear diatomics in vacuum.*
    Units are eV for energy (y) and Å for distance (x).
    While many elements exhibit strong repulsion at small distances, an even larger number (60) show erratic behavior at sub-Angstrom separation with unphysical sharp drops in energy.
  ],
)<fig:mace-mp-homonuclear-diatomics>

When modeling high-temperature or high-pressure phases, a model must have strong core repulsion to prevent atoms from approaching too closely or even fusing.
To test the physicality of all homonuclear 2-body interactions, @fig:mace-mp-homonuclear-diatomics shows diatomic energy-distance curves of #mace-mp for all elements.
In a surprisingly large number of cases, we observe problematic fluctuations or erratic drops in energy at very close approach, e.g. for #ce("Li"), #ce("B"), #ce("Na"), #ce("Al"), #ce("P"), #ce("Cl") at $~#si1[0.5Å]$ and for O and F with higher training data representation at even smaller distances of 0.2 -- #si4[0.3Å].
The noble gases #ce("He"), #ce("Ne"), #ce("Ar") with negligible presence in the training set (@fig:element-counts-by-occurrence) are flat.

While @fig:mace-mp-homonuclear-diatomics shows the medium-sized #mace-mp with #si1(n-mace-medium-params) parameters as used throughout this chapter, the small model with #si1[3847696] parameters suffered from fewer elements with imploding negative energy at close approach (51 vs 60 elements going below #si1[-20eV]), possibly indicating a degree of overparameterization in the medium model.

One possible avenue for addressing this issue is to incorporate an analytical short-range repulsive term that is only active below a certain cutoff distance $r_"cutoff"$.
The difficulty here would be to implement a switching mechanism that correctly untangles atoms from MACE's many-body message passing as they enter the short-range regime, while also ensuring a smooth transition from #mace-mp at intermediate ranges to the short-range repulsion potential.
An open question is how sensitive simulation results would be to the choice of $r_"cutoff"$ and to what extent it would need to be element-dependent.
A second option that avoids the switching mechanism altogether is to always include a short-range repulsive term.
Simple 2-body terms like ZBL are inexpensive and only contribute when atoms are close.
However, given the severe energy drops for some elements in @fig:mace-mp-homonuclear-diatomics, even adding a positive ZBL term may not be sufficient to guarantee repulsion at close distances.

Another option that sidesteps complicating the model is to only use the analytical short-range potential such as Ziegler-Biersack-Littmark (ZBL) @ziegler_stopping_1985 to generate additional training labels for systems of densely packed atoms, or computing all dimers at various separation with exact DFT.
This would leave the model architecture unchanged and simply teach the model to raise the energies of high-density configurations by compensating for the severe lack of sub-Angstrom separation data in #mptrj.
We plan to explore these options, especially the data augmentation approach, in future work.

== Materials Discovery via Element Substitution
<sec:mace-mp-materials-discovery>

#remark[
  Work in this section was led by Konstantin S. Jakob at Fritz-Haber-Institute, Max-Planck-Society, Berlin, Germany.
  I reviewed the results, edited the text and contributed/fixed parts of the code in `pymatgen` @ong_python_2013 used to perform the analysis.
]

#figure(
  move(dx: -2.5%)[
    #image("figs/mace-mp/elem-sub-discovery.svg", width: 120%)
  ],
  caption: [
    *#mace-mp discovers new stable phases.*
    Distribution of #mace-mp relative energies and volumes for 100 stoichiometric substitutions of MP compositions.
    The distribution is sharply peaked at $V / V_("ref") = 1$ and $E - E_("ref") = 0$, indicating that the substituted cells often relax back to the known ground state structure from MP.
  ],
)<fig:mace-mp-elem-sub-discovery>

We performed exhaustive element substitutions for 100 randomly selected MP compositions.
The number of existing polymorphs in MP for each of these chemical systems varies widely, ranging from one (e.g. for #ce("NaNiIO6"), #ce("NaSrSnBiO6")) to at most 423 (for #ce("Sr2CoO4")).
Specifically, MP was first filtered to remove all structures with more than 16 atoms in the reduced formula to ensure a sufficient number of possible substitutions.
This set was randomly split into host and target compositions with a 60:40 ratio.
100 compositions were randomly drawn from the 40% target split and substituted into each stoichiometrically matching host, yielding #num-fmt(154685) substituted structures.
These were optimized with #mace-mp using full unit cell relaxations (without D3 dispersion corrections).
@fig:mace-mp-elem-sub-discovery (left) shows the results for relative energies and volumes compared to the most stable MP structure of that same composition.
The distribution is sharply peaked at $V / V_("ref") = 1$ and $E - E_("ref") = 0$, indicating that the substituted cells often relax back to the known ground state structure from MP.
This suggests #mace-mp's suitability for finding the correct ground state of unknown materials.
#mace-mp energies were validated with MP-compatible DFT calculations (using `pymatgen`'s `MPRelaxSet` to prepare VASP input files), yielding an RMSE of #si4[97meV/atom].

Beyond recovering the MP ground state, the wide range of substitutions tested also yields a large number of novel polymorphs for each composition.
#num-fmt(2518) of these have negative relative energies and are thus predicted to be more stable than the current MP ground state.
To validate these predictions, DFT relaxations were performed for all structures with negative relative energies.
The results confirm that #num-fmt(2120) of them are indeed more stable than the corresponding MP reference.
However, not all constitute new stable phases.
Many relaxations converged to the same MP minimum configuration (with slightly lower energy likely due to numerical noise).
In other cases, multiple lower-energy structures are found for a single composition, only one of which can be the true ground state.
Nonetheless, for 9 of the original 100 MP compositions considered here, new structures with energies below the current MP hull were discovered (for #for (idx, formula) in "Bi3Pb Cs3BiF6 Cs3TlF6 LuCrO5 NaNiIO6 NaSrSnBiO6 NdGaAu2 Sr2CoO4 TiS2O8".split().enumerate() {
  if idx > 0 { ", " }
  link("https://materialsproject.org/materials?formula=" + formula, ce(formula))
}).
We believe these to be genuinely new phases that are thermodynamically stable with respect to the MP convex hull.
For each novel ground state discovered, the closest MP structure is:
#for (idx, pair) in (
  mp-1106139: "Bi3Pb",
  mp-559695: "Cs3BiF6",
  mp-561827: "Cs3TlF6",
  mp-1211553: "LuCrO5",
  mp-545399: "NaNiIO6",
  mp-1522253: "NaSrSnBiO6",
  mp-1220399: "NdGaAu2",
  mp-1100068: "Sr2CoO4",
  mp-775149: "TiS2O8",
).pairs().enumerate() {
  if idx > 0 {
    ", "
  }
  let (key, value) = pair
  mp-link(key)
  [ for #ce(value)]
}
Remarkably, these new phases were also not reported in the recent #gnome effort (which focused on compositions not included in MP).
The WBM dataset does, however, report slightly more stable structures for #ce("NaNiIO6") and #ce("NdGaAu2").
It also includes additional structures to ours for #ce("Cs3BiF6") and #ce("Cs3TlF6"), which are less stable than the ones we found.

== Bulk and Shear Moduli
<sec:mace-mp-bulk-shear-moduli>

#remark[
  Work in this section was led by #link("https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=Mff-qs4AAAAJ")[Matthew Kuner] at the University of California, Berkeley, USA.
  I helped write the text, contributed usage advice, implemented the #link("https://github.com/materialsvirtuallab/matcalc/blob/1342d9e89/matcalc/elasticity.py#L22")[`ElasticityCalc`] property calculator (compatible with any #link("https://wiki.fysik.dtu.dk/ase/ase/calculators/calculators.html")[ASE `Calculator`]) together with Shyue Ping Ong in `MatCalc` @riebesell_matcalc_2023 which was used to obtain bulk and shear modulus predictions, and the plotting functions to generate @fig:parity-bulk-and-shear-moduli implemented in `pymatviz` @riebesell_pymatviz_2022.
]

Being able to predict elastic properties such as bulk and shear modulus is relevant for many industrial applications including coating, cutting and polishing as well as turbine and other high-temperature and high-wear engine materials @kaner_designing_2005 @zhang_finding_2021.
Like phonons, elasticity depends on the second derivative of energy with respect to strain, again testing a model's ability to precisely capture PES curvature.

To test #mace-mp in this regard, we benchmarked against the elastic properties of over #si1[10k] MP materials by calculating the Voigt-Reuss-Hill average @voigt_lehrbuch_1910 @reuss_berechnung_1929 @hill_statistical_1952 bulk modulus and shear modulus as derived from #mace-mp stress-strain relations.

All #si1[10k] structures are bulk crystals at equilibrium.
While none of the DFT deformation calculations contained in MP are present in
the #mptrj training set used for #mace-mp, and the deformations we applied are not identical given #mace-mp relaxes to a somewhat different ground state than the original MP structure, the purpose of this analysis is not to assess extrapolation performance but the fidelity of the PES for predicting downstream observables that also constitute application-relevant material properties.

The initial structures used for these calculations were the PBE-relaxed @perdew_rationale_1996 configurations from MP which were first re-relaxed using #mace-mp and then deformed.
Specifically, a total of 4 strain magnitudes were used along six independent strain modes (in Voigt notation):

$
  vector(ϵ)
  = [ϵ_11, ϵ_22, ϵ_33, ϵ_44, ϵ_55, ϵ_66]
$<eq:strain-vec>
where the strain values we chose are
$
  ϵ_11 = ϵ_22 = ϵ_33 in {±0.01, ±0.005}\
  ϵ_44 = ϵ_55 = ϵ_66 in {±0.06, ±0.03}
$<eq:strain-values>

These calculations were performed using the `MatCalc` #link("https://github.com/materialsvirtuallab/matcalc/blob/main/matcalc/elasticity.py")[`elasticity` module] @riebesell_matcalc_2023.
Moreover, to filter out likely unphysical DFT predictions, elastic properties from MP were excluded from this analysis if the DFT average bulk $K_"VRH"$ or shear $G_"VRH"$ modulus are less than #si1[−50GPa] or greater than #si1[600GPa].
$
  #si1[-50GPa] < (K_"VRH" "or" G_"VRH") < #si1[600GPa]
$<eq:bulk-shear-moduli-cutoff>

#figure(
  grid(
    columns: (1fr, 1fr),
    column-gutter: 1em,
    subfigure(
      image("figs/mace-mp/parity-bulk-modulus.svg"),
      pos: bottom + left,
      dy: -12pt,
      label: <fig:parity-bulk-modulus>,
    ),
    subfigure(
      image("figs/mace-mp/parity-shear-modulus.svg"),
      pos: bottom + left,
      dy: -12pt,
      label: <fig:parity-shear-modulus>,
    ),
  ),
  caption: [
    #mace-mp vs MP bulk (a) and shear (b) moduli for $~#si1[10k]$ MP materials.
    For bulk moduli $K_"VRH"$, a single point for #mp-link[mp-721759] (face-centered cubic nitrogen) was excluded, as #mace-mp
    predicted an unphysically high bulk modulus (>#si1[600GPa]).
    For shear moduli $G_"VRH"$, 26 points were excluded from this plot as #mace-mp
