To quantify the magnitude of PES softening observed in different universal potentials, we define a softening scale parameter $c_S$, which is determined by sampling #ce("Li2B3PO8") (#mp-link[mp-1020015]) off-equilibrium states from high-temperature MD at #si1(num-mode: "format")[1000K] followed by running static calculations to get the interatomic forces on each atom with both DFT and the ML potential in question.
@fig:slanted-off-equi-force-parity shows a parity plot of MLFF vs DFT forces from these off-equilibrium states.

Systematic PES softening is characterized by a clockwise tilt of predicted forces from the diagonal parity line, which corresponds to systematic force underpredictions.
A linear regression can be performed to extract the slope of the distribution, where the slope indicates the extent of the systematic error, and is therefore defined as the PES softening scale $c_S$.
$c_S = 1$ corresponds to the MLIP's force distribution aligning with the diagonal, which indicates the curvature of the MLIP-PES systematically agrees with DFT with only local random noise.
$c_S > 1$ which is observed for all models tested here (#chgnet, #mace-mp and #m3gnet), indicates the MLIP PES is overly smooth, resulting in low forces.
// By contrast, given a sufficient sample size, a random force error would result in a line of best fit that coincides with the parity line.

To investigate how broadly PES softening affects different chemistries, we randomly sampled 1000 unique chemical systems from the WBM dataset @wang_predicting_2021 not included in the MP pre-training set of any of the models to ensure testing under OOD conditions.
We sampled 10 off-equilibrium structures from each MD trajectory at $T = #si1(num-mode: "format")[1000K]$ to calculate static DFT forces @qi_robust_2023.
Comparing the force predictions from MLIPs and DFT shows a clear underprediction trend.
@fig:softening-scale-violins shows the distribution of PES softening scales $c_S$ across the 1000 WBM OOD chemistries.
We find $c_S$ smaller than 1 for 93% of materials with #m3gnet, 98% for #chgnet, and 97% for #mace-mp, which demonstrates the softening behavior is consistent across diverse chemical spaces and current universal ML potentials.
#gnome similarly exhibits pronounced softening when trained on the #m3gnet dataset, as shown in @merchant_scaling_2023[Figs.~S34 -- S37].
The softening effect is somewhat mitigated but still present after training on the full #gnome dataset of #si1[89M] structures.
These examples show that PES softening is prevalent across various models and datasets.
A systematic analysis is needed to quantify and correct this error.

While similar signs of softening due to choice of training data were previously observed @pandey_predicting_2021 @bartel_datacentric_2021, less attention was dedicated to a systematic examination.
@pandey_predicting_2021 reported a distribution shift from training CGCNN @xie_crystal_2018 to predict DFT energies of ICSD structures taken as is from the database without relaxation.

=== Super data-efficient fine-tuning
<sec:data-efficient-fine-tuning>

The systematic MLIP PES flatness appears as a tilted distribution of forces in the parity plot as shown in @fig:slanted-off-equi-force-parity.
Intuitively, one can easily rotate the distribution back to the diagonal to eliminate systematic errors and reset the softening scale to 1.
In @fig:slanted-off-equi-force-parity, the bottom-left table with columns `Slope`, `MAE`, `cMAE` report the linear fitted slope from the actual distribution (colored dash lines), the corresponding actual `MAE` and the corrected `cMAE` if all force predictions are uniformly divided by the slope to rotate predictions until slope and parity align.
The cMAEs are 12 to 16% lower than the actual MAEs, indicating that $1/7$ to $1/8$ of MLFF force errors are systematic and can be easily corrected:

$
  #chgnet: 0.22 xarrow(-16%) 0.18 quad
  #mace-mp: 0.19 xarrow(-15%) 0.16 quad
  #m3gnet: 0.18 xarrow(-12%) 0.16 wide \
  script("MAE (eV/Å)" xarrow("percent change") "cMAE (eV/Å)")
$<eq:soft-pes-mae-vs-cmae>

Mathematically, rotating the force distribution is equivalent to multiplying a scalar to every force value, which can be realized by multiplying the MLIP-predicted energy $"MLFF"({vector(r)_i}, {C_i})$ by the scalar slope $c_S$.
$
  E^"corr" &= c_S dot "MLFF"({vector(r)_i} , {C_i}) = c_S dot E,
  wide && vector(f)_i^"corr" &&= -(diff E^"corr") / (diff vector(r)_i) = c_S dot vector(f)_i .
$<eqn:soft-pes-fine-tuning>

The above formulation is equivalent to fine-tuning an MLIP with all model weights fixed except for a final linear layer, which modifies only the scalar parameter $c_S$ in @eqn:soft-pes-fine-tuning.
Since only a scalar parameter is modified, a single label (1 force component) suffices for training.
Fine-tuning typically involves hundreds to thousands of additional labels.
This observation of remedying PES softness with a minute amount of fine-tuning data elucidates that softness is a data issue rather than a model issue.
@fig:soft-pes-force-error-violins-linear-correction shows the off-equilibrium force MAE and theoretical cMAE for the 1000 WBM structures.
The distribution of decreased MAEs therefore provides a theoretical lower bound for the expected performance gain of fine-tuning MLFFs.
This lower bound can in turn be cheaply and quickly approximated by fitting a final-layer linear correction from a single training label.

Our results suggest a theoretical explanation for the commonly observed data-efficient performance boost achieved by fine-tuning MLFFs compared to training MLIPs from scratch with the same data @kaur_dataefficient_2024.
The data efficiency arises from the observation that a considerable part of the MAEs in pre-trained MLFFs are systematic and thus easily fixed with small amounts of data.

== Limitations and Next Steps
<sec:mace-mp-limits>

#mace-mp (and to a slightly lesser extent #chgnet and #m3gnet) approaching DFT accuracy and stable MD across such a wide range of atomic configurations covering most of the periodic table is a landmark achievement for a single interatomic potential.
Yet many limitations in the current version remain.
Foremost, the #mptrj training set was generated at the PBE-level of theory @perdew_rationale_1996, which requires Hubbard $U$ corrections to improve electronic correlations for particular transition metal--anion or metal--transition metal combinations.
This introduces inconsistencies in the PES that again must be posthoc compensated~@jain_computational_2016, introducing a source of confusion for the model since two materials with similar chemistries may now have inconsistent energies if one contains a $U$-corrected element-pair and the other does not.
PBE is also well-known to lack long-range dispersive forces which therefore #mace-mp likewise fails to model, requiring the addition of posthoc dispersion force corrections such as D3 @grimme_consistent_2010.
Recent developments in DFT around the #r2scan @sun_strongly_2015 @bartok_regularized_2019 @furness_accurate_2020 meta-GGA functional are beginning to supersede PBE by achieving significantly improved accuracy at acceptable increase in computational cost @kingsbury_performance_2022.
With future computing power, hybrid functionals~@heyd_hybrid_2003 @henderson_accurate_2011 or the random phase approximation~@harl_assessing_2010 may become affordable enough to generate fine-tuning datasets and improve upon this even further, albeit at huge cost by today's standards.
Refitting the model to a more modern functional will significantly increase its predictive power and simultaneously reduce the need for system-dependent corrections, making it more universally applicable and closer to a plug-and-play tool that can be used even by non-experts.

Despite the success stories in @sec:mace-mp and even more in @riebesell_foundation_2023, #mace-mp is limited to a #si4[12Å] receptive field afforded by two steps of message passing each with graph cutoff $r_C = #si1[6Å]$.
It therefore cannot incorporate truly long-range interactions acting over distances greater than #si4[12Å].
Some observables, particularly in the context of dilute solutions and at interfaces, cannot be calculated with a medium-range model like this.
Moreover, #mace-mp has no concept of magnetic or spin degrees of freedom.
This is an obvious improvement for future model iterations as several approaches have already been published for incorporating explicit electrostatic interactions @ghasemi_interatomic_2015 @grisafi_incorporating_2019 @ko_fourthgeneration_2021 @vondrak_qpac_2023, as well as spin degrees of freedom @novikov_magnetic_2022 @rinaldi_noncollinear_2024 @deng_chgnet_2023.

In the case of low-pressure simulations of ethanol @riebesell_foundation_2023[sec.~A.16] we noticed these small quantitative deviations can lead to qualitative errors by shifting the temperature or pressure of a phase transition, which then result in unphysical equilibrium phases at ambient conditions.
Another failure mode that popped up in two different test cases (random structure search @riebesell_foundation_2023[sec.~A.14] and high-pressure hydrogen @riebesell_foundation_2023[sec.~A.21]) are atoms at very close approach causing sudden extreme drops in energy, resulting in the respective simulations being trapped in unphysical erroneously low-energy geometries.

Both these failure modes are not specific to any particularly challenging chemical system but are direct shortcomings of the training data.
As such, they should be straightforward to address by extending the existing training data to lower and higher pressures @magdau_machine_2023 and concatenating pressure as a global state variable onto the input.
This will place stronger constraints on the model's behavior in diverse pressure regimes.
Likewise, a future iteration of the training set could be augmented using repulsive pair potentials @byggmastar_machinelearning_2019 such as ZBL @ziegler_stopping_1985 to generate very-short atom pair--force labels to constrain the model a more physical PES at sub-angstrom distances.
The current training set contains no examples of such close approach, leaving a physically agnostic statistical model with no guidance on what to predict.

In summary, promising avenues to improve the model's accuracy include

/ Increasing model size: More free parameters means lifting the expressivity ceiling.
  Unlikely to yield sizeable improvements given #mace-mp's current size of #si1(n-mace-medium-params) parameters is already 10x that of #chgnet which performs worse but not by a large margin.

/ Removing inconsistencies: As mentioned above, having trained only PBE-level data which require posthoc $U$ corrections for some materials may confuse the model.
It also has an incomplete picture of physical forces given GGA's lack of long-range dispersion forces @grimme_density_2007 @grimme_consistent_2010.

/ Training set augmentation: Increasing the number and variety of atomic configurations for training is likely to unlock by far the biggest gains in accuracy and versatility given the performance of proprietary models such as #gnome and #link("https://matlantis.com/news/pfp-validation-for-public-v5-0-0")[PFP] which trained on $1-2$ orders of magnitude larger datasets than #mptrj.

Efforts to alleviate current limitations around data inconsistency and size are ongoing.
We started an open source #link("https://github.com/materialsproject/atomate2/pull/532")[#matpes] collaboration with Shyue Ping Ong's group mid-last year aiming to create one of the largest and most diverse #r2scan$$-level datasets specifically designed for ML potential training.
However, even in its current form, #mace-mp serves as a good starting point for both data- and compute-efficient fine-tuning.
How much additional data is needed for such refinement depends on the required accuracy and degree of departure from the training set @gardner_synthetic_2024.
In many cases, we expect a fine-tuning set of hundreds of examples to be sufficient.
Transfer-learning approaches can also enable these models to fit higher-quality reference data, often requiring an order of magnitude less high-quality data than the original training set @bartok_machinelearning_2013 @smith_approaching_2019 @dral_hierarchical_2020.

While it is not yet wise to solely rely on ML potentials for any prediction without further validation @morrow_how_2023, we are optimistic that training sets of significantly increased fidelity, diversity and size will be sufficient to achieve quantitative agreement with the target level of theory across chemical space.
In that case, future versions of #mace-mp or other foundational force fields may truly provide a universal model for carrying out materials simulations.

