= Summary
<sec:summary>

The projects in this thesis collectively explored the current boundaries of ML-accelerated materials discovery and simulation.
ML capabilities have advanced at an impressive pace in the last few years with significant improvements across model architecture, training data, usability and reproducibility.
Many models now come as versioned, easily installable Python packages#footnote[
  E.g. `pip install`
  #link("https://pypi.org/project/chgnet")[`chgnet`]
  #link("https://pypi.org/project/mace-mp")[`mace-torch`]
  #link("https://pypi.org/project/m3gnet")[`m3gnet`]
  is all it takes to install the 3 currently best open models on #mbd.
].
ML potentials covering most of the periodic table in particular have undergone a flurry of innovation and reached a critical juncture.
Models like #mace-mp, #chgnet, #m3gnet, #sevennet, PFP, #gnome and Equiformer v2#footnote[We and Zackary Ulissi's group are each working on submitting Equiformer v1 and v2 trained on #mptrj to #mbd.
Our work on v2 has stalled recently though due to persistent NaN predictions appearing during training in deeply nested `e3nn` which proved resistant to Philipp Benner's debugging efforts.], among others can perform various forms of stability and property prediction as well as drive MD for challenging chemical processes over unprecedented length and time scales @behler_four_2021.
To put this into perspective, as recently as 2020, the ability of ML to accelerate materials discovery was still a topic of debate @bartel_critical_2020 and rightfully so given results at the time.
MLFFs are now accurate and versatile enough to be serious contenders to compete with more established simulation methods on a variety of tasks.
Even more importantly, their linear scaling with system size makes new kinds of complex, long-duration simulations possible for the first time.

== #mbd
<section:summary-mbd>

#mbd established machine-learned force fields as the state-of-the-art method for ML-guided materials discovery.
By demonstrating their superiority over energy-only models such as #megnet @chen_graph_2019, ALIGNN @choudhary_atomistic_2021, CGCNN @xie_crystal_2018, #bowsr @zuo_accelerating_2021 and #wrenformer @goodall_accelerating_2022, #mbd catalyzed the creation of #chgnet @deng_chgnet_2023 and especially #mace-mp @riebesell_foundation_2023, two of the most accurate and versatile open-source ML potentials to date.
Force models can chart a path through atomic configuration space approaching the DFT-relaxed structure from where a more reliable final energy prediction can be made.
#mbd proved a highly useful tool for the initial validation and performance assessment of both models.
Our findings include discovery acceleration factors (DAFs) compared to random selection greater than 3 across the whole WBM test set (@tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos), and 5.6 when considering only the #si1[10k] most stable predictions from each model (@tab:metrics-table-first-10k) (with #si1(n-wbm-uniq-protos / n-wbm-stable-uniq-protos) the maximum possible DAF on our test set).
Our results advocate for the integration of both ML geometry optimization and relaxed energy prediction into future database expansion efforts, as filtering out ML-unstable structures strongly reduces the number of DFT calculations required to reach a desired level of convex hull exploration.
Model errors as a function of training set size in log-log scale yield roughly straight lines even up to #ord(7) training samples @vonlilienfeld_retrospective_2020[fig.~2] @merchant_scaling_2023[figs.~1e, S14--S21], suggesting that further decreases in MLFF errors are readily unlocked with unbiased training data augmentation.
We observe the same trends in #mbd from proprietary models like #gnome and #link("https://matlantis.com/news/pfp-validation-for-public-v5-0-0")[PFP] which significantly outperform all open models (see @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos-with-closed) having training on $~2$ orders of magnitude more data (#link(mbd-repo-url + "/blob/71a5edc/models/gnome/gnome.yml#L45")[#ord(8) structures]) than the canonical #mbd training set (#si1(n-mptrj-entries) structures).
Model architecture is likely to play an insignificant role here, as both PFP (TeaNet architecture @takamoto_teanet_2022) and #gnome (#nequip architecture @batzner_equivariant_2022) are standard GNNs devoid of unusual architectural features.
Active learning loops where new training data is added based on model uncertainty or error estimates are likely to be even more effective than unbiased data increase.
This prior was recently confirmed by #mattersim @yang_mattersim_2024[table~S2] which outperforms #gnome on most #mbd metrics using $~5x$ less training structures ($~#si0[17e6]$ vs $~#si0[89e6]$) highlighting the importance of optimizing for structural diversity.

It is worth emphasizing at this point that we controlled as best we could for data leakage on industry models with incompatible training sets by confirming performance metrics are insensitive to testing on subsets of WBM data filtered to remove compositional overlap with proprietary training sets such as #gnome.
That said, we are unable to monitor what happens behind closed doors.
This makes a benchmark such as #mbd with a publicly available test set @wang_predicting_2021 reliant on an honor system, especially for submissions with closed source and/or weights where fine-tuning the model on the test set cannot be verified to yield substantial improvements in performance (the absence of which would strongly hint at data leakage and perhaps prior training on the test set).
A future benchmark of similarly permissive design would benefit from a hidden test set unavailable to external model submissions as is the case e.g. for the OCP series of benchmarks @tran_open_2022 @chanussot_open_2021 @sriram_open_2023, allowing for somewhat more confident evaluation of proprietary models.

Several well-established benchmarks including Matbench @dunn_benchmarking_2020 and Jarvis @choudhary_large_2023 already provide a platform for direct architecture comparisons.
Our objective with #mbd was not to reproduce the rigid benchmarks common in conventional ML domains like language and vision which in our opinion do not map well onto chemistry.
The crucial difference in those domains is data abundance, making architectural and training procedure innovations the primary focus of research.
ML for chemistry by contrast is data-starved.
This makes innovative architecture-data combinations more likely to be the primary source of progress which in turn renders rigid-data benchmarks less conducive to advancing the field.
As an example, interatomic potentials are trained on forces and stresses and can therefore leverage available ab-initio training data to greater effect than energy-only models.
This constitutes a genuine domain-advantage of ML potentials and we want #mbd to reflect that.
Thus, our objective to ask system-level rather than purely architecture-focused questions led to permissiveness as an overarching design principle and the opinionated choice to accommodate models trained on different datasets.

To elaborate on this point, a recent study found a substantial portion of high-throughput data is redundant when considering in-distribution (ID) performance @li_exploiting_2023.
By specifying a maximum training set and a fixed test set, #mbd provides a controlled environment in which future work could innovate on downsampling schemes that result in more efficient training or more consistent data while measuring the impact on performance.
Such work would be able to evaluate the claims in @li_exploiting_2023 in the context of OOD performance.
To some extent, the answer to this question popped out for free from #mbd by comparing #chgnet which was trained on #mptrj (#si1(n-mptrj-entries) structures) and #m3gnet trained on the #link("https://figshare.com/articles/dataset/MPF_2021_2_8/19470599")[MPF.2021.2.8] dataset (#si1(n-mpf-2021-entries) structures), an almost #si1(n-mptrj-entries / n-mpf-2021-entries)x smaller subset of the allowed data.
Given the architectural similarities between #chgnet and #m3gnet, the leaderboard reveals a surprisingly small degradation in regression performance from #chgnet to #m3gnet.
The more task-relevant classification metrics by contrast exhibit a larger deterioration, perhaps calling into question the transferability of results in @li_exploiting_2023 to the OOD stability classification setting.
Of course, a rigorous ablation study would be necessary to thoroughly substantiate such claims.

To summarize, we believe #mbd succeeded at providing a walled garden for probing system-level questions in the context of ML for materials discovery.
We hope the greater control it affords end-users will help inspire novel research directions, particularly with regards to utilizing a wider variety of the huge amounts of available (but often inconsistent) ab-initio reference data.

== Foundation Models
<sec:summary-foundation-models>

By demonstrating the effectiveness of ML stability screening for high-throughput materials discovery in @sec:mbd, we gained trust in the reliability and transferability of these models.
This in turn encouraged us to invest the significant time and resources required to train models like #chgnet and #mace-mp.
Ref.~@riebesell_foundation_2023 (on which most of @sec:mace-mp is based) explores their abilities and limitations in great detail on a diverse set of tasks, finding #mace-mp to be capable of accurately simulating a surprising range of chemistries in solid, liquid, and gaseous phases.
Despite being trained solely on bulk crystals, #mace-mp demonstrates surprising versatility, able to model molecules and proteins as well as catalytic processes and entire batteries.
Such foundation models, pre-trained on large structural and property databases, have the potential to run near-DFT-accuracy simulations at a fraction of the cost.
Even more excitingly, they can simulate systems orders of magnitude larger over longer timescales than possible with DFT.
They also serve as excellent starting points for data-efficient fine-tuning to specific applications as demonstrated in @sec:mlff-pes-softening. // TODO incorporate or delete: and existing literature @focassio_performance_2024 @clausen_adapting_2024 @shoghi_molecules_2023
The emergent ability to extrapolate the interactions governing large complex systems, both inorganic, organic and metal-organic, from having trained solely on inorganic bulk crystals, as thoroughly demonstrated in @sec:mace-mp and @riebesell_foundation_2023, is a remarkable scientific discovery in its own right.
More work is needed to fully understand how this extrapolation ability arises and how it can be further enhanced.

Together, the insights gained in @sec:mbd[Chapters] -- @sec:mace-mp[] lay the groundwork for future advancements in dataset and interatomic potential development and bring us closer to the goal of accurate, efficient off-the-shelf ML-driven materials simulation accessible to force-field non-experts.

