= Outlook
<sec:outlook>

Given this work focused on the nascent and fast-moving field of GNN interatomic potentials, many questions remain unanswered.
Directions for future work include:

== PES Softening
<sec:summary-pes-softening>

The initial phonon analysis of #mace-mp which we later extended to #chgnet and #m3gnet reveals a consistent trend of underpredicted phonon frequencies across models and diverse chemistries attributable to underestimated restoring forces on atomic displacements.
Many of the 35 simulation tasks in @riebesell_foundation_2023 showed similar issues also originating from an unphysically flat potential energy surface.

@sec:mlff-pes-softening investigates the root cause of this PES softening and finds it to be a data problem rather than a model problem, originating from the biased sampling of current pre-training datasets that are largely distributed around energy minima of bulk solids.
As a result of the bias for smoothness built into MLFFs, far-from-equilibrium atomic configurations have systematically underestimated energies and forces, causing quantitative and sometimes even qualitative errors in simulations of high-energy dynamic processes like ion migrations and phase transformation.

We show that PES softness can be effectively resolved by fine-tuning on a handful of far-equilibrium states, explaining the data-efficient performance boost frequently observed from fine-tuning, indicative of correcting systematic errors.

This raises the need for improved next-generation datasets for training foundational MLFFs.
Despite significant efforts dedicated to model design and training strategies, less emphasis has been placed on constructing comprehensive and well-curated open-source materials datasets.
Current generation foundation models rely on databases such as MP that were not originally generated with ML in mind, leaving significant room for improvement.
Results throughout this thesis but @sec:mlff-pes-softening in particular stress the importance of increasing both chemical and configurational diversity in next-generation datasets to ensure better sampling of high-energy regions of the PES.
This will be crucial to allow MLFFs to simulate a wider range of physical phenomena like high-temperature and/or pressure MD, phase transitions, and chemical reactions.

Increasing training data diversity raises questions about the impact of model size and expressivity on the ability to capture intricate PES details @ko_recent_2023.
Excited states often contain high-order interactions resulting in non-linear behavior.
The Lennard-Jones potential serves as a toy example of this where the close-approach region is dominated by $r^(-12)$ repulsion while the equilibrium region is governed by the $r^(-6)$ term.
Given that higher-order polynomials require more expressivity to learn @yarotsky_error_2017, model size may need to increase to accurately capture future diversified near- and far-equilibrium training sets.
While existing results shine little light on the effect of model size on PES physicality, further studies should investigate the number of model parameters needed to describe a truly universal PES.

== Probing Bias-Variance Tradeoff in GNNs
<sec:outlook-bias-variance-tradeoff>

The bias-variance tradeoff is the widely observed empirical trend that increasing model complexity (usually quantified by the number of trainable parameters) reduces bias but increases variance.
Bias is the amount of prior expectations baked into the model by assumptions made during the design that later prevent it from correctly fitting the underlying process that generated the observed data.
Variance, on the other hand, measures randomness in the model's predictions due to the sampled data points used for training (which necessarily comprise a subset of the true distribution to be inferred).
The more complex a model, the more it tends to fit to random noise.

However, empirical evidence from large over-parameterized neural networks including GNNs challenges the bias-variance paradigm.
As the size and depth of GNNs increase, the test error even on OOD samples sometimes decreases, in contradiction to the expected variance increase.
Several studies have proposed theoretical explanations for this phenomenon known as double descent @nakkiran_deep_2021.
Ref.~@yarotsky_error_2017 establishes strict upper and lower bounds on model complexity of models with a small Lipschitz constant, i.e. models that learn smooth functions.
Ref.~@bubeck_universal_2021 showed that (depending on the interplay between model size, depth, and training) double descent can occur for small Lipschitz models.
They found that models that underwent double descent yield better robustness to adversarial attacks, an observation not limited to neural networks.
Ref.~@hastie_surprises_2022 further demonstrated that increasing model parameters can improve training fit while simultaneously restricting the solution to a smaller $L_2$-norm ball in weight space, thus improving stability and generalization.
Prior work had linked this effect to posterior contraction in Bayesian deep learning @wilson_bayesian_2020 @maddox_rethinking_2020.
Ref.~@bousquet_stability_2002 showed that models insensitive to small changes in the training data have more tightly coupled train and test errors, such that larger models with lower train error can also have lower test error.

More research is needed to substantiate the preventability of bias-variance tradeoff in GNNs and to understand the precise conditions needed for double descent.
Such findings would have critical implications for larger next-generation MLFFs that tie into the PES softening issue discussed above.
Finding reliable methods to simultaneously reduce bias and variance would guide the way to more reliable ML foundation models for materials chemistry.

== Benchmarking Foundation Models
<sec:outlook-benchmarking>

Progress in machine learning research is often driven by good benchmarks, the most famous example being the ImageNet classification task in computer vision @deng_imagenet_2009.
The availability of challenging and informative standardized tasks spurs advances by establishing a goal post with which to measure progress over time and compare the merit of different ideas and methods.
For molecular systems, the QM9 @ramakrishnan_big_2015 and MD17 @chmiela_exact_2018 data sets have been the go-to benchmark tasks.
Matbench @dunn_benchmarking_2020 which inspired @sec:mbd has been an important first step in establishing a standard suite of ML tasks for inorganic materials.
It measures predictive accuracy across 13 regression and classification tasks spanning a range of data set sizes.
However, its limitation to supervised learning lacks a pre-training dimension that allows transfer-learning benefits and the ability to use more of the available training labels (e.g. forces plus energies) to be reflected.
It also lacks a simulation aspect, arguably the most versatile use for ML potentials in downstream research which thus more directly connects benchmark metrics to real-world utility for users.
As a result, Matbench could make no distinction between energy-only and force models which proved to be a critical factor in #mbd performance.
Finally, the most informative metric is often task-dependent.
E.g. precision and enrichment in selecting candidate materials are more pertinent when quantifying acceleration of materials discovery than predictive accuracy.

While #mbd (@sec:mbd) was able to address some of these limitations, it focused solely on stability prediction, thus moving into sharp relief the now-pressing lack of a more comprehensive standardized benchmark for ML foundation models that goes beyond materials discovery to cover the rich diversity of possible downstream applications other researchers will use them for.
One reason such a benchmark is difficult to design is the lack of agreement on what the most important tasks and related performance metrics are.
Ideally, the field could agree on a minimal set of tasks that yield a maximally discriminative set of metrics.
It will require careful consideration, iteration and extended discussion between benchmark authors and stakeholders to reach a consensus on which evaluation metrics best reflect the wide variety of possible use cases for these models.
Identifying an agreeable set of benchmark tasks and metrics will greatly facilitate securing sufficient buy-in from model authors to solicit external model submissions.
This in turn lowers the workload on benchmark curators and aids long-term maintainability and relevance of the benchmark.

A good question to ask when designing such a benchmark is which metrics capture the ability to predict a multitude of downstream observables and are therefore informative to readers from many subfields?
This question naturally leads to metrics that are highly sensitive to the physicality of the PES as the root source of all downstream predictions.
They should also quantify foundation model stability and accuracy across diverse chemistries and physical conditions, the ability to extrapolate to new systems, computational efficiency, and reward a model that delivers high-quality uncertainty estimates.
Given the large datasets and considerable training costs involved, such a benchmark would necessarily constitute a major curation effort that is cost-prohibitive for most academic groups.
Standardizing a consistent foundation model training set may need to come from a well-known and trusted incumbent to attract sufficient attention, acceptance and ultimately adoption.
Given the huge effort required to create the high-quality large-scale datasets needed for such a benchmark, the data creation and benchmark design may end up being separate efforts as was the case for #mbd.
The inability of many academic groups to train even a single foundation model due to the prohibitive cost (often requiring dozens of GPUs over multiple days, i.e. #ord(4) GPU hours which is only going to grow), let alone the tens of training runs needed to populate a benchmark leaderboard establishes a barrier to entry.

Given architecture is decidedly less important than training data, it stands to reason that to set themselves apart, future foundation models will largely innovate on the training set, creating a natural pressure away from a consistent benchmark evaluation.
That said, the expected near-term proliferation of foundation models and resulting confusion among users about which one to choose will significantly increase the need for a standardized benchmark and likely exert sufficient pressure to cause its creation.

== Commoditizing Foundation Models
<sec:outlook-commoditizing>

To realize the full potential of ML foundation models, several challenges must be addressed:

- Extend *accessibility to non-experts* by improving ease of use and setup.
  This may involve creating user-friendly visual interfaces into which researchers drag and drop structure files, and select desired tasks (relaxation, MD, property prediction, etc.) and the tool handles the rest including warning the user if results are untrustworthy.

- Improving *interpretability* can help build trust and aid scientific insights.
  These models are powerful but opaque, making them potentially treacherous in the hands of non-experts.
  Techniques to identify which input features drive specific outputs @morrow_how_2023 and *reliable uncertainty estimation* possibly through model committees will be important to build trust and achieve deployment into high-stakes applications.

- Training on *multiple modalities* is essential to expose models to the full diversity of chemical space.
  This includes surfaces, defects, molecules, metal-organic hybrid materials, bulk solids, amorphous phases, interfaces and multi-element alloys and 2D materials.
  Having seen such systems will be vital for modeling numerous processes including catalysis and electrochemical processes (e.g. water splitting), ab- and adsorption of gases and molecules, deposition of heterostructures and 2d crystals, nanoparticle growth, and many more.
  Handling the increased complexity may require more sophisticated model architectures.
  It will certainly substantially increase training cost.
  However, the biggest challenge will likely be achieving data consistency across that many modalities so as not to confuse the model.
  The best demonstration to date that this can be done was recently published in @shoghi_molecules_2023.

- Increasing *data fidelity*.
  All current universal potentials are fitted to PBE-level data which has known accuracy limitations.
  Refitting to #r2scan @furness_accurate_2020 @kingsbury_performance_2022 is a highly promising avenue to improve accuracy and reduce the need for posthoc corrections.

== Discovering Pareto Optimal Materials
<sec:outlook-pareto-optimal-materials>

@sec:diel has shown our inability to reliably predict band gaps significantly degrades the hit rate of identifying new high-performance dielectric materials.
The key failure mode stems from false insulators -- metals predicted to be gapped.
While we observed decreasing band gap error by increasing the training set to #si1(n-diel-train-mp-wbm) samples from combining MP and WBM, metals misclassified as insulators remained a critical cause for wasted DFPT calculations.
The band gap is a non-local property of the electronic rather than ionic structure of a material, which most existing ML architectures have no notion of, making it particularly challenging to model with statistical methods.
Consequently, alternative approaches for estimating the bandgap should be explored, such as predicting the electronic density of states (DOS) from which the bandgap can be extracted @kong_density_2021 or modeling the electronic structure directly @koker_higherorder_2023.
A single DOS can be discretized into hundreds of training labels, increasing the amount of available reference data.
More generally, effective architectures for predicting spectral properties would be valuable across a wide range of material science applications @chen_direct_2021 @riebesell_foundation_2023.

Our dielectrics workflow would also benefit from using a top-performing MLFF like #mace-mp or #chgnet to enable pre-DFPT dynamic stability filtering.
This would reduce the funnel's false positive stable rate earlier and more cheaply (see @sec:dynamic-stability-issues).
Thus the lessons learned from #mbd and especially @sec:mace-mp on data-driven thermodynamic and kinetic stability prediction tie directly into our dielectrics workflow, demonstrating how parts of the thesis inform each other.
Specifically, #mbd informed the foundation model training and analysis in @sec:mace-mp which in turn will inform future iterations of our dielectrics workflow.

Identifying novel stable materials is just the first step in materials discovery; the ultimate goal is to predict and experimentally realize new functionality.
Many of the most useful functional materials exhibit trade-offs between competing physical effects.
For instance, good thermoelectric materials need to combine high electrical with low thermal conductivity.
Good dielectrics should be highly polarizable yet strong insulators.
Although some studies have focused on optimizing a single functional property, such as hardness @zuo_accelerating_2021 @zhang_finding_2021, multi-objective optimization of competing properties is unavoidable in virtually all industrial applications.
Tackling the multi-objective regime head-on will reveal the main shortcomings in current workflows, allowing us to better focus our efforts on resolving them.

== Generative Modeling
<sec:outlook-generative-modeling>

The ultimate goal of computational materials design is a tool that given a set of target properties, suggests stable atomic configurations that can be made in a lab and satisfy the requested performance criteria.
Initial efforts to develop generative diffusion models for inorganic crystals such as CDVAE @xie_crystal_2022, DiffCSP @jiao_crystal_2024 and more recently #mattergen @zeni_mattergen_2023 have demonstrated encouraging potential to realize this inverse design paradigm.
While we successfully employed a much simpler form of novel crystal generation using chemical-similarity-guided element substitution in @sec:diel, the hit rate (@tab:diel-hit-rate-comparison) of future implementations of the workflow presented in @fig:diel-discovery-workflow could benefit immensely from crystal generation successfully conditioned on band gap and dielectric constant, especially if such models can reduce or avoid the failure mode of metal-insulator misclassification.
This would vastly reduce the number of expensive DFPT calculations required to identify a desired number of high-$Φ_M$ materials, which in turn would speed up the discovery process and lower the barrier to entry.

We believe there's been reason for skepticism on the viability of diffusion models for crystals in the past.
However, #mattergen outperforming widely employed methods such as MLFF-assisted random structure search (RSS), element substitution, and ML-assisted screening provides compelling evidence that generative models will become an essential component of future materials design efforts.
#mattergen's step change in stability, uniqueness, and novelty of generated structures over prior work appears to derive principally from `Alex-MP-20`, a significantly larger training set, and two architectural improvements:
+ The joint diffusion for atom types, coordinates, and lattice (as proposed in DiffCSP @jiao_crystal_2024).
+ The introduction of adapter modules enabling fine-tuning for conditional generation across various properties.

Despite these advances, several challenges remain:

+ Diffusion models tend to generate low-symmetry $P 1$ structures, particularly for larger crystals, symptomatic of a distribution mismatch with respect to crystals found in nature.
  Given this issue appears to have been partially resolved from CDVAE to #mattergen, further optimization of the denoising process and/or training set augmentation may suffice to fully resolve it.

+ Pioneering research on generative models dealt with molecules, i.e. non-periodic systems with fewer symmetry constraints typically consisting of a much smaller set of elements.
  While #mattergen and its predecessors have since succeeded at generalizing to inorganic crystals, further work is needed to enable the generation of catalytic surfaces, metal-organic frameworks and other large complex systems.
  This would open up highly impactful chemical reactions such as nitrogen fixation and carbon capture to the inverse design paradigm.

+ Another area for future development is the incorporation of non-scalar property constraints, such as band structures or X-ray diffraction (XRD) spectra.
  The ability to generate materials based on vectorial or even higher-order constraints would enable generative band engineering and the prediction of atomic structures from experimentally measured XRD spectra of unknown samples.

+ As with any subfield of ML, progress is spurred and can only be quantified in the presence of well-designed performance metrics and benchmarks to help identify areas for improvement and assess the quality of generated materials.
  The current lack of benchmarks for crystal generation makes model comparison difficult.

+ Finally, the ultimate test for a generative model is successful experimental synthesis and characterization which has yet to be demonstrated and will require closer collaboration with experimentalists.
  Until this is achieved, skeptics can rightly point out that this shortcoming calls into question the practical utility of generative models for materials.

== Closing Remarks
<sec:outlook-closing-remarks>

From accelerating the stability prediction of hypothetical crystals, both thermodynamic and phononic, to guiding complex multi-step funnel-type discovery efforts, to enabling near-DFT-accuracy simulations across diverse chemistries, this thesis demonstrated how many areas of computational materials science are positively impacted by ML.

Looking ahead, improvements in high-quality open-source software, autonomous labs, declining computational costs, sophisticated error-correcting high-throughput DFT workflows @ganose_atomate2_2024 @kavanagh_doped_2024 @zhu_highthroughput_2024, and rapid improvements in deep learning architectures are paving the way for the systematic design of atomic systems.

Close collaboration between materials experts (computational and experimental), ML researchers and robotics engineers will be essential to fully leverage the potent combination of theory, ML and automated labs without sacrificing scientific rigor.
If successful, developing robotic experimentation for automated synthesis and characterization and integrating it with ML and theory guidance will dramatically accelerate and scale up materials research.

While industry efforts will likely drive rapid progress, the open-source community must step up to ensure that reproducibility and FAIRness (findable, accessible, interoperable, and reusable data) are maintained in ML model development.
An open community that freely shares new data and models will greatly improve the pace of progress and ensure we unlock their full potential.

