@fig:hist-wbm-hull-dist are the #mbd stability prediction targets.
Formation energies were filtered to ±#si4[5eV/atom], discarding 22 structures to the right of the visible range with questionable formation energies between +5 and +#si4[80eV/atom], as well as 502 suspicious structures left of the visible range with exactly -#si4[10eV/atom] formation energy.
@fig:wbm-energy-hists not only gives insight into the nature of the dataset but comparing @fig:hist-wbm-e-form-per-atom[Figs.] and @fig:hist-wbm-hull-dist[] reveals the increased difficulty of stability vs formation energy prediction arising from the much narrower distribution of convex hull distances.
Even the filtered formation energies have a range of #si4[10eV/atom] vs less than #si4[1eV/atom] for hull distances.
Accurate stability classification requires correctly ranking the subtle energy differences between chemically similar compounds in the same chemical system rather than comparing a single material with the reference energies of its constituent elements.
DFT has been shown to significantly benefit from systematic error cancellation between similar chemistries when trying to identify the lowest-lying polymorph @hautier_accuracy_2012.
This beneficial cancellation has yet to be conclusively demonstrated for ML stability predictions.
So far, only the lack thereof has been shown for a previous generation of models in @bartel_critical_2020 where they encountered a much more random error distribution among similar chemistries than simulations from first principles.

