== Proprietary Models on #mbd
<sec:mbd-proprietary-models>

We show the performance of proprietary models trained on incompatible training sets in @tab:metrics-table-uniq-protos-with-closed.
#gnome @merchant_scaling_2023 from Google DeepMind and PFP @takamoto_towards_2022 from Matlantis are the only two models in this category so far.
#gnome has been #link("https://github.com/janosh/matbench-discovery/pull/84")[officially submitted] while vetting the #link("https://matlantis.com/news/pfp-validation-for-public-v5-0-0")[PFP results], testing for data leakage and preparing a preprint detailing the evaluation process including how to correct for PFP's different elemental reference energies from having trained on diverse, incompatible DFT reference data is ongoing.
#gnome @merchant_scaling_2023 significantly outperforms all open models as well as PFP (based on preliminary results) across all regression and classification metrics.
Importantly, DeepMind reported nearly identical metrics on a subset of WBM excluding all compositional overlap with the #gnome training data, thus measuring the model's generalization to unseen compositions.
While not conclusive evidence, this suggests that data leakage is not the main driver of the model's performance. #gnome's impressive ability to benefit substantially from a much larger training set indicates that GNN expressiveness in general is far from exhausted.
Despite the incompatible training data used (rendering #gnome an unusual admission to a benchmark), we wanted to highlight this result as it signals to the community the viability of larger and more diverse training sets.
Perhaps unsurprising given continuous improvements in model accuracy with increasing data size even up to internet-scale datasets have been consistently observed in other ML domains such as vision and language, it nonetheless de-risks scaling efforts for other ML force field authors to know the same holds in inorganic chemistry.

